{{About|the 1955–1957 station wagon|the 1970–1995 van|Chevrolet Van}} [[File:1956 Chevrolet 210 Wagon.jpg|thumb|1956 Chevrolet Beauville]] The '''Chevrolet Beauville''' was originally a [[station wagon]] option for the 1954 [[Chevrolet Bel Air]]. The name was later resurrected as a full-size [[van]] option for the [[Chevrolet Van]] in 1970. Both were related to the lower trim level [[Chevrolet Townsman]].
==1954== In 1954 Chevrolet introduced the 4-door Beauville Wagon as an option for the Bel Air Line. It came standard with a [[Straight-6|6-cylinder]] engine and featured woodgrain trim around the side windows.
==1955== In 1955 the 4-door Beauville Wagon came standard with a [[Straight-6|6-cylinder]] engine or a [[V8 engine|V8]] mated to a [[manual transmission]].
{| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! Type of Beauville ! Number made ! Standard price |- | 1955 4-door Bel Air Beauville Wagon | 24,313 | [[Straight-6|6-cylinder]]= $2,262 [[V8 engine|V8]]= $2,361 |}
==1956== In 1956 the Beauville became a wagon option for the Chevrolet 210 as well. {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! Type of Beauville ! Number made ! Standard Price ! Seating capacity |- | 1956 4-door 210 Beauville Wagon
| 17,988 | 6-cylinder= $2,348 V8= $2447 | 9 passengers |- | 1956 4-door Bel Air Beauville Wagon (V8 and 6-cylinder Have different Chrome strips) | 13,279 | 6-cylinder= $2,482 V8= $2581 | 9 passengers |}
===Engines=== Chevrolet Station wagons offered a wide variety of engines rated from the {{Convert|140|bhp|kW|abbr=on}} 6-cylinder to the {{Convert|225|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} V8.
One base engine Chevrolet offered in 1956 was a {{convert|235.5|cuin|cc|sing=on}} 6-cylinder engine with a cast-iron block and a compression ratio of 8.0:1. It was carbureted, with a Rochester single barrel [[carburetor]] and produced {{convert|140|bhp|kW}} power at 4200 [[revolutions per minute]]. Another base engine offered by Chevrolet in 1956 was a {{convert|265|cuin|cc|sing=on}} [[V8 engine|V8]] with a 2-barrel carburetor with {{convert|162|bhp|kW}} at 4400 rpm.
In 1956 two other {{convert|265|cuin|cc|sing=on}} V8s were offered but both had a 9.25:1 [[compression ratio]], 4-barrel carburetors, and a dual exhaust. The [[Turbo-Fire 225]] engine was equipped with 2 Carter 4-barrel carburetors and produced {{convert|225|hp|abbr=on}} at 5200 rpm while the Turbo-Fire 205 engine had a single 4-barrel carburetor with a peak {{Convert|205|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4600 rpm.
==1957== In 1957 the Beauville station wagon was not offered in the Bel Air line, only in the 210. {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! Type of Beauville ! Number sold ! Standard Price ! Seating capacity |- | 1957 4-door 210 Beauville wagon | 21,803 | 6-cylinder= $2,563 V8= $2663 | 9 passengers |} <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carsandstripes.com/chevrolet-1957.asp |title=1957 Chevrolet |publisher=Carsandstripes.com |date=2007-05-02 |accessdate=2009-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328073534/http://www.carsandstripes.com/chevrolet-1957.asp |archive-date=2009-03-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1957 the engines offered by Chevrolet in the 210 Beauville were a 235.5-cubic-inch 6-cylinder with {{Convert|140|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}, a 265-cubic-inch V8 with {{Convert|162|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}, and a number of 283-cubic-inch V8s, the most powerful being the super turbo-fire 283 reached {{Convert|283|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. The super turbo-fire 283 was a fuel-injected engine that was a $550 option back in 1957.<ref>{{cite web|author=sea@OldRide.com |url=http://www.oldride.com/library/1957_chevrolet_bel_air.html |title=1957 CHEVROLET BEL AIR Information Specifications Resources Pictures |publisher=Oldride.com |date= |accessdate=2009-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theclassicchevrolet.com/1956_chevrolet_engines.htm |title=The Classic Chevrolet facts about 1956 Chevrolet Engines |publisher=Theclassicchevrolet.com |date= |accessdate=2009-05-07}}</ref>
