{{About|the full-size van|the concept car|Chevrolet Express (concept car)}}
{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chevrolet Express/GMC Savana
| image = 2005 Chevrolet Express -- NHTSA.jpg
| manufacturer = [[General Motors]]
| assembly = [[Wentzville Assembly]], [[Wentzville, Missouri]], U.S.
| production = 1995–present<br>1995–2014 (1500 series only)
| predecessor = [[Chevrolet Van|Chevrolet Van/Beauville<br />GMC Vandura/Rally]]
| class = [[Full-size van]]
| body_style = [[Van]]
| successor  =  [[Chevrolet City Express]] (1500 Series only)
}}
The '''Chevrolet Express''' and its mechanically identical twin '''GMC Savana''' are [[full-size van]]s from [[General Motors]]. They replaced the [[Chevrolet Van]] and [[GMC Vandura]] in 1995. The Express and Savana, known as the GMT600 platform, was a refreshed change from the previous generation van.  The GMT600 featured full body on frame construction, the new central-port injection V6 and V8 engines, and greatly improved ride and handling from its GMT400-derived chassis.  

After 2003, the Express and Savana had updated front-end sheet metal similar to the [[GMT800]] light trucks and [[GMT360]] SUVs, and were fitted with the LS (Gen III) engines. The remainder of the body was not modified. This redesign was designated as the GMT610. In 2004, Stability Control ([[StabiliTrak]]) was added to all passenger vans. In 2008, the interior was updated and side impact roof airbags were standard on all passenger models. They also offer the [[E85]] [[Flexible-fuel vehicle|Flexfuel]] Vortec 5.3L V8 engine in both the 2008 Express 1500 Work Van and Passenger Van. The 6.6L [[Duramax V8 engine]] Diesel was added as an option for 2006.

In 2017, a new 2.8L Duramax Diesel engine was added.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chevrolet.com/express/cargo-van|title=2018 Express Cargo Van: Work Van|website=www.chevrolet.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>
In 2018, a new 6.0L V8 gaseous CNG/LPG capable engine was added. In 2018, conventional sealed beam headlights were discontinued for the base models, and the composite headlights found on higher trims became standard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gmc.com/vans/savana-passenger-van|title=2018 Savana Passenger Van|website=www.gmc.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>
For 2021, a 6.6L V8 engine introduced in the 2020 [[Chevrolet Silverado|Silverado/Sierra HD]] was added, replacing both 6.0L V8 engines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gmauthority.com/blog/2020/03/2021-chevrolet-express-receives-new-6-6l-v8-gas-engine/|title=2021 Chevrolet Express Receives New 6.6L V8 Gas Engine|publisher=GM Authority|date=2020-03-03}}</ref>

