== First generation (J309; 2011–2018) == {{Infobox automobile | name = First generation (J309) | image = 2012 Chevrolet Orlando LTZ VCDi Automatic 2.0 Front.jpg | production = 2011–2018 | assembly = {{unbulleted list | South Korea: [[Gunsan]] ([[GM Korea]], until 2018)<ref name="korea2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2018/02/gm-closes-korean-plant-amid-overseas-troubles-chevrolet-orlando-dies/|title=GM Closes Korean Plant Amid Overseas Troubles; Chevrolet Orlando Dies With It|date=13 February 2018}}</ref> | Vietnam: [[Hanoi]] ([[GM Vietnam]]) | Russia: [[Kaliningrad]] ([[Avtotor]], until 2015) | Venezuela: [[Valencia,_Carabobo|Valencia]] (GM Venezolana, until 2015) | Uzbekistan: [[Pitnak]] ([[GM Uzbekistan]], until 2018)<ref name="uz2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/region/125890.html|title=GM Uzbekistan stops assembling Chevrolet Orlando|date=22 January 2018|website=AzerNews.az}}</ref> }} | platform = [[GM Delta platform]] | engine = {{unbulleted list | 1.4 L ''[[GM Family 0 engine|Ecotec]]'' [[I4 engine|I4]]-[[Turbocharger|T]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]]) | 1.8 L ''[[GM Family 1 engine#Generation III|Ecotec]]'' I4 (petrol) | 2.4 L ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LAF|Ecotec]]'' I4 (petrol) | 1.6 L ''[[GM Medium Diesel engine|CDTI Ecotec]]'' I4-T ([[Diesel engine|diesel]]) | 2.0 L ''[[GM Family Z engine#Chevrolet Orlando|VCDi]] Family Z'' I4-T (diesel) }} | powerout = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|103|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} (1.4 L, petrol) | {{convert|100|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} (1.6 L, diesel) | {{convert|104|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} (1.8 L, petrol) | {{convert|96|–|120|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} (2.0 L, diesel) | {{convert|130|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} (2.4 L, petrol) }} | transmission = {{unbulleted list | 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 6-speed manual | 6-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] }} | wheelbase = {{convert|2760|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heise.de/autos/artikel/Chevrolet-Orlando-Freund-der-Familie-1149499.html |title=Chevrolet Orlando: Freund der Familie |work=Heise |date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> | length = {{convert|4652|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} | width = {{convert|1836|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} | height = {{convert|1633|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} | weight = {{convert|1655|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} }}
=== Concept === The Orlando concept was a 5-door, 7-seat vehicle based on Chevrolet Cruze sedan. It included a two-tier grille, headlamps that flow into the front fenders and muscular fender forms that wrap around the wheels, 2.0-litre 4-cylinder turbo-diesel engine rated {{convert|150|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|320|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}. It was unveiled at the [[2008 Paris Motor Show]] and later at the [[North American International Auto Show#2009|2009 North American International Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Phillips |first=Drew |date=11 January 2009 |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/01/11/detroit-2009-chevy-orlando-concept-comes-stateside-production/ |title=Detroit 2009: Chevy Orlando Concept comes stateside, production version due in 2011 [w/VIDEO] |publisher=Autoblog |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>
In 2010, GM showed the [[GMC Granite]] small MPV concept, which is similar to the Orlando.<ref>{{cite web |last=Filipponio |first=Frank |date=19 December 2009 |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/12/19/report-gm-to-show-chevy-orlando-based-gmc-granite-and-hi-po-bui/ |title=Report: GM to show Chevy Orlando-based GMC Granite and hi-po Buick Regal in Detroit |publisher=Autoblog |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>
=== History === [[File:2012 Chevrolet Orlando LTZ VCDi Automatic 2.0 Rear.jpg|thumb|left|Chevrolet Orlando (United Kingdom)]]
In August 2009, at its extended product review, GM previewed the production-spec Orlando and confirmed its production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leftlanenews.com/on-the-scene-some-details-from-gms-product-preview.html |title=On the scene: Some details from GM's product preview |work=Left Lane News |first=Mark |last=Elias |accessdate=15 August 2010}}</ref>
The production model was unveiled at the 2010 Busan International Motor Show,<ref>{{cite web |last=Bowman |first=Zach |date=30 April 2010 |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/04/30/buick-lacrosse-rebranded-as-daewoo-alpheon-in-south-korea/ |title=Buick LaCrosse rebranded as Daewoo Alpheon in South Korea |publisher=Autoblog |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> followed by the [[2010 Paris Motor Show]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Ewing |first=Steven J. |date=25 August 2010 |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/08/25/chevrolet-orlando-production-version-unveiled-ahead-of-paris/ |title=Chevrolet Orlando production version unveiled ahead of Paris |publisher=Autoblog |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> and the [[North American International Auto Show#2013|2013 North American International Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ross |first=Jeffrey N. |date=10 January 2013 |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/01/10/chevy-filling-its-naias-stand-with-5-models-not-sold-in-us/ |title=Chevy filling its NAIAS stand with 5 models not sold in US |publisher=Autoblog |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> Production began at the Gunsan Assembly Plant in South Korea.
GM initially intended that the Orlando would go into production in the United States,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/cars-trucks/daily-news/090114-2011-Chevy-Orlando-Small-SUV-Big-on-Space/ |title=2011 Chevy Orlando: Small SUV, Big on Space |work=U.S. News & World Report |date=14 January 2009 |accessdate=15 August 2010}}</ref> however, in May 2010, GM reversed their decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nitrobahn.com/news/no-chevrolet-orlando-for-u-s-says-general-motors/ |title=No Chevrolet Orlando for U.S., says General Motors |work=Nitrobahn |date=1 May 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505021633/http://www.nitrobahn.com/news/no-chevrolet-orlando-for-u-s-says-general-motors/ |archive-date=5 May 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Chevrolet Orlando sold in Canada starting in 2011 for the 2012 model year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chevrolet brings fun and functional European MPV to Canada with all-new Orlando |url=http://media.gm.ca/media/ca/en/chevrolet/vehicles/orlando/2012.html |accessdate=29 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120713150704/http://media.gm.ca/media/ca/en/chevrolet/vehicles/orlando/2012.html |archivedate=13 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
The European model was available from 2011 until 2014 when most of Chevrolet's vehicles, except muscle and sports cars were permanently withdrawn from the European market, except Russia and [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]] member nations. Later in 2015, the Chevrolet Orlando was discontinued the Russian market.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wroom.ru/en/cars/chevrolet/orlando |title=Chevrolet Orlando |language=ru |website=Wroom.ru |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> The Orlando was discontinued for the 2015 model year in Canada.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cain |first=Timothy |date=4 March 2015 |url=http://www.goodcarbadcar.net/2015/03/chevrolet-orlando-discontinued-in-canada.html |title=Chevrolet Orlando Discontinued In Canada - No 2015 Model Year Orlando |website=GoodCarBadCar.net |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>
The diesel engine for the Korean market was updated in 2015 to meet the government's Euro 6 requirement. All diesel Chevrolet Orlandos sold in Korea were equipped with a 1.6-litre inline-four CDTi engine outsourced from [[Opel]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kim |first=Marie |date=2 December 2015 |url=http://www.businesskorea.co.kr/english/news/industry/13166-enthusiastic-response-gm-korea-sells-51052-units-november |title=Enthusiastic Response: GM Korea Sells 51,052 Units in November |work=BusinessKorea |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>
Worldwide production of the first generation Orlando ended in 2018, following its discontinuation by GM Uzbekistan and the closure of the plant in South Korea which produced it.<ref name="uz2018" /><ref name="korea2018" />
=== Engines === {|class = wikitable |- !Engine code!!Type!! Power@rpm !! Torque@rpm !! Transmission |- !colspan=5|Petrol engines |- |LUJ |{{convert|1364|cc|L|1|abbr=on|disp=flip}} ''[[GM Family 0 engine|Ecotec]]'' [[inline-four engine|I4]] ([[turbocharger|t/c]]) |{{convert|103|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} |{{convert|200|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} | * 6-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] |- |2H0 |{{convert|1796|cc|L|1|abbr=on|disp=flip}} ''[[GM Family 1 engine#DCVCP|Ecotec]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] |{{convert|104|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}}@6200 |{{convert|176|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}@3800 | * 5-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] * 6-speed ''[[GM 6T40 transmission|GM 6T45]]'' [[automatic transmission|automatic]] |- |LAF |{{convert|2384|cc|L|1|abbr=on|disp=flip}} [[Fuel injection#Direct injection|DI]] [[GM Ecotec engine#LAF|''Ecotec'' LAF]] [[Straight-4|I4]] |{{convert|130|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}}@6700 |{{convert|171|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}@4900 | * 6-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] * 6-speed ''[[GM 6T40 transmission|Hydra-Matic 6T40]]'' [[automatic transmission|automatic]] |- !colspan=5|[[Liquefied petroleum gas]] engines |- |LBN |{{convert|1998|cc|L|1|abbr=on|disp=flip}} [[Straight-4|I4]] |{{convert|103|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}}@6000 |{{convert|18.8|kgm|Nm lbft|0|abbr=on}}@4600 | * 6-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]] |- !colspan=5|[[turbodiesel|Diesel]] engines |- |? |{{convert|1998|cc|L|1|abbr=on|disp=flip}} [[GM Family Z engine|''VCDi'' Family Z]] [[Straight-4|I4]] turbo |{{convert|96|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}}@3800 |{{convert|315|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}@2000 | * 6-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] |- |Z20D1 |{{convert|1998|cc|L|1|abbr=on|disp=flip}} [[GM Family Z engine|''VCDi'' Family Z]] [[Straight-4|I4]] turbo |{{convert|120|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}}@3800 |{{convert|360|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}@1750–2750 | * 6-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] * 6-speed ''[[GM 6T40 transmission|GM 6T45]]'' [[automatic transmission|automatic]] |} Canadian models included 2.4-litre direct injection petrol [[Inline-four engine|four-cylinder engine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.gm.com/media/ca/en/chevrolet/vehicles/orlando/2012.tab1.html |title=2012 Chevrolet Orlando |publisher=[[General Motors]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115054453/http://media.gm.com/media/ca/en/chevrolet/vehicles/orlando/2012.tab1.html |archive-date=15 January 2012}}</ref> European models include 1.8-litre petrol, 2.0-litre diesel engines. South Korean models include 2.0-litre LPG and 2.0-litre (163PS) [[diesel engine]]s before update to 1.6-litre [[Opel]] diesel in 2015.
=== Safety === {{Euro NCAP |year=2011 |overall_stars=5 |description=Chevrolet Orlando |reference={{cite web |title=Official Chevrolet Orlando 2011 safety rating results |url=https://www.euroncap.com/en/results/chevrolet/orlando/10962 |website=Euro NCAP}} |adult_points=34 |adult_percent=95 |child_points=39 |child_percent=79 |pedestrian_points=18 |pedestrian_percent=49 |safety_points=5 |safety_percent=71 }}
=== Marketing === As part of the Chevrolet Orlando launch in the UK, a life-sized [[Play-Doh]] clay model replica was unveiled in London.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bowman |first=Zach |date=10 March 2011 |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2011/03/10/life-size-play-doh-chevrolet-orlando-appears-on-london-streets/ |title=Life-size Play-Doh Chevrolet Orlando appears on London streets |publisher=Autoblog |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/gb/en/chevrolet/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/gb/en/2011/CHEVROLET/03_09_orlan_doh |title=Toy racer: life-size Play-Doh car sticks to road |publisher=[[General Motors]] |date=9 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202094510/http://media.gm.com/content/media/gb/en/chevrolet/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/gb/en/2011/CHEVROLET/03_09_orlan_doh |archive-date=2 December 2011}}</ref>
