== Second generation (2018–present) == {{Infobox automobile | name = Second generation | image = Chevrolet Orlando CN Red Line 01 China 2019-04-04.jpg | production = 2018–present | assembly = China: [[Shanghai]] ([[Shanghai GM]]) | platform = [[GM Delta platform|D2XX platform]] | related = [[Buick Envision]] [[Buick GL6]] | engine = 1.35 L ''[[GM Family 0 engine|L3T Ecotec]]'' [[I3 engine|I3]]-[[Turbocharger|T]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]]) | powerout = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|116|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} }} | transmission = {{unbulleted list | 6-speed manual | 6-speed automatic }} | wheelbase = {{convert|2796|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paultan.org/2018/07/19/chevrolet-orlando-reborn-as-a-crossover-in-china/|title=Chevrolet Orlando reborn as a crossover in China|date=19 July 2018}}</ref> | length = {{convert|4684|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} | width = {{convert|1807|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} | height = {{convert|1628|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} | weight = | predecessor = [[Chevrolet Lova RV]] }}
The second generation Orlando is made in China by [[Shanghai-GM]]. Available in 5- and 7-seater versions, the second generation Orlando was designed to be in a body style similar to a crossover. Power comes from a 1.35&nbsp;L (1,349 cc) turbocharged [[Inline-three engine|three-cylinder]] engine producing {{convert|156|hp|kW PS|abbr=on|0}} at 5,500 rpm and {{Convert|170|lb.ft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} between 1,800–4,400 rpm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.auto-data.net/en/chevrolet-orlando-ii-530t-ecotec-163hp-dss-34950|title=Chevrolet Orlando II 530T Ecotec (163 Hp) DSS {{!}} Technical specs, data, fuel consumption, Dimensions|website=www.auto-data.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> Optional Red Line Package makes engine output to {{Convert|161|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carnewschina.com/2018/07/18/new-chevrolet-orlando-not-an-mpv-no-more/|title=The New Chevrolet Orlando Is Not An MPV No More|first=Tycho de|last=Feijter|date=18 July 2018|website=CarNewsChina.com}}</ref>
