The '''Chevrolet Volt''' is a [[plug-in hybrid]] car manufactured by [[General Motors]], also marketed in [[rebadging|rebadged]] variants as the '''Holden Volt''' in Australia and New Zealand, '''Buick Velite 5''' in China, and with a different [[fascia (car)|fascia]] as the '''Vauxhall Ampera''' in the United Kingdom and as the '''Opel Ampera''' in the remainder of Europe. Volt production ended in February 2019.<ref name="End2019"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chevy-volt-discontinued-chevrolets-last-volt-rolls-off-the-assembly-line/|title=Chevy Volt discontinued: Chevrolet's last Volt rolls off the assembly line|work=CBS News |date=2019-02-22|accessdate=2019-03-02}}</ref>

Sales of the 2011 Volt began in the United States in mid-December 2010, followed by various European countries and other international markets in 2011. Global combined Volt/Ampera-family sales totaled about 177,000 units by the end of October 2018.<ref name=Top5Global102018/> The U.S. is the leading market, with 152,144 Volts delivered through the end of 2018, followed by Canada with 16,653 Volts sold through September 2018. Just over 10,000 Opel/Vauxhall Ampera cars had been sold in Europe {{as of|2016|06|lc=y}}, with the Netherlands leading the European region. {{Asof|2018|09}}, the Volt/Ampera family of vehicles is the world's all-time best-selling plug-in hybrid vehicle, and the Volt is also the U.S. all-time top-selling [[plug-in electric car]].

The Volt operates as a pure [[battery electric vehicle]] until its battery capacity drops to a predetermined threshold from full charge. From there, its [[internal combustion engine]] powers an electric [[Electric generator|generator]] to extend the vehicle's range as needed. When the engine is running it may be periodically mechanically linked (by a clutch) to a [[planetary gear]] set, and hence the output drive axle, to improve energy efficiency. The Volt's [[regenerative braking]] also contributes to the on-board electricity generation. Under the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) cycle, the 2013/15 [[model year]] Volt [[all-electric range]] is {{convert|38|mi|abbr=on}}, with a combined electric mode/gasoline-only rating of {{Convert|62|mpgus|abbr=on}} [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent|equivalent]] (MPG-equivalent).

The [[Chevrolet Volt (second generation)|second-generation Volt]]'s improved battery system and drivetrain increased the all-electric range to {{Convert|53|mi}}, its EPA-rated fuel economy in [[charge-sustaining]] mode to {{Convert|42|mpgUS|abbr=on}}, and the combined city/highway fuel economy in [[all-electric mode]] to 106 MPG-e, up from 98 MPG-e. Deliveries to retail customers in the U.S. and Canada began in October 2015 as a 2016 [[model year]].

The Volt has won several awards, including the 2009 [[Green Car Vision Award]], 2011 [[Green Car of the Year]], 2011 [[North American Car of the Year]], 2011 [[World Car of the Year|World Green Car]], 2012 [[European Car of the Year]], and 2016 Green Car of the Year.

== Terminology ==
{{Further|Hybrid vehicle drivetrain}}
[[File:Hybridserie.png|thumb|Basic powertrain configuration of a [[series hybrid]] vehicle, one of the two possible modes of the Chevrolet Volt when operated as range-extender vehicle]]

The [[Society of Automotive Engineers]]' (SAE) definition of a hybrid vehicle states that the vehicle shall have "''two or more energy storage systems both of which must provide propulsion power, either together or independently.''"<ref>{{cite web
 | url = http://media.gm.com/content/dam/Media/microsites/product/volt/docs/paper.pdf| title = SAE paper 2008-01-0458: The Electrification of the Automobile: From Conventional Hybrid, to Plug-in Hybrids, to Extended-Range Electric Vehicles | publisher = [[Society of Automotive Engineers]] (SAE)
 | year=2008| accessdate = 2011-05-14}}</ref> General Motors has avoided the use of the term "hybrid" when describing its [[Voltec]] designs, even after the carmaker revealed that in some cases the combustion engine provided some assist at high speeds or to improve performance. This contribution from the gas engine is only at high speeds. Normal driving there is no contribution and the car runs all electric.<ref name=NYT101110>{{cite news |last=Stenquist |first=Paul| date=2010-10-11 |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/11/g-m-officially-introduces-2011-chevrolet-volt-amid-controversy/ |title=G.M. ‘Officially’ Introduces 2011 Chevrolet Volt Amid Controversy |work=The New York Times |at=Wheels |accessdate=2010-10-11}}</ref> Instead General Motors describes the Volt as an [[electric vehicle]] equipped with a "range extending" gasoline-powered [[internal combustion engine|internal combustion engine (ICE)]] as a [[Engine-generator|genset]] and therefore dubbed the Volt an "Extended Range Electric Vehicle" or E-REV.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chang |first=Richard S. |date=2009-06-25 |title=Chevrolet Volt Hits Road, Ahead of Schedule |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/06/25/chevrolet-volt-hits-road-ahead-of-schedule/ |work=The New York Times |at=Wheels |accessdate= 2011-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/auto/index.ssf/2010/10/is_the_chevrolet_volt_a_true_e.html |title=Is the Chevrolet Volt a True Electric Car? General Motors Defends EV Label |work=MLive.com |last=Oosting |first=Jonathan |date=2010-10-12 |accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref> In a January 2011 interview, the Chevy Volt's Global Chief Engineer, Pamela Fletcher, referred to the Volt as "an electric car with extended range."<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kuchment |first=Anna |date=January 2011 |title=Practically Green: A Q&A with the Chevy Volt's Chief Engineer |journal=Scientific American |url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=practically-green |accessdate=2011-03-27 |publisher=Nature America |volume=304 |issue=1 |page=25 |issn=0036-8733 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0111-25a}}</ref>

According to the [[Society of Automotive Engineers]] (SAE) definitions, the Volt is a [[plug-in hybrid]] vehicle, due to the combination of an internal combustion engine and two electric motors, along with a battery that can accept off-board energy.<ref name=NYTVolt/> The Volt operates as a purely [[electric vehicle]] for the first {{convert|25|to|50|mi|km}} in charge-depleting mode. When the battery capacity drops below a pre-established threshold from full charge, the vehicle enters charge-sustaining mode, and the Volt's control system selects the most efficient drive mode to improve performance and boost high-speed efficiency.<ref name=NYTVolt/><ref name=MT101101>{{cite journal |last=Markus |first= Frank |date = 2010-10-10 |title=Unbolting the Chevy Volt to See How It Ticks |url=http://www.motortrend.com/features/editorial/1010_unbolting_the_chevy_volt_to_see_how_it_ticks/index.html |journal=[[Motor Trend]] |accessdate=2010-10-11}}</ref>

== History ==
=== Concept vehicle ===
The Chevrolet Volt [[concept car]] debuted at the January 2007 [[North American International Auto Show]], becoming the first-ever [[series hybrid|series]] [[plug-in hybrid]] [[concept car]] shown by a major car manufacturer.<ref name=IEEE2007/><ref name=GCC010607>{{cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2007/01/gm_introduces_e.html?cid=27360790 |title=GM Introduces E-Flex Electric Vehicle System; Chevrolet Volt the First Application |work=[[Green Car Congress]] |publisher=BioAge Group |date=2007-01-06 |accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref> The Volt concept vehicle had four doors with a rear [[liftgate]] and seating for four passengers. This was a significant change in design when compared to the [[General Motors EV1]] of the 1990s, which only seated two to reduce weight and to make the necessary room for the [[lead-acid battery]] pack. The top speed was also increased on the Volt, from the electronically limited {{convert|80|mph|km/h|-1}} to {{convert|100|mph|km/h|-1}}. The battery pack size was reduced, from about {{convert|300|L|cuft|abbr=on|1|order=flip}} in volume in the EV1, to {{convert|100|L|cuft|abbr=on|1|order=flip}} in the Volt.<ref name=IEEE2007>{{cite web |url=http://www.spectrum.ieee.org/green-tech/advanced-cars/lithium-batteries-for-hybrid-cars |title=Lithium Batteries for Hybrid Cars |last=Voelcker |first=John |work=IEEE Spectrum |date=January 2007 |accessdate=2011-05-14 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521102837/http://spectrum.ieee.org/green-tech/advanced-cars/lithium-batteries-for-hybrid-cars |archivedate=2011-05-21 |df= }}</ref>{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|p=43}}

General Motors' then-Vice-Chairman for global product development [[Bob Lutz (businessman)|Robert Lutz]] was looking for a "Prius fighter", a leapfrog product like Apple's [[iPod]].<ref name="AdageStoryBehind">{{cite news |last1=Guilford |first1=Dave |title=The Story Behind Chevy Volt's $40,000 Price Sticker |url=https://adage.com/article/news/gm-s-bob-lutz-chevy-volt-wound-40k-price-tag/138244 |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=adage.com |date=3 August 2009 |language=en}}</ref> The two-seater [[sports car]] being developed by [[Tesla Motors|Tesla]], the [[Tesla Roadster (2008)]], and the rapid advancement of [[lithium-ion]] battery technology inspired him to push the carmaker to develop the Volt after the 2006 Detroit Auto Show,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/81580 |title=Bob Lutz: The Man Who Revived the Electric Car |work=Newsweek.com |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=91–16<!-- is this to page 116? --> }}{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=4,5}} overcoming internal opposition that recalled losing a billion dollar in the 1990s over the [[General Motors EV1|EV1]] electric vehicle program.<ref name="AdageStoryBehind"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Friend |first=Tad |url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2009/08/24/090824fa_fact_friend |title=Elon Musk and electric cars |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=2009-01-07 |accessdate=2009-09-14 |quote= All the geniuses here at General Motors kept saying lithium-ion technology is 10 years away, and Toyota agreed with us—and boom, along comes Tesla. So I said, 'How come some tiny little California startup, run by guys who know nothing about the car business, can do this, and we can't?' That was the crowbar that helped break up the log jam.}}</ref> Lutz's initial idea was to develop an [[all-electric car]], but Jon Lauckner, General Motors Vice President for global program management, quickly sketched out the powertrain layout, estimated the vehicle weight and  battery requirements, convinced Lutz that to avoid an expensive battery, [[range anxiety]] concerns, and lack of public [[charging station|charging infrastructure]], they could use a smaller battery pack with a small combustion engine driving a generator acting as a backup to extend the range, but without a mechanical connection between the gasoline engine and the drive wheels, so it would be a pure electrically driven vehicle without many of the limitations General Motors learned from the EV1 experience.{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=91-16}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lauckner |first1=Jon |title=A Car Guy's Electric Moment |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/a-car-guys-electric-moment/ |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=www.cbsnews.com |date=17 August 2010}}</ref>
{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=Chevy Volt Concept NAIAS 2007 02.jpg|image2=Chevy Volt Concept NAIAS 2007 01.jpg|width=220|caption1=|caption2=The Chevrolet Volt [[concept car]] was unveiled at the January 2007 [[North American International Auto Show]]}}

Most of the Volt initial design parameters defined for the development of the concept car, then referred as the "iCar" in homage to the [[iPod]], were kept throughout the process up to the final production version. A key design parameter was a target of {{convert|40|mi|km}} for the [[all-electric range]], selected to keep the battery size small and lower costs, and mainly because research showed that in the U.S. 78 percent of daily [[commuting|commuters]] travel 40 miles or less. This target range lets drivers make most travel electrically driven, with the assumption that charging takes place at home overnight. This requirement translated to using a [[lithium-ion battery]] pack with an energy storage capacity of 16 {{kWh|link=yes}} considering that the battery would be used until the [[state of charge]] (SOC) of the battery reached 30%. This limit to the SOC was necessary in order to maintain operational performance under a wide range of environments, and to minimize the [[Battery (electricity)#Lifespan of rechargeable batteries|battery degradation]] to allow at least a ten-year life span. The initial target range for the gasoline engine/generator was set between {{Convert|250|to|300|mi}} and the vehicle had to be family size for four or five passengers.{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=91-16}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/16503845|title=GM to unveil Volt electric concept car|agency=Associated Press|work=NBC News |date=2007-01-07|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref>

Another key design decision was to develop the concept car based on a new family of common [[powertrain]] components for electric propulsion, which initially was called the E-Flex Systems, “E” stands for electric drive and “Flex” for the different sources of electricity, but later was renamed [[Voltec]] drive system. The E-Flex or Voltec powertrain is an attempt to standardize many components of possible future electrically propelled vehicles, and to allow multiple interchangeable electricity-generating systems. The E-Flex powertrain has the potential to adapt the vehicles to pure [[battery electric vehicle|battery electric]], to [[fuel cell vehicle|fuel cell-powered]] or to several other sources of energy to create electricity on board, such as [[engine-generator]] sets (genset) fueled by [[gasoline]], [[Diesel fuel|diesel]], [[biodiesel]], [[ethanol fuel]] ([[Neat ethanol fuel|E100]]), or [[flex-fuel]] ([[E85]]). [[Regenerative braking]] would also contribute to the on-board electricity generation.<ref name=GCC010607/>{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=29–33}}<ref name=ABG010707/> In October 2006 the E-flex powertrain was selected for the new propulsion architecture and the name Volt was chosen by General Motors.{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=29–33}}

The Volt concept car became the first application of the E-Flex (Voltec) drive system with a combination of an [[electric motor]], the same used in the [[Chevrolet Equinox Fuel Cell]], a {{convert|16|kW.h|MJ|abbr=on|lk=on}} [[lithium-ion]] battery pack with 136 [[kW]] of peak power, and a genset consisting of a small 1.0 L, 3-cylinder [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] [[flex-fuel]] capable engine linked to a {{convert|53|kW|hp|abbr=on|lk=on}} generator. General Motors called this genset an electric vehicle (EV) range extender. The vehicle was propelled by an electric motor with a peak output of {{convert|120|kW|hp|abbr=on}} delivering 236&nbsp;lb ft (320 Nm) of motoring [[torque]]. {{fact span|The concept car featured several advanced materials from GE Automotive Plastics that helped GM reduce the vehicle weight by up to 50 percent.|date=November 2019}}

The Volt concept featured a {{Convert|12|USgal|L impgal|abbr=on}} fuel capacity providing the vehicle a total driving range of around {{Convert|640|mi|abbr=on}}, which considered a gasoline fuel efficiency of about {{Convert|50|mpgus|abbr=on}} and a {{convert|40|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[all-electric range]]. According to General Motors estimates, a daily drive of {{Convert|60|mi|km|abbr=on}}, combined with an overnight recharge to support the first 40 all-electric miles, would yield an effective gasoline fuel economy of {{Convert|150|mpgus|abbr=on}}.<ref name=GCC010607/><ref name=ABG010707>{{cite web |url=http://www.autobloggreen.com/2007/01/07/detroit-auto-show-general-motors-e-flex-platform/ |title=A Look at the GM E-Flex Platform| last=Abuelsamid |first=Sam|work=Autoblog Green |date=2007-01-07|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> General Motors also emphasized that the Volt would further reduce dependence on imported oil if E85 ethanol was used instead of gasoline to power the on-board generator engine. Robert Lutz added that if the driver used E85, "''the fuel economy figure became 525 miles per'' (equivalent) ''petroleum gallon''", as only 15% of gasoline is used in this blend.{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=35}}{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=73, 74}} General Motors also noted that actual production of the Volt depended on further battery development, because the required rechargeable batteries needed to make the Volt a viable vehicle did not exist in the market and had yet to be developed.<ref name=GCC010607/>{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=91-16}}{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=73, 74}} The concept car was actually powered by two 12-volt [[Lead–acid battery|conventional car batteries]], just enough power to allow the vehicle to move at low speeds in the stand.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lutz|first=Bob|title=Car Guys vs. Bean Counters: The Battle for the Soul of American Business|year=2011|publisher=Portfolio Hardcover, [[Penguin Group]]|isbn=978-1-59184-400-6|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781591844006}} Location 2234 [[Amazon Kindle|Kindle]] edition.</ref>

Lutz initially said the Volt was expected to sell around $30,000, based on the cost of a conventional car of that size with a conventional four-cylinder engine plus US$8,000 for the lithium battery.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Squatriglia |first1=Chuck |title=Bob Lutz Drives the Volt, Calls It 'Electrifying' |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/06/bob-lutz-drives/ |website=Wired |accessdate=5 November 2019 |date=6 June 2008}}</ref><ref name="Voltcost"/> Developers faced cost escalation as they found out the Volt could not share components from GM's compact car platform like power steering, power brake, air-conditioning compressor that were driven by a belt running off the engine, in addition to the cost of a compact {{convert|110|kW|hp|abbr=on|lk=on}} electric motor and specialized microprocessors to control energy flow to the motor, GM eventually decided to price the Volt at a base price from around US$40,000.<ref name="Voltcost">{{cite news |title=How Volt's cost rose and rose and rose . . . |url=https://europe.autonews.com/article/20090802/COPY02/308029996/how-volt-s-cost-rose-and-rose-and-rose |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=Automotive News Europe |date=2 August 2009 |language=en}}</ref> The US$1 billion cost to develop the Volt is equivalent to creating three vehicles on an existing platform.<ref name="Voltcost"/>

== First generation (2010–2015) ==
=== Production model ===
[[File:2008 Chevrolet Volt hatchback (concept) 01.jpg|thumb|right|First production version of the Chevrolet Volt at the 2008 [[Australian International Motor Show]]]]

The production design model officially unveiled on September 16, 2008, as part of General Motors centennial celebration at the [[Renaissance Center|Wintergarden]] headquarters in Detroit.<ref name=GMPressRelease>{{cite web|url=http://www.prefix.com/Downloads/Volt.pdf|title=Chevrolet Volt Leads General Motors Into Its Second Century|date=2008-09-16|accessdate=2009-12-21|publisher=General Motors Company|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324034213/http://www.prefix.com/Downloads/Volt.pdf|archivedate=2012-03-24|df=}}</ref> The production model differed greatly in design from the original concept car. The carmaker cited necessary [[aerodynamic]] changes needed to reduce the concept car's high [[drag coefficient]] of {{Cd|0.43}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/21/automobiles/21AERO.html?pagewanted=1 |title=Edgy, Yet Still Aerodynamic |last=Patton |first=Phil |work=The New York Times |date=2008-12-19 |accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> down to a more efficient {{Cd|0.28}},<ref>{{cite web|last=Sherman|first=Don|title=2011 Chevrolet Cruze Eco|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/comparisons/2011-chevrolet-cruze-eco-page-3|work=Car and Driver|accessdate=2012-02-21|date=September 2011}}</ref> though still somewhat higher than the [[Toyota Prius]] {{Cd|0.25}}. Another reason was the use of General Motors' new global compact vehicle platform [[Delta II platform|Delta II]] to keep costs reasonable, and shared with the 2010 model year [[Chevrolet Cruze]].{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|p=71}} Another significant difference from the concept car is the seating, as the production Volt seats four rather than five passengers. This change was due to the higher-than-usual central tunnel that runs from the front console to the rear seat that houses the car's T-shaped battery pack.<ref>{{cite news |last=Motavalli |first=Jim |date=2008-09-21 |title=G.M. Tones Down the Volt |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0DEED9113DF932A1575AC0A96E9C8B63 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref>

After the concept was put into the pipeline for production, General Motors began looking for a partner to develop the Volt's [[lithium-ion battery]] pack. The carmaker evaluated about twenty-five different [[battery cell]] chemistries and constructions from around two dozen lithium-ion battery makers around the world.{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=48–57}} Due to their more promising cell technologies, two companies were selected in June 2007, [[Compact Power]] (CPI), which uses a lithium manganese oxide (LiMn<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>) cell made by its parent company, [[LG Chemical]]; and [[Continental Automotive Systems]], which uses [[Lithium iron phosphate battery|lithium iron phosphate]] based [[Commodity cell|cylindrical cells]] made by [[A123Systems]].{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=48–57}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2007/06/05/breaking-gm-awards-two-battery-development-contracts-for-chevy/|date=2007-06-05|title=GM awards two battery development contracts for Chevy Volt|work=AutoblogGreen |last=Abuelsamid |first=Sam}}</ref>{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=84–89}} By the end of October 2007 CPI (LG Chem) delivered their finished battery pack [[prototype]]s, and A123 delivered theirs by January 2008. General Motors testing process was conducted at the laboratory the carmaker had created for the [[GM EV1]] program. The battery packs included monitoring systems designed to keep the batteries cool and operating at optimum capacity despite a wide range of ambient temperatures.{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=48–57}}{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=84–89}} To ensure the battery pack would last ten years and {{Convert|150,000|mi}} expected for the battery warranty, the Volt team decided to use only half of the 16 {{kWh|link=yes}} capacity to reduce the rate of capacity degradation, limiting the [[state of charge]] (SOC) up to 80% of capacity and never depleting the battery below 30%.{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=84–89}}<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.engr.colostate.edu/~thb/Publications/POWER14185_nocover.pdf|title=Investigation of battery end-of-life conditions for plug-in hybrid electric vehicles|last1=Wood|first1=Eric|last2=Alexander|first2=Marcus|last3=Bradley|first3=Thomas H.|journal=Journal of Power Sources|pages=5147–5154|year=2011|volume=196|accessdate=2011-05-22|doi=10.1016/j.jpowsour.2011.02.025|issue=11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929002955/http://www.engr.colostate.edu/~thb/Publications/POWER14185_nocover.pdf|archive-date=2011-09-29|url-status=dead}} ''See p. 5149''.</ref> General Motors also was expecting the battery could withstand 5,000 full discharges without losing more than 10% of its charge capacity.{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=84–89}} According to GM, {{asof|2016|08|lc=y}}, no batteries have been changed due to degradation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/07/27/gm-build-phev-batteries-china-cadillac-ct6/ |title=GM will likely build PHEV batteries in China soon |first=Sebastian |last=Blanco |work=Autoblog |date=2016-07-27 |accessdate=2016-08-18}}</ref>

[[File:Chevy Volt and Cruze Eco 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Chevrolet Volt (left) and [[Chevrolet Cruze|Chevrolet Cruze Eco]] (right)]]

In April 2008 General Motors started extensive battery testing. In two years the carmaker put the battery packs to the equivalent of 150,000 real-world miles (240,000&nbsp;km) and ten years of use.{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=84–89}} The durability of the battery pack was tested for a broad range of extreme ambient conditions including a [[Multi-axis shaker table|shaker table]] to simulate potholes and a thermal chamber, to simulate temperatures varying from {{Convert|116|F|C|abbr=on}}, typical of the [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]] deserts, to {{Convert|-40|F|C|abbr=on}} typical of the [[Alaska]] [[tundra]].{{Sfn|Edsall|2010|pp=48–57}} In April 2008 the lithium-ion battery pack was placed in [[Chevrolet Malibu]]s fitted with the Volt [[powertrain]] to be used as test mules for further real-world testing.{{Sfn|Fletcher|2011|pp=84–89}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Blanco|first=Sebastian|url=http://www.autobloggreen.com/2008/04/03/gms-chevy-volt-update-all-systems-go-malibu-based-mules-comin/|title=GM's Chevy Volt update: All systems go, Malibu-based li-ion mules coming soon|work=AutoblogGreen|date=2008-04-03|accessdate=2010-10-23}}</ref> In October 2008 General Motors chose CPI (LG Chemical) to provide the battery systems for the first production version of the Volt.<ref>{{cite news |first=Soyoung |last=Kim |title=LG Chem to supply GM Volt batteries |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssChemicalsCommodity/idUSN2239779020081022?sp=trueh |work=Reuters|date=2008-10-22|accessdate=2009-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Drew |last=Johnson |title=GM inks Chevrolet Volt battery contract |url=http://www.leftlanenews.com/gm-inks-chevrolet-volt-battery-contract.html |date=2008-10-24 |work=Leftlane|accessdate=2009-08-11}}</ref> In July 2008 General Motors confirmed that a non-turbocharged, 1.4 L 4-cylinder engine would be used as the range extender, and that the intention was to build it in [[Flint, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawlor |first=Joe |url=http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/index.ssf/2008/07/general_motors_confirms_intent.html |title=General Motors confirms intention to manufacture engine for battery-powered Volt in Flint |newspaper=The Flint Journal |date=2009-07-28 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20090123113933/http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/index.ssf/2008/07/general_motors_confirms_intent.html |archivedate=2009-01-23}}</ref> In April 2009, General Motors let journalists test the Volt [[powertrain]] without the range-extending generator in the body of [[Chevrolet Cruze]] sedans that GM used as [[test mule]]s at the [[GM Technical Center]] in [[Warren, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Squatriglia|first=Chuck|title=Billion-Dollar Baby: We Drive the Chevrolet Volt|url=https://www.wired.com/autopia/2009/04/billion-dollar-baby-we-drive-the-chevrolet-volt/|work=Wired|accessdate=2012-02-21|date=2009-04-28}}</ref>

The first [[Pre-production car|pre-production test car]] based on the final Volt design was built in June 2009, in Warren, Michigan,<ref name=PreProd>{{cite web|url=http://gm-volt.com/2009/03/25/gms-response-to-the-gm-voltcom-first-chevy-volt-to-be-built-post-and-comments|title=GM’s Response to the GM-Volt.com First Chevy Volt to be Built Post and Comments|work=GM-VOLT: Chevy Volt Electric Car Site|date=2009-03-25|accessdate=2009-03-29}}</ref><ref name=Motavalli2009>{{cite news |last=Motavalli |first=Jim |date=2009-06-02 |title=G.M. Says Chevy Volt Is Still on Track |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/06/02/gm-says-chevy-volt-is-still-on-track/ |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |at=Wheels |accessdate=2009-06-02}}</ref> and by October 2009, 80 Volts had been built and were tested under various conditions.<ref name=Motavalli2009/><ref name=NYT230/> On March 31, 2010, the first factory-built Volt was produced at the [[Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly|Detroit Hamtramck Assembly Plant]] to test the [[production line]] and for quality control purposes, both of the tooling and the pre-production vehicles produced before regular production began.<ref name=UST0310>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2010/03/gm-finishes-building-first-chevy-volt-battery-car-using-production-tooling-says-the-practice-run-was-ok/1|title=GM builds first Chevy Volt, says production line practice run OK |work=[[USA Today]]|date=2010-03-31|accessdate=2010-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/04/volt-20100402.html|title=First Pre-Production Chevy Volt Rolls Off Line|work=Green Car Congress|date=2010-04-02|accessdate=2010-04-05}}</ref>

[[Tony Posawatz]] was the Volt Vehicle Line Director from 2006 to 2012,<ref>{{cite web |last=Chapman |first=Mary M. |date=2012-08-14 |title=Fisker Appoints Tony Posawatz, a Chief With Complementary Roots |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/08/14/fisker-names-tony-posawatz-who-led-development-of-chevy-volt-its-new-chief-executive/ |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |at=Wheels |accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref> and he was known as employee #1 and led the team from concept to production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://events.ntpshow.com/evs26/CUSTOM/images/PDF/PosawatzTony-bio.pdf|title=Anthony L. Posawatz, P. E.|publisher=World Electric Vehicle Association|accessdate=2014-01-06|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509165323/http://events.ntpshow.com/evs26/CUSTOM/images/PDF/PosawatzTony-bio.pdf|archivedate=2013-05-09|df=}}</ref>

[[File:Chevrolet Volt WAS 2011 946.JPG|thumb|Final production vehicle, the 2011 Chevrolet Volt]]

;Official introduction
General Motors held a ceremony at its Detroit Hamtramck Assembly Plant on November 30, 2010, to introduce the first Chevrolet Volt off the assembly line. The first Volt built for retail sale was earmarked for display at General Motors' Heritage Center museum in [[Sterling Heights, Michigan]].<ref name=Prod2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/01/business/energy-environment/01volt.html?ref=automobiles|title=G.M. to Hire 1,000 to Engineer More Electric Cars |last=Vlasic |first=Bill |work=The New York Times |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2010-11-30}}</ref> The second unit was offered at a public auction, with an opening bid of {{USD|50,000}} and it was won by [[Rick Hendrick]] who paid {{USD|225,000}}. The proceeds went to fund math and sciences education in Detroit through the Detroit Public Schools Foundation.<ref name=VoltAuction>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/12/17/rick-hendrick-wins-first-retail-chevy-volt-for-225-000/ |title=Rick Hendrick Wins First Retail Chevy Volt for $225,000 |publisher=AOL |website=Autoblog |date=2010-12-17 |accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> Deliveries to retail customers in the United States began in mid December 2010.<ref name=Volt87K>{{cite web|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/retrospective-four-years-of-nissan-leaf-and-chevy-volt/|title=Retrospective: Four Years of Nissan Leaf and Chevy Volt |author=Jeff Cobb|publisher=HybridCars.com|date=2014-12-10|accessdate=2014-12-10}}</ref> Volt deliveries began in Canada in September 2011.<ref name=Canada/> The first deliveries of the Chevrolet Volt in Europe took place in November 2011.<ref name=EUVolt/><ref name=FRAVolt/> The European version of the Volt, the Opel Ampera, was released to retail customers in Europe in February 2012.<ref name=AmperaDeliver/> Deliveries of the right-hand drive Vauxhall Ampera in the UK began in May 2012.<ref name=EUVolt/> The Holden Volt was released in Australia in December 2012.<ref name=Australia/>

=== Specifications ===
==== Drivetrain ====
{{See also|GM Voltec powertrain}}
[[File:Chevrolet Volt under the hood WAS 2011 1107.jpg|thumb|Right side: [[power inverter]] on top of the [[electric motor]] used for traction; left side: the 1.4 L gasoline engine used as a [[Engine-generator|generator]] to keep the battery at minimum charge.]]

The 2011 Chevrolet Volt has a {{kWh|16}} / 45 A·h ({{kWh|10.4}} usable) [[lithium-ion battery]] pack that can be [[state of charge|charged]] by plugging the car into a 120-240 VAC residential electrical outlet using the provided [[SAE J1772]]-compliant charging cord. No external charging station is required.<ref name="SAEJ1771" /> The Volt is propelled by an [[electric motor]] with a peak output of {{convert|111|kW|hp|abbr=on}} delivering {{convert|273|lbft|Nm|abbr=on|0}} of torque. Capacity of the battery pack was increased to {{kWh|16.5}} ({{kWh|10.9}} usable) for 2013 models, which increased the all-electric range from {{convert|35|to|38|mi|abbr=on}}. Other specifications remained the same. The battery pack capacity was increased to {{kWh|17.1}} for 2015 models. This incremental upgrade is likely to reflect in an improvement in range over previous model years, but {{as of|2014|07|lc=y}}, the 2015 Volt has not been re-certified with the EPA.<ref name="2015Volt">{{cite news|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/2015-volt-gets-17-1-kwh-battery/|title=2015 Volt Gets Larger 17.1-kWh Battery|author=Jeff Cobb|work=HybridCars.com|date=2014-07-06|accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref>

While driving, after the Volt battery has dropped to a predetermined threshold from full charge, a small [[naturally aspirated engine|naturally aspirated]] 1.4 L [[Straight-4|4-cylinder]] gasoline fueled [[internal combustion engine]] (Opel's [[GM Family 0 engine|Family 0]]<ref name="RSC">{{cite web|title=Sustainable transportation based on electric vehicle concepts: a brief overview|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/224880220_Sustainable_transportation_based_on_electric_vehicle_concepts_a_brief_overview|last1=Eberle|first1=Ulrich|first2=Rittmar|last2=von Helmolt|publisher=[[Royal Society of Chemistry]] |date=2010-05-14| accessdate=2010-06-08}}</ref>) with approximately {{convert|80|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, powers a 55&nbsp;kW [[electrical generator|generator]] to extend the Volt's range. The vehicle also has a [[regenerative braking]] system. The electrical power from the generator is sent primarily to the electric motor, with the excess going to the batteries, depending on the [[state of charge]] (SOC) of the battery pack and the power demanded at the wheels.<ref name="2011voltspecs">{{cite web|author= |year=2011 |title=2011 Volt Specs and Features |url=http://www.chevrolet.com/volt/features-specs/ |url-status = dead|website=Chevrolet |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223173940/http://www.chevrolet.com/volt/features-specs/ |archivedate=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2011-01-03 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Holden2011">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2011-12-09 |title=Volt's Revolutionary Voltec System Delivers Efficiency with Performance |url=http://www.holden.com.au/Satellite?c=News_C&cid=1236936928055&pagename=Holden.com.au%2FHLDFleetLayout |url-status = live|website=Holden Australia |publisher=Holden Ltd. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KVzX3YLy?url=http://www.holden.com.au/Satellite?c=News_C&cid=1236936928055&pagename=Holden.com.au%2FHLDFleetLayout |archivedate=2013-10-20 |accessdate=2013-10-20 |df= }}</ref>

Prior to the 2016 model year, the Volt required premium gasoline of [[octane rating|(R+M)/2 octane rating]]{{Sfn|General Motors|2012|pp=9–53}} of 91 or higher because the higher octane permitted the 10.5:1 [[compression ratio]] engine to use more ignition timing advance to maximize fuel efficiency by 5 to 10% compared to regular gasoline.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://gm-volt.com/2010/07/30/why-the-volt-requires-premium-gasoline/| title = Why the Volt Requires Premium Gasoline| publisher = GM-Volt | date = 2010-07-30 | accessdate = 2011-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://blogs.insideline.com/straightline/2010/07/2011-chevy-volt--fill-er-up-with-premium.html|title = 2011 Chevy Volt : Fill 'er Up. With Premium| author = Mike Magrath| publisher = [[Edmunds.com]]| date = 2010-07-29| accessdate = 2011-06-05}}</ref> For users who drive mostly in electric mode, and to avoid maintenance problems caused by storing the same gasoline in the tank for months, the 2011 Volt has a sealed and pressurized fuel tank to avoid evaporation. As a result, the fuel filler must be depressurized before opening the tank. Also, the engine management system monitors the time since the engine last ran, and prompts the driver to run past the {{convert|40|mi|km|adj=on}} [[all-electric range]] before recharging to consume some gasoline. If the driver does not run on gasoline, the system automatically runs the maintenance mode, which starts the engine to consume some of the aging fuel and circulate fluids within the engine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/09/13/new-problem-new-solution-chevrolet-volts-maintenance-mode-w/|title=New Problem, New Solution: Chevrolet Volt's "Maintenance Mode" Will Burn Gas To Prevent Aging |last=Abuelsamid |first=Sam |publisher=AOL |website=AutoblogGreen |date=2010-09-13|accessdate=2010-09-13}}</ref> A configuration with an [[E85]] [[flex-fuel]] capable engine is under development and was expected to be available in 2013.<ref name="NYTVolt">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/17/automobiles/17VOLT.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=Chevy%20Volt&st=cse |title=Sorting Myth From Fact as Volt Makes Its Debut |work=The New York Times |last=Mayersohn |first=Norman |date=2010-10-01 |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref>
{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=Chevy Volt drivetrain cut-away WAS 2010 8889.JPG|image2=Chevrolet Volt interior WAS 2011 1113.jpg|width=220|caption1=[[Powertrain]] cut-away of the Volt showing both engines and the underfloor T shape tunnel where the battery pack is located|caption2=The Volt seats four people as the battery runs down the center of the car preventing a rear bench}}

;Operating and driving modes
The [[Voltec]] drivetrain has three power converting elements:<ref name="GM-drive_unit">{{cite web|url=http://media.gm.com/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Oct/1011_gm_volt.html|publisher=General Motors|title=Chevrolet Volt: Engineered for Everyday Life|accessdate=2011-12-16|date=2010-10-11}} Download the document Drive_unit.doc on the link [http://media.gm.com/content/dam/Media/documents/US/Word/101010_volt_launch/Drive_Unit.doc Voltec Electric Drive System Overview].</ref>
* Primary traction electric motor/generator, provides good acceleration for driving at lower speeds and regeneration for braking, its maximum output of 111&nbsp;kW setting the maximum output of the whole system.
* Secondary electric motor/generator, works primarily as generator capable of producing 55&nbsp;kW or when necessary acts as a motor assisting the primary electric motor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=343-NQKOvLg |title=Chevy Volt Powertrain Deep Dive {{!}} Part 2|work=youtube |first=Pamela |last=Fletcher |date=2010-10-18 |accessdate=2013-03-12}}
</ref>
* Internal combustion engine of 63&nbsp;kW power,<ref>{{cite web
 |author     = 
 |title      = 2011 Chevrolet Volt Specifications
 |url        = http://media.gm.com/product/public/us/en/volt/tech/specifications.html
 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101018041809/http://media.gm.com/product/public/us/en/volt/tech/specifications.html
 |url-status = dead
 |archive-date = 2010-10-18
 |publisher  = General Motors
 |accessdate = 2011-12-16
}} Download the document
[http://media.gm.com/content/product/public/us/en/volt/tech/specifications/_jcr_content/par/sectioncontainer_1/par/download/file.res/Chevrolet%20Volt%20Specifications.doc Chevrolet Volt Specifications.doc]{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} on the link of the same name.</ref> engaged when the batteries reach the predetermined threshold.

These units are connected via a [[planetary gear]] and three electrically controlled hydraulic [[clutch]]es to provide power output for propulsion in any of four programmed operating modes:<ref name="GM-drive_unit" />

# Single motor electric – The primary motor runs solely on battery power, maximum propulsion power is 111&nbsp;kW.
# Dual motor electric – At higher vehicle speeds the secondary motor engages over the planetary gear such that it reduces the speed of the primary motor. This facilitates higher efficiency and better mileage for the combined system, without increasing the maximum power.
# Single motor extended – The battery reaches its minimum charge, which triggers the combustion engine. The engine drives the secondary motor as a generator, via the charging electronics, to keep the minimum battery charge level. The primary motor can still provide its 111&nbsp;kW for short acceleration, albeit not sustained.
# Dual motor extended – The electric motors are used again in dual configuration with increased efficiency at higher speeds. Additionally the gasoline engine contributes propulsion power via the planetary gear. While power is drained from the battery the amount is less than in mode 2 for the same propulsion power, thus extending the range.

The drivetrain permits the Volt to operate as a pure [[battery electric vehicle]] until its battery capacity has been depleted to a defined level, at which time it commences to operate as a [[Types of hybrid vehicle#Series hybrid|series hybrid]] design where the gasoline engine drives the generator, which keeps the battery at minimum level charge and provides power to the electric motors. The full charge of the battery is replenished only by loading it on the [[electrical grid]].<br /> While in this series mode at higher speeds and loads, (typically above {{Convert|30|mph}} at light to moderate loads) the gasoline engine can engage mechanically to the output from the transmission and assist both electric motors in driving the wheels, in which case the Volt operates as a [[Series-parallel hybrid|power-split or series-parallel hybrid]]. After its all-electric range has been depleted, at speeds between {{Convert|30|to|70|mph}}, the Volt is programmed to select the most efficient drive mode, which improves performance and boosts high-speed efficiency by 10 to 15 percent.<ref name="NYTVolt" /><ref name="GCCVolt4Mode">{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/10/chevy-volt-delivers-novel-two-motor-four-mode-extended-range-electric-drive-system-seamless-driver-e.html#more|title=Chevy Volt Delivers Novel Two-Motor, Four-Mode Extended Range Electric Drive System; Seamless Driver Experience Plus Efficiency|work=Green Car Congress|date=2010-10-20|accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref>

While operating modes are switched automatically the Volt allows the driver to choose from three drive modes: normal, sport and mountain. The mountain mode, which is expected to be required only under unusual power demand conditions, increases minimum battery [[state of charge]] (SOC) to around 45%, thus maintaining performance on steep and long grades. The driver hears more engine noise due to the higher rate of power generation required to maintain this mode.<ref name="GCCVolt4Mode" /> The sport mode causes the engine to rev higher, and the response to the throttle pedal is quicker.<ref name="PM101001">{{cite news|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/cars/reviews/hybrid-electric/volt-reliability-report-test|title=900 Miles Reliability Report in the Chevy Volt|work=[[Popular Mechanics]]|date=2010-10-10|accessdate=2010-10-11}}</ref> The Ampera has an additional option, the "City Mode" or "battery hold", allowing the driver to save the energy currently stored in the battery for use when traveling in urban areas or restricted zones.<ref name="GCC021711" /><ref name="Differences" /> The 2013 model year Volt includes a "Hold" option to provide the same choice.<ref name="Volt2013_02" />

==== Battery ====
{{See also|Electric vehicle battery}}

The 2011 Volt's [[lithium-ion battery]] (Li-ion) battery pack weighs {{convert|435|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and "consists of 288 individual cells arranged into nine modules. Plastic frames hold pairs of lithium-ion cells that sandwich an aluminum [[cooling fin]]. The design and construction of that aluminum plate was critical to ensuring an even temperature distribution with no hot or cool spots across the flat, rectangular cell. The battery pack has its own cooling circuit that is similar to, but independent from, the engine cooling system."<ref name="Holden2011" /><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://media.gm.com/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.print.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/0214_battery.html |title=Cooling Fins Help Keep Chevrolet Volt Battery at Ideal Temperature |publisher=General Motors |location=US |work=GM Volt Media Portal |date=2011-02-14 |accessdate=2011-04-28}}</ref>

[[File:Chevrolet Volt charging WAS 2011 833.jpg|thumb|left|Inlet for the electrical charger in the left side of the Chevrolet Volt with the manufacturer's provided charging cord]]

For the 2011/2012 model years, the battery pack stores {{kWh|16}} of energy but it is controlled or buffered via the energy management system to use only {{kWh|10.3}} of this capacity to maximize the life of the pack. For this reason the battery pack never fully charges or depletes, as the software only allows the battery to operate within a [[state of charge]] (SOC) window of 65%, after which the engine kicks in and maintains the charge near the lower level. The minimum SOC varies depending on operating conditions. When the car needs more power, such as in mountain mode, the lower limit of the SOC rises to 45% to ensure enough power is available.<ref name="Holden2011" /><ref name="GCCVolt4Mode" /> The battery capacity was increased to {{kWh|16.5}} for the 2013 [[model year]], the SOC window was increased to use {{kWh|10.8}} of the total battery energy, and the buffer to ensure battery life is not reduced. These changes increases the Volt's [[all-electric range]], but charging takes slightly longer. GM achieved the improved battery performance and durability through minor changes to the material composition of the battery cell chemistry.<ref name="Volt2013_02">{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1076766_2013-chevy-volt-gets-38-mile-electric-range-higher-98-mpge-rating|title=2013 Chevy Volt Gets 38-Mile Electric Range, Higher 98-MPGe Rating |last=Voelcker |first=John |website=Green Car Reports |date=2012-06-07 |accessdate=2012-06-09}}</ref><ref name="Volt2013_01">{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/06/2013volt-20120607.html |title=GM tweaks battery materials, pack size, SOC window to increase 2013 Chevrolet Volt EV range to 38 miles |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Green Car Congress |date=2012-06-07|accessdate=2012-06-09}}</ref>

Despite containing near identical energy (+/- {{kWh|0.5}}), the Volt's battery pack is over 70% lighter than the [[EV1]]'s original {{convert|1310|lb|kg|abbr=on}}, {{kWh|16.5}} AC Delco [[lead-acid battery]] pack, mainly because the Volt uses higher [[specific energy]] Li-ion batteries. Li-ion batteries are expected to become less expensive as [[economy of scale|economies of scale]] take effect.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://avt.inel.gov/pdf/fsev/eva/ev1_eva.pdf |title=EVAmerica Baseline Performance Testing, 1999 General Motors EV1 with NiMH Batteries |publisher=[[US Department of Energy]] (DOE), [[Idaho National Laboratory]] (INL), Advanced Vehicle Testing Activity (AVTA) |date=2002-07-30 |accessdate=2009-10-08 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://www.webharvest.gov/peth04/20041017150240/http://avt.inel.gov/pdf/fsev/eva/ev1_eva.pdf |archivedate=2004-10-17 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://avt.inel.gov/pdf/fsev/eva/ev1_eva.pdf |title=EVAmerica Baseline Performance Testing, 1997 General Motors EV1 with PbA Batteries |publisher=[[US Department of Energy]] (DOE), [[Idaho National Laboratory]] (INL), Advanced Vehicle Testing Activity (AVTA) |date=2002-08-02 |accessdate=2009-10-08 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://www.webharvest.gov/peth04/20041017150240/http://avt.inel.gov/pdf/fsev/eva/ev1_eva.pdf |archivedate=2004-10-17 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.evchargernews.com/CD-A/gm_ev1_web_site/specs/specs_specs_top.htm |title=EV1 – specs |date=2001-04-17 |accessdate=2009-10-09}}</ref>

Because batteries are sensitive to temperature changes, the Volt has a thermal management system to monitor and maintain the battery cell temperature for optimum performance and durability. The Volt's battery pack provides reliable operation, when plugged in, at cell temperatures as low as {{Convert|-13|F|C|abbr=on}} and as high as {{Convert|122|F|C|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Holden2011" /><ref name="GCC071410" /><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.chevrolet.com/content/dam/Chevrolet/northamerica/usa/nscwebsite/en/Home/Ownership/Manuals%20and%20Videos/02_pdf/2k14volt2ndPrint.pdf |title=2014 Chevrolet VOLT Owner Manual |publisher=Chevrolet |location=US |accessdate=2014-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140120184111/http://www.chevrolet.com/content/dam/Chevrolet/northamerica/usa/nscwebsite/en/Home/Ownership/Manuals%20and%20Videos/02_pdf/2k14volt2ndPrint.pdf |archive-date=2014-01-20 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> The Volt features a battery pack that can be both warmed or cooled. In cold weather, the car electrically heats the battery coolant during charging or operation to provide full power capability. In hot weather, the car can use its air conditioner to cool the battery coolant to prevent over-temperature damage.<ref name="Holden2011" /><ref name="GCC071410" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gm-volt.com/2010/12/09/the-chevrolet-volt-coolingheating-systems-explained/|title=The Chevrolet Volt Cooling/Heating Systems Explained|publisher=GM-Volt.com|date=2010-12-10|accessdate=2014-07-26}}</ref>

General Motors guarantees the Volt's battery for eight years or {{convert|100,000|mi|km}}, and cover all 161 battery components.<ref name="GCC071410" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/15/business/15auto.html?_r=1&ref=automobiles|title=G.M. to Offer 8-Year Guarantee for New Electric Car’s Battery |last=Zeller |first=Tom, Jr.|newspaper=The New York Times |date=2010-07-14 |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref> GM estimates that Volt batteries will degrade by 10 to 30% after 8 years or 100,000 miles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-20022049-54.html |title=GM envisions refreshing EV batteries |work=CNET News Green Tech |last=LaMonica |first=Martin |date=2010-11-08 |accessdate=2011-04-28}}</ref> GM has applied for a patent that may allow technicians to quickly and cheaply recover some of the performance of degraded battery packs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gm-volt.com/2010/11/08/gm-applies-for-patent-for-lithium-ion-battery-cell-refurbishing-system|title=GM Applies for Patent for Lithium-ion Battery Cell Refurbishing System|work=GM-Volt.com|date=2010-11-08|accessdate=2012-05-16}}</ref> The Volt's battery management system runs more than 500 diagnostics at 10 times per second, allowing it to keep track of the Volt's battery pack in real-time, 85% of which ensure the battery pack is operating safely and 15% monitor battery performance and life.<ref name="GCC071410">{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/07/volt-20100714.html|title=Chevrolet Volt Battery Pack Carries Standard Eight-Year, 100,000-Mile Warranty|work=Green Car Congress|date=2010-07-14|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref>

The Volt uses a plug specification published in 2009, [[SAE J1772|SAE J1772-2009]], that is considered a standard for electric cars in North America.<ref name="SAEJ1771">{{cite web |title=Plug Standard Needed For Electric Car-Charging Cord Interface: SAE J1772|date=2009-03-30|url=http://gm-volt.com/2009/04/16/plug-standard-needed-for-electric-car-charging-cord-interface-sae-j1772/#comment-107648|accessdate=2009-04-06}}</ref> Depending on in-car settings a full charge takes from approximately 10 hours (12A setting) to as much as 14 hours (8A setting) from a standard North American 120&nbsp;[[Volt|V]], 15&nbsp;[[Ampere|A]] outlet and about 4 hours from a 240&nbsp;V AC source and suitable 240 V [[EVSE]]. The Volt comes with a {{Convert|20|ft|m|abbr=on}} charging cord suitable for the standard household power outlet in its country of sale. If plugged in, recharging can be controlled remotely through a smartphone application.<ref name="Holden2011" />

==== Others ====
To save energy, the Volt sometimes heats the seats instead of blowing heated air through [[HVAC]] system, as heating the vehicle's cabin draws significant power, and can even exceed what is needed to move the vehicle on occasions.<ref name="C&Dfulltest">http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/2011-chevrolet-volt-full-test-road-test 2011 Chevrolet Volt Full Test from the Car and Driver (Dec 2010)</ref> A power-saving stereo system uses amplifiers that switch on and off rapidly to save power. It uses 50 percent less energy. The system is also lighter because the use of high grade [[neodymium magnet]]s.<ref name="C&Dfulltest" />

=== Performance ===
The Volt has a top speed of {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref name="NYTVolt" /> According to [[Edmunds.com]] road tests, the Volt's [[0 to 60 mph]] {{nowrap|(0–97 km/h)}} acceleration time is 9.2 seconds running on electric-only mode, and 9.0 seconds with the gasoline engine assisting propulsion.<ref name="EdmundsPerfor">{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/chevrolet/volt/2011/road-test-specs.html|title=2011 Chevrolet Volt Road Test Specs|work=Edmunds.com|accessdate=2011-06-05}}</ref> [[Motor Trend]] reports the Volt's quarter mile (402 m) time is 16.9 sec at {{Convert|84.3|mph|abbr=on}},<ref name=MTJune11>{{cite news|url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/oneyear/1106_2011_chevrolet_volt_arrival/index.html|title=Arrival: 2011 Chevrolet Volt|author=Frank Markus|work=[[Motor Trend]]|date=2011-04-13|accessdate=2011-05-08}} ''Over {{convert|2360|mi|km}}'' driven</ref> while Edmunds reports a quarter mile (402 m) time of 16.8 sec at {{Convert|81.5|mph|abbr=on}} in electric-only operation, and 16.6 sec at {{Convert|85.5|mph|abbr=on}} with the gasoline engine assisting.<ref name="EdmundsPerfor" /> Motor Trend reports a {{Convert|60|to|0|mph|abbr=on}} braking distance of {{Convert|112|ft|m|abbr=on}} and Edmunds.com of {{Convert|124|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name="EdmundsPerfor" /><ref name="MTJune11" />

==== Range ====
[[File:2013 Chevrolet Volt EPA sticker.png|thumb| [[Monroney label]] showing EPA's fuel economy and environmental comparison label for the 2013 Chevrolet Volt]]

According to General Motors the Volt's [[all-electric range]] with fully charged batteries varies from {{convert|25|to|50|mi}} depending on terrain, driving technique, and temperature.<ref name="NYTVolt" /><ref name="Chevroletvoltage.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.chevroletvoltage.com/index.php/volt-blog/18-volt/2240-2011-chevrolet-volt-receives-new-fuel-economy-label-from-epa.html|title=2011 Chevrolet Volt Receives New Fuel Economy Label From EPA &#124; Volt |work=Chevroletvoltage.com |date=2010-11-24|accessdate=2011-06-02}}</ref>

The 2013 model year Volt increased its EPA's rated all-electric range to {{Convert|38|mi}}.<ref name="Volt2013_02" /><ref name="Volt2013_01" /> The 2014 and 2015 Volt have the same EPA ratings.<ref name="Volt2013_14">{{cite web|url=https://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/Find.do?action=sbs&id=32655&id=33900&id=35246|title=2013 and 2014 and 2015 Chevrolet Volt|publisher=Fueleconomy.gov|author=[[U. S. Environmental Protection Agency]] and [[U.S. Department of Energy]]|date=2015-06-09|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>

The Opel Ampera official all-electric range under the EU-approved [[World Forum for Harmonization of Vehicle Regulations#Environmental compatibility|UN ECE R101]] standard for plug-in hybrids is {{convert|83|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ein Auto mit eigenem Kraftwerk |first=Klaus |last=Brieter |journal=[[ADAC|ADAC Motorwelt]] |year=2012 |issue=1 |language=German |pages=26–30}}</ref>

==== Fuel economy ====
;United States
[[File:2012 Chevrolet Volt EPA window sticker 0483.jpg|thumb|2012 Volt EPA/DOT Window sticker showed potential fuel cost saving.]]

The [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) officially rated the 2011 model year Volt's combined city/highway [[fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] in [[all-electric mode]] at 93 [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent]] (MPG-e) (2.5 L gasoline equivalent/100&nbsp;km; 112 mpg-imp gasoline equivalent) and 94 MPG-e for the 2012 model year.<ref name="EPA2012mpge" />

For the 2012 model year, EPA revised the Volt's fuel economy ratings, increasing the combined city/highway rating in all-electric mode from 93 MPG-e to 94 MPG-e, and the highway rating was increased from 90 MPG-e to 93 MPG-e.<ref name="EPA2012mpge">{{cite web |url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/phevsbs.shtml |title=2011–12 Chevrolet Volt|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Fueleconomy.gov |date=2011-11-07 |accessdate=2011-11-07}}</ref> As a result of its improved battery pack, the 2013 model year EPA rating climbed to a combined city/highway fuel economy of 98 miles per gallon gasoline equivalent (2.4 L gasoline equivalent/100&nbsp;km; 118 mpg-imp gasoline equivalent).

;Europe
The Opel Ampera official equivalent fuel consumption under the EU-approved UN ECE R101 standard for plug-in hybrids is {{convert|1.2|L/100 km|mpgus mpgimp|abbr=on|1}} (83.3&nbsp;km/L).<ref name="hede">{{cite web |last=Hedevang |first=Kurt |url=http://fpn.dk/motor/bil/article2560207.ece |title=Opel Ampera below 600,000 DKK |language=Danish |publisher=Consumer Online |date=2011-09-28 |accessdate=2011-10-14 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006071224/http://fpn.dk/motor/bil/article2560207.ece |archivedate=2011-10-06 |df= }}</ref> However, a leading Opel engineer prefers saying 169 Wh/km (16.9 kWh/100&nbsp;km) while battery-powered, and then 20&nbsp;km/L (5 L/100&nbsp;km) petrol-powered. The ECE R101 standard weights [[charge-depleting]] mode as 76% and gasoline-only driving as 24%.<ref name="AmperaRange">{{cite web |last=Arent |first=Torben |url=http://www.fdm.dk/nyheder/opels-miljoebil-klar-83-kml |publisher=United Car Owners |title=Opels miljøbil klar: 83 km/l |language=Danish |date=2011-09-27 |accessdate=2011-10-18}} ''Title translation: Opel's eco-car ready: 83 km/L''</ref>

===Operating cost and payback period===
According to ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' in December 2011, the Chevrolet Volt fuel cost in electric mode was 3.8[[Cent (currency)|¢]]/mile.<ref name="CR1211">{{cite news |url=http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2011/12/leaf-volt-tests-show-electric-cars-cost-less-per-mile-to-operate.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108013333/http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2011/12/leaf-volt-tests-show-electric-cars-cost-less-per-mile-to-operate.html |url-status = dead|archive-date=2012-01-08 |title=Leaf, Volt Tests Show Electric Cars Cost Less per Mile To Operate |last=Evarts |first=Eric |work=Consumer Reports |date=2011-12-08 |accessdate=2011-12-09 }}</ref>

According to [[Edmunds.com]], the price premium paid for the Volt in 2012, after discounting the {{USD|7,500}} [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#New plug-in electric vehicles|U.S. federal tax credit]], takes a long time for consumers to recover in fuel savings, often longer than the normal ownership time period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/industry-center/analysis/will-higher-gas-prices-boost-hybrid-ev-sales.html|title=Will Higher Gas Prices Boost Hybrid, EV Sales? |last=Krebs |first=Michelle |website=Edmunds.com|date=2012-02-28|accessdate=2012-02-29}}</ref>

===Tailpipe emissions===
{{Main|Plug-in hybrid#Greenhouse gas emissions|l1=Greenhouse gas emissions in plug-in hybrids|Plug-in electric vehicle#Air pollution and greenhouse gas emissions|l2=Air pollution and greenhouse gas emissions in plug-in electric vehicles}}

=== Safety ===
{{Euro NCAP |align=right |year=2011 |overall_stars=5 |description=Chevrolet Volt |reference={{cite web |title=Official Chevrolet Volt 2011 safety rating results |url=https://www.euroncap.com/en/results/chevrolet/volt/10963 |website=Euro NCAP}}|adult_points=30 |adult_percent=85 |child_points=38 |child_percent=78 |pedestrian_points=15 |pedestrian_percent=41 |safety_points=6 |safety_percent=86 }}

The Volt received a five-star overall crash safety rating from the [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA), the highest possible score. This rating was obtained with NHTSA's New Car Assessment Program for 2011 [[model year]] vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/06/03/chevy-volt-earns-five-star-nhtsa-crash-rating-w-videos |title=Chevy Volt earns five-star NHTSA crash rating |work=AutoblogGreen |last=Blanco |first=Sebastien |date=2011-06-03 |accessdate=2011-06-03}}</ref>

;Accident and rescue handling
In August 2010, General Motors began a training program for first responders when performing rescue duties involving the Chevrolet Volt. .<ref name="1stResponders">{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/08/gmfr-20100827.html|title= General Motors Kicks Off National Electric Vehicle Training Tour For First Responders|work=Green Car Congress|date=2010-08-27|accessdate=2011-11-11}}</ref>

;Warning sounds
Due to significant noise reduction typical of vehicles traveling in [[all-electric mode]] at low speeds, the Volt is fitted with a manually activated [[Electric vehicle warning sounds|electronic warning sound system]] called ''Pedestrian-Friendly Alert System'' for use when the car is operating at low speeds to alert pedestrians to the car's presence.<ref name="NYTRingT">{{cite web |last=Motavalli |first=Jim |date=2010-06-01 |title=Electric Car Warning Sounds: Don’t Expect Ring Tones |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/01/electric-car-warning-sounds-dont-expect-ringtones/ |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |at=Wheels |accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref>

== Second generation (2016–2019)==
{{main|Chevrolet Volt (second generation)}}
[[File:2016 Chevrolet Volt NAIAS 2015 trimmed.jpg|thumb|The [[Chevrolet Volt (second generation)|second generation Chevrolet Volt]] was unveiled at the 2015 [[North American International Auto Show]].]]

The second generation Chevrolet Volt was officially unveiled at the January 2015 [[North American International Auto Show]].<ref name=Sales2016Volt>{{cite news|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2015/01/next-gen-chevy-volt-erev-is-more-efficient-with-50-mile-electric-range.html|title=Next-gen Chevy Volt EREV is more efficient, with 50-mile electric range|author=Mike Millikin |work=Green Car Congress |date=2015-01-12|accessdate=2015-01-12}}</ref> Retail deliveries began in the United States and Canada in October 2015 as a 2016 [[model year]], with 1,324 units delivered in the U.S. that month.<ref name=2016Volt>{{cite news|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/2016-volts-account-for-1324-sales-out-of-2035-october-deliveries/|title=2016 Volts Account For 1,324 Sales Out Of 2,035 October Deliveries|author=Jeff Cobb|work=HybridCars.com|date=2015-11-03|accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref><ref name=Canada2015>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1100803_plug-in-electric-car-sales-in-canada-october-2015-the-wallet-ballot|title=Plug-in Electric Car Sales in Canada, October 2015: The Wallet Ballot|first=Matthew |last=Klippenstein |publisher=Green Car Reports|date=2015-11-06|accessdate=2015-11-07}}</ref> Availability in the American market was limited to California and the other 10 states that follow [[California Air Resources Board#California zero-emissions vehicle|California's zero emission vehicle]] regulations. GM scheduled the second generation as a 2017 model year to be released in the 39 remaining states by early 2016.<ref name=2016Volt/> Manufacturing of the 2017 MY Volt began in February 2016, and the first units arrived at dealerships at the end of February 2016. The 2017 model complies with stricter Tier 3 emissions requirements and was available nationwide.<ref name=2017Volt>{{cite web| url=http://insideevs.com/2017-chevrolet-volt-arrives-dealerships-deals-announced/ |title=2017 Chevrolet Volt Arrives At Dealerships, Deals Announced |first=Steven |last=Loveday |publisher=InsideEVs.com|date=2016-02-28|accessdate=2016-02-28}}</ref>

The second generation Volt has an upgraded powertrain with a 1.5-liter engine that uses regular gasoline; the 18.4 [[kWh]] battery pack has new chemistry that stores 20% more electrical energy and uses fewer cells, 192 compared with 288 on the 2014 Volt; it uses a new power controller that is integrated with the motor housing; the electric motors weigh {{Convert|100|lb|abbr=on}} less and use smaller amounts of [[Rare earth element|rare earth metals]]. GM engineers explained that the second generation Volt was developed using extensive input from Volt owners.<ref name=Sales2016Volt/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/29/automobiles/chevrolet-unveils-new-volt-powertrain.html?|title=New Volt Will Have Improved Powertrain and Longer Range|author=Lindsay Brooke|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2014-10-28|accessdate=2014-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2014/10/28/chevrolet-volt-gm-general-motors-ceo-mary-barra/18053171/ |title= GM CEO: 2016 Volt gets U.S. drivetrain, Detroit debut|author1=Mark Phelan |author2=Greg Gardner |work= [[USA Today]] |date= 2014-11-01 |accessdate= 2014-10-28}}</ref>

[[File:Chevrolet Volt WAS 2017 1731.jpg|thumb|left|2017 model year Chevrolet Volt]]

These improvements allow the 2016 Volt to deliver better EPA ratings than the first generation model. The all-electric range was officially rated at {{Convert|53|mi|abbr=on}}, up from {{Convert|38|mi|abbr=on}} attained by the 2015 Volt. The gains in efficiency allow the second generation Volt to improve its combined fuel economy in gasoline-only ([[charge-sustaining]]) mode to {{Convert|42|mpgUS|abbr=on}}, up from {{Convert|37|mpgUS|abbr=on}} for the previous model. The official second generation Volt's rating for combined city/highway fuel economy in [[all-electric mode]] is 106 [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent]] (MPGe; 2.2{{nbsp}}Le/100{{nbsp}}km), up from 98{{nbsp}}MPGe (2.4{{nbsp}}Le/100{{nbsp}}km) for the 2015 first generation model.<ref name=EPAVolt2016>{{cite news|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/2016-chevrolet-volt-rated-for-53-miles-electric-range/|title=2016 Chevrolet Volt Rated For 53 Miles Electric Range|author=Jeff Cobb|publisher=HybridCars.com|date=2015-08-04|accessdate=2015-08-04}}</ref><ref name=Volt2015_2016>{{cite web|url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/Find.do?action=sbs&id=36863&id=35246|title=Compare Side-by-Side - 2016/2015 Chevrolet Volt|publisher=Fueleconomy.gov|author=[[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]] and [[U.S. Department of Energy]]|date=2015-09-01|accessdate=2015-09-02}}</ref> The combined gasoline-electricity fuel economy rating of the 2016 model year Volt is {{Convert|77|mpgus|abbr=on}} [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent|equivalent]], 82{{nbsp}}MPGe (2.9{{nbsp}}Le/100{{nbsp}}km) in city driving and 72{{nbsp}}MPGe (3.3{{nbsp}}Le/100{{nbsp}}km) in highway.<ref name=EPAtop10>{{cite web|url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/topten.jsp|title=Fueleconomy.gov's Top Fuel Sippers (EPA Ratings, All Years)
|publisher=fueleconomy.gov|author=[[U. S. Environmental Protection Agency]] and [[U.S. Department of Energy]]|date=2015-12-04|accessdate=2015-12-05}} ''Excludes all-electric vehicles. Click on the tab "Top Fuel Sippers (EPA Ratings, All Years)" - The 2013-2014 Chevrolet Volt has a combined fuel economy of 62{{nbsp}}MPGe (3.8{{nbsp}}Le/100{{nbsp}}km), while 2016 Volt has a combined fuel economy of 77{{nbsp}}MPGe (3.0{{nbsp}}Le/100{{nbsp}}km). The BMW i3 REx has a combined fuel economy of 88{{nbsp}}MPGe (2.7{{nbsp}}Le/100{{nbsp}}km)''</ref> Both the all-electric range and fuel economy ratings are the same for the 2017 model year Volt.<ref name=Volt2016_2017>{{cite web|url= http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/Find.do?action=sbs&id=37309&id=36863 |title=Compare Side-by-Side - 2017/2016 Chevrolet Volt|publisher=Fueleconomy.gov|author=U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and U.S. Department of Energy|date=2016-03-18 |accessdate=2016-03-20}}</ref>

[[File:Chevrolet Volt WAS 2017 1516.jpg|thumb|Second generation [[GM Voltec powertrain|Voltec]] 1.5{{nbsp}}L gasoline-powered engine (left) and  power inverter on top of the traction electric motor (right).]]

In April 2013, CEO [[Daniel Akerson]] announced that GM expects the second generation Volt to be priced on the order of {{USD|7,000}} to {{USD|10,000}} lower than the 2013 model year with the same features.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insideevs.com/gm-ceo-chevrolet-volt-price-to-drop-by-7000-to-10000-for-next-gen/ |title=GM CEO: Chevrolet Volt Price To Drop By $7,000 to $10,000 For Next Gen |last=Cole |first=Jay |work=InsideEVs.com |date=2013-04-30 |accessdate=2013-05-01}}</ref> The 2016 Volt pricing started at {{USD|33,170}} before any [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#United States|government incentives]], plus {{USD|825}} for destination. The starting price was {{USD|1,175}} lower than the 2015 Volt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1098130_2016-chevrolet-volt-priced-from-33995-or-1195-lower-than-2015-volt|title=2016 Chevrolet Volt Priced From $33,995, Or $1,175 Lower Than 2015 Volt|author=John Voelcker|publisher=Green Car Reports|date=2015-05-03|accessdate=2015-06-14}}</ref> In California, order books for the second generation Volt were opened on May 28, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2015/05/27/2016-chevy-volt-orders-start-tomorrow/|title=Chevy Volt orders start tomorrow|author=Chris Bruce|publisher=Autoblog.com|date=2015-05-27|accessdate=2015-06-14}}</ref>

In July 2014, Opel announced that due to the slowdown in sales, they would discontinue the Ampera after the launch of the second generation Volt—and that between 2014 and 2018, Opel planned to introduce a successor electric vehicle in Europe.<ref name="Opel_weak_sales" /> General Motors announced in February 2016 that the all-electric [[Opel Ampera-e]] hatchback would go into production in 2017. This is the European version of the [[Chevrolet Bolt EV]].<ref name=Ampera_e>{{cite news|url= http://fortune.com/2016/02/11/gm-chevy-bolt-opel-ampera-e/| title=GM Unveils an All-Electric Car for Europe |first=Kirsten |last=Korosec |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |date=2016-02-11 |accessdate=2016-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/02/12/opel-ampera-e-chevy-bolt-europe/#slide-3796659 |title= Opel Ampera-e brings a Bolt of EV driving to Europe |first= Chris |last= Bruce |work=Autoblog.com |date=2016-02-12 |accessdate=2016-02-12}}</ref>

In April 2015, General Motors confirmed that it would not build the second generation Volt in [[right-hand-drive]] configuration. Due to low sales, only 246 units had been sold in Australia by mid-April 2015, and they discontinued the Holden Volt once they sold the remaining stock.<ref name=Volt2Aust/>

