=== North America ===
Assembly of the Volt was assigned to [[Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly]] plant following the conclusion of the 2007 [[United Auto Workers|UAW-GM]] [[2007 General Motors strike|contract talks]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Terlep |first=Sharon |last2=Aguilar |first2=Louis |title=Detroit to build GM's car of future |date=2007-09-29 |work=Detroit News |url=http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070929/AUTO01/709290383/1148}}</ref> For initial production the gasoline engine is being imported from the [[Opel]] engine plant in [[Aspern]], [[Austria]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Ron |last=Fonger |title=Chevy Volt's first range-extending engines will come from Austria, not Flint |url=http://www.mlive.com/naias/index.ssf/2009/01/volts_first_rangeextending_eng.html |work=MLive |publisher=MLive Media Group |date=2009-01-13|accessdate=2009-01-15}}</ref> In November 2010, General Motors began investing {{USD|138.3}} million at its engine operations plant in [[Flint, Michigan]] to support increased production of the [[Ecotec]] 1.4 L engine that is used in the [[Chevrolet Cruze]], the upcoming 2012 [[Chevrolet Sonic]], and the variant used in the Chevrolet Volt. The Flint plant was expected to start production of 400 engines a day in early 2011, ramp up daily production to 800 engines in late 2011, and to increase its capacity to 1,200 a day by late 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author= |date=2010-11-24 |title=GM to Invest $163 Million, Retain 184 Jobs in Three Plants |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Nov/1124_pt_flint |url-status = dead|website=GM News |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20101127185020/http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Nov/1124_pt_flint |archivedate=2010-11-27 |accessdate=2011-05-19 |df= }}</ref> In May 2011, General Motors decided to invest an additional {{USD|84 million}} at the Flint plant to further increase 1.4 L engine production capacity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/05/gm-investing-109m-in-mich-plants-to-support-14l-ecotec-engines-general-motors-will-invest-109-million-in-its-operations.html |title=GM investing $109M in Mich plants to support 1.4L Ecotec engines |work=Green Car Congress |date=2011-05-13 |accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref>

In 2010, General Motors planned an initial production for calendar year 2011 of 10,000 Volts and 45,000 units for 2012, up from the 30,000 units initially announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/chevrolet-increases-projected-2012-volt-production-capacity-by-50-percent/|title=Chevrolet Increases Projected 2012 Volt Production Capacity by 50 Percent|work=[[Car and Driver]]|date=2010-07-30|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> In May 2011, the carmaker again raised its production targets, as Volt and Ampera production capacity was increased to 16,000 units in 2011, including 3,500 units for exports and 2,500 demonstration units destined to U.S. dealerships, and the rest for U.S. sales. However, in November 2011 GM's sales chief announced that they would not meet its sales goal of 10,000 vehicles in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shepardson |first=David |title=GM Won't Meet 10,000 Volt Sales Goal in '11; CEO Vows To Buy Volts from Nervous Owners |url=http://detnews.com/article/20111201/AUTO01/112010446/1148/auto01/GM-won%E2%80%99t-meet-10-000-Volt-sales-goal-in-%E2%80%9911 |work=[[The Detroit News]] |date=2011-12-01 |accessdate=2011-12-01 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

Out of the 2012 production, General Motors expected to produce 10,000 Amperas for sale in Europe, 6,000 destined for Opel and 4,000 for Vauxhall in the UK. In addition, 2,000 Volts were available for the region.<ref name=2012Prod>{{cite news |url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110804/ANE/110809903/1193|title=Opel/Vauxhall to receive 10,000 Amperas from GM next year |last=Jolley |first=David |work=[[Automotive News]]Europe |date=2011-08-04 |accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> By early 2012 GM abandoned its sales target to deliver 45,000 Volts in the U.S and instead announced that production in 2012 would depend on demand.<ref name=NYT030212/><ref name=CT030212/> By March 2012 the Volt plant has a global production capacity of 60,000 vehicles per year.<ref name=CT030212>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/classified/automotive/sns-will-the-chevy-volt-be-sold-in-mexico-20120302,0,2764764.story |title=Will the Chevy Volt be sold in Mexico? |last=Popely |first=Rick |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=2012-03-02 |accessdate=2012-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306075055/http://www.chicagotribune.com/classified/automotive/sns-will-the-chevy-volt-be-sold-in-mexico-20120302,0,2764764.story |archive-date=2012-03-06 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref>

The Volt's [[battery cell]]s are produced by [[LG Chem]] in [[South Korea]] and then shipped to the US, where the battery packs are assembled at a purpose-built facility in [[Brownstown Charter Township, Michigan]] owned and operated by General Motors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gm-volt.com/2009/01/12/its-official-gm-chooses-lg-chemcompact-power-inc-to-supply-chevy-volt-lithium-ion-battery-packs|title=GM Chooses LG Chem to Supply Chevy Volt’s Lithium-ion Batteries and Will Build the Packs Themselves|date=January 12, 2009|work=GM-Volt.com}}</ref> Compact Power, the North American subsidiary of LG Chem, is building a battery plant in [[Holland, Michigan]] to manufacture the advanced battery cells for the Volt and other carmakers, with capacity to produce enough cells for 50,000 to 200,000 battery packs per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electriccarsreport.com/2011/03/lg-chem-wins-gm-supplier-of-the-year-award/|title=LG Chem Wins GM Supplier of the Year Award|work=Electric Cars Report|date=2011-03-17|accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref> The {{USD|303}} million Holland plant was funded by 50% [[U.S. Department of Energy]] matching [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|stimulus funds]] and is planned to open by mid-2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/11/lgchem-20101107.html|title=LG Chem to establish new electrolyte production plant in Michigan|work=Green Car Congress|date=2010-11-07|accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref>

The 2011 Chevrolet Volt was officially launched on November 30, 2010 at a ceremony at the Hamtramck plant, where the first production unit for retail sale came off the assembly line.<ref name=Prod2/> The first retail vehicle was delivered to a customer in [[Denville, New Jersey]] on December 15, 2010.<ref name=FirstRetailDelivery>{{cite web|url=http://www.plugincars.com/first-chevy-volts-reach-customers-will-out-deliver-nissan-december-106575.html|title=First Chevy Volts Reach Customers, Will Out-Deliver Nissan in December|work=plugincars.com|date=2010-12-16|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> GM reported it had built 12,400 Volts in total through December 2011. This includes dealers' demo vehicles in North America and Amperas in dealerships in Europe, crash test vehicles and other unavailable Volts owned by GM.<ref name=ABG010512/><ref name=GCR010512/>

GM halted production for about one month at the Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly plant by mid June 2011 to complete some upgrades, including the installation of new tooling, equipment and overhead conveyor systems throughout the facility. These upgrades allowed GM to triple the rate of Volt production and prepared the plant for 2012 Volt and Ampera production.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shepardson |first=David |date=2011-07-19 |title=GM Restarts Volt Production |url=http://www.gminsidenews.com/forums/f13/gm-restarts-volt-production-output-now-3-times-initial-rate-only-100-dealers-104522/ |work=The Detroit News |accessdate=2011-05-31}}</ref> After the plant retooling, the production rate reached 150 units per day four days a week by August 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/08/31/volt-drawing-strangers-to-chevy-into-dealerships/|title=Volt drawing strangers to Chevy into dealerships |work=AutoblogGreen|date=2011-08-30|accessdate=2011-09-08}}</ref> The Volt plant was also down during January 2012 in preparation for building the California lower-emission version.<ref name=NYT030212/> A four-week shutdown due to slow sales took place between March and April 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-04/gm-ceo-seeks-to-boost-volt-s-monthly-sales-to-3-000.html|title=GM CEO Seeks to Boost Volt’s Monthly Sales to 3,000 |last=Higgins |first=Tim |work=[[Bloomberg Markets]]|date=2012-04-04|accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref> GM said it had around 3,600 Volts in inventory and needed to reduce dealer inventories as production is expected to meet market demand.<ref name=NYT030212>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/03/business/gm-suspends-production-of-chevrolet-volt.html?_r=1|title=G.M. Again Pauses Production of Chevy Volt|last=Bunkley |first=Nick|work=The New York Times|date=2012-03-02|accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.latimes.com/business/autos/la-fi-autos-gm-volt-20120303,0,5159035.story|title=GM to pause Chevy Volt production for 5 weeks|last=Stevens |first=Matt|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=2012-03-03|accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref> GM also extended the traditional two-week summer vacation by an extra week at the Hamtramck plant.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2012/04/03/chevy-volt-sales-double-in-march/|title=Chevy Volt sales double in March|work=[[Fox News]]|date=2012-04-03|accessdate=2012-04-03|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406024357/http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2012/04/03/chevy-volt-sales-double-in-march/|archivedate=2012-04-06|df=}}</ref> GM closed its Detroit-Hamtramck plant from September 17 until October 15, 2012, affecting roughly 1,500 workers on downtime while the plant was retooled to assemble the all-new 2014 [[Chevrolet Impala]] alongside the 2013 Volt. This was the second time in 2012 that GM has halted Volt production.<ref>{{cite news|last=Healey|first=James|title=GM suspending Chevy Volt output, retooling for Impala|work=[[USA Today]]|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2012/08/gm-suspends-chevy-volt-production-over-slow-sales/1#.UDywscGPUl8|date=2012-08-27|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref>

Production of the 2013 model year Volt began in July 2012 and customer deliveries began during the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/news/2013-chevy-volts-now-available-48884.html|title=2013 Chevy Volts Now Available|last=Cobb|first=Jeff|work=HybridCars.com|date=2012-07-24|accessdate=2012-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728074428/http://www.hybridcars.com/news/2013-chevy-volts-now-available-48884.html|archive-date=2012-07-28|url-status = dead}}</ref> In October 2012, GM announced they would build the [[Cadillac ELR]] extended-range luxury coupe at the Detroit-Hamtramck Assembly plant, together with the Chevrolet Volt, Opel Ampera, and Holden Volt. The addition of the ELR to the plant represents an additional {{USD|35}} million investment, bringing the total product investment to {{USD|561}} million since December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/10/elr-20121016.html|title=Cadillac extended range electric vehicle ELR to be built at Detroit-Hamtramck |work=Green Car Congress |date=2012-10-16|accessdate=2012-10-17}}</ref> The first 2014 ELRs rolled off the production line in late May 2013. These were pre-production units destined for testing purposes before production for retail customers began at the end of 2013.<ref name=ELR01/> Deliveries of the 2014 model year Volt began in August 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insideevs.com/2014-chevrolet-volt-shipping-now/|title=2014 Chevrolet Volt Shipping Now|last=Cole |first=Jay|work=InsideEvs.com|date=2013-08-09|accessdate=2013-08-11}}</ref> Volt sales in the U.S. reached the 50,000 unit milestone in October 2013,<ref name=Volt50K>{{cite web|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/gm-sells-50000th-chevy-volt-in-october/|title=GM Sells 50,000th Chevy Volt In October|author=Jeff Cobb|publisher=HybridCars.com|date=2013-11-01|accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref> out of more than 60,000 vehicles of the Volt/Ampera family sold worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insideevs.com/chevy-volt-sales-surpass-50000-in-us/|title=Chevy Volt Sales Surpass 50,000 in US|author=Eric Loveday|publisher=InsideEVs.com|date=2013-11-02|accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref> Production of the 2015 model year Volt ended in mid-May 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topspeed.com/cars/car-news/last-first-gen-chevy-volt-rolls-off-the-assembly-line-ar169470.html#main|title=Last First-Gen Chevy Volt Rolls Off The Assembly Line|author= Jeffrey N. Ross|publisher=TopSpeed.com|date=2015-05-21|accessdate=2015-06-14}}</ref> while manufacturing of pre-production units of the second generation began in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insideevs.com/pre-production-2016-chevrolet-volts-now-built-pricing-announcement-expected-next-month/|title=Pre-Production 2016 Chevrolet Volts Now Being Built – Pricing Announcement Expected Next Month|author=Eric Loveday|publisher=InsideEVs.com|date=2015-03-30|accessdate=2015-03-31}}</ref> In July 2016, Volt sales in the American market passed the 100,000 unit milestone, out of about 117,000 Volt/Ampera family vehicles sold worldwide through June 2016.<ref name=VoltUS100K>{{cite news |url=http://www.hybridcars.com/top-selling-chevy-volt-crosses-100000-us-sales-milestone/ | title= Top-Selling Chevy Volt Crosses 100,000 US Sales Milestone |first=Jeff |last=Cobb |work=HybridCars.com | date=2016-07-26 |accessdate= 2016-07-26}} ''{{As of|2016|06}}, around 117,000 units of the Volt/Ampera family have been sold globally, including close to 10,000 Opel/Vauxhall Ampera variants sold in Europe. Volt sales in the American market passed the 100,000 milestone in July 2016.''</ref><ref name=Volt100Kmilestone>{{cite news | url=http://www.hybridcars.com/100000th-chevy-volt-sold-in-us/ | title= 100,000th Chevy Volt Sold in US |first=Jeff |last=Cobb |work=HybridCars.com | date=2016-08-01 |accessdate= 2016-08-09}}</ref> Volt production ended  on February 19, 2019. The final Volt that rolled off the assembly line went the GM Heritage Center in [[Sterling Heights, Michigan]].<ref name="End2019">{{cite web|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2019/02/final-chevrolet-volt-heads-to-gm-heritage-center/ |title=Final Chevrolet Volt Heads To GM Heritage Center|publisher=GM Authority |date=2019-02-28 |accessdate=2019-03-02}}</ref>

==== United States ====
{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=Chevrolet Volt WAS 2010 8852.JPG|image2=Chevrolet Volt WAS 2010 8846.JPG|width=220|caption1=2011 Volt's frontal view|caption2=2011 Rear view}}

Sales of the 2011 Chevrolet Volt began in selected markets due to limited initial production, as General Motors' original target for 2011 was 10,000 units.<ref name=CNNMoney0701>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/07/01/autos/volt_release_states/index.htm?hpt=T2|title=Chevy Volt bound for Texas, New York area|work=[[CNN Money]]|last=Valdes-Dapena |first=Peter|date=2010-07-01|accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref> The first cars were delivered in [[Washington D.C.]], the [[New York metropolitan area|New York City metropolitan region]], [[California]], and [[Austin, Texas]].<ref name=motavilli2010>{{cite news |last=Motavilli |first=Chris |date=2010-07-01 |title=Chevy Volt’s Initial Rollout to Include New York City |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/01/chevy-volts-initial-rollout-to-include-new-york-city/ |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |at=Wheels |accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref> By May 2011 the Volt had been launched also in [[Connecticut]], [[Maryland]], [[Michigan]], [[New Jersey]], and [[Virginia]].<ref name=GCC051911>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/05/volt-20110519.html |title=Chevrolet Volt Plant Prepping for Boost in Volt and Ampera Production; Exports to Canada, China and Europe This Year |work=Green Car Congress |date=2011-05-19 |accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref> Deliveries in [[Delaware]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Hawaii]], [[North Carolina]], [[Oregon]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[South Carolina]], and [[Washington (state)|Washington]] began in the third quarter of 2011.<ref name=GCC050411/> In June 2011, Chevrolet dealers nationwide began taking orders for the 2012 Volt, and deliveries in all 50 states began in November 2011.<ref name=GCCVolt12>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/06/volt-20110610.html|title=Chevrolet begins taking orders in all 50 US states for 2012 Volt; $1K drop in starting price|work=Green Car Congress|date=2011-06-10|accessdate=2011-06-10}}</ref><ref name=ABGVolt12>{{cite web |last=Loveday |first=Eric |title=2012 Chevrolet Volt Priced at $39,995*, Now Available To Order Ntionwide |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/06/10/2012-chevrolet-volt-priced-at-39-995-now-available-to-order-n/ |work=AutoblogGreen |publisher=AOL |date=2011-06-10 |accessdate=2011-06-10}}</ref>

The [[suggested retail price]] (MSRP) for the 2011 Chevrolet Volt in the U.S. started at {{USD|40,280}}. That price excluded destination freight charge, tax, title, license, dealer fees, optional equipment—and savings due to factory incentives, tax deductions, or other subsidies for qualifying buyers.<ref name=GCCPrice>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/07/chevrolet-volt-msrp-starts-at-41000-33500-net-of-full-federal-credit-3year-lease-program-with-option.html#more |title=Chevrolet Volt MSRP Starts at $41,000, $33,500 Net of Full Federal Credit; 3-year Lease Program with Option to Buy |work=Green Car Congress |date=2010-07-27 |accessdate=2010-07-27}}</ref><ref name=VoltGMPrice>{{cite web |url=http://www.chevrolet.com/volt/|title=2011 Volt |publisher=General Motors Company |accessdate=2011-01-01}}</ref> The MSRP for the 2012 Volt starts at {{USD|39,995}} including a {{USD|850}} destination freight charge and excludes tax, title and license fees, or other available government subsidies. The base price is {{USD|1,005}} less than the 2011 [[model year]], and General Motors explained that this price reduction was possible because of a "wider range of options and configurations that come with the expansion of Volt production for sale nationally."<ref name=GCCVolt12/><ref name=ABGVolt12/> The price dropped to {{USD|34,995}} including destination charges for the 2014 model year.<ref name=PriceVolt14/>

Due to the capacity of the Volt's battery pack it qualifies for the maximum {{USD|7,500}} [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Federal government|federal tax credit]] as specified in the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Purchasers of Plug-In Cars Will Get Tax Credits |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/27462414 |date=2008-10-30 |work=NBCnews.com |agency=Associated Press |quote= |accessdate=2009-07-25}} ''Plug-in electric cars with at least a 4-kilowatt-hour battery pack will be eligible for a {{USD|2,500}} credit, with an additional {{USD|417}} for each additional kilowatt-hour of battery capacity, up to {{USD|7,500}}. The Volt is eligible for the maximum credit.''</ref> The federal tax credit phases out over a one-year period after the manufacturer has sold at least 200,000 vehicles in the U.S.<ref name=IRS2009>{{cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Notice 2009–89: New Qualified Plug-in Electric Drive Motor Vehicle Credit |url=https://www.irs.gov/irb/2009-48_IRB/ar09.html |publisher=[[Internal Revenue Service]] |date=2009-11-30 |accessdate=2010-04-01}}</ref> Several states also have additional [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Other states|incentives or rebates]] available for [[plug-in electric vehicle]]s for qualifying buyers.<ref name=GCCPrice/><ref name=PluginAm>{{cite web|url=http://action.pluginamerica.org/t/5960/content.jsp?content_KEY=5545|title=State and Federal Incentives for EVs, PHEVs and Charge Stations|publisher=[[Plug In America]]|accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> The 2011 Volt price including all available regular production and premium options is {{USD|44,600}}, including destination charges and before tax credits or any subsidies.<ref name=NYTfeatures>{{cite news |last=Motavalli |first=Jim |date=2010-07-28 |title=The $41,000 Question: Is the Chevy Volt Worth the Money? |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/28/the-41000-question-is-the-chevy-volt-worth-the-money/?hpw |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |at=Wheels |accessdate=2010-07-31}}</ref> For the 2012 model year the price of the Volt with all available options is {{USD|46,265}} before tax credits or any subsidies available.<ref name=GCCVolt12/><ref name=ABGVolt12/> {{As of|2018|10}}, General Motors combined sales of plug-in electric vehicles in the U.S. totaled almost 197,000 units and are expected to pass 200,000 early in 2019. Thereafter, the applicable tax credit reduces gradually until it is completely phased out beginning on January 1, 2020.<ref name=UStaxcredits2018>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/arielcohen/2018/11/30/gm-must-adapt-or-die-a-lesson-for-u-s-automakers/ |title=GM Must Adapt Or Die: A Lesson For U.S. Automakers |first=Ariel |last=Cohen |work=Forbes |date=2018-11-30| accessdate=2018-12-01}}</ref>

[[File:Barack Obama driving at the White House.jpg|thumb|left|[[President Obama]] driving a Volt at the [[White House]].]]

The price for the home [[charging station|charging units]] is {{USD|490}} plus installation costs. The [[Voltec]] is a home-charging unit built by [[SPX Corporation|SPX]] for Volt owners. It is a 240-volt ([[Level 1, 2, and 3 charging#US Charging Standards|Level II]]) charger, and, according to General Motors, can replenish the Volt's batteries in about four hours. Consumer Reports has advised buyers to budget up to {{USD|2,000}}, as many older homes may need a substantial electrical upgrade because the U.S. [[National Electrical Code]] requires that the charger have its own dedicated 220-volt, 30-amp circuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2010/10/pricing-chevrolet-volt-home-charger-to-cost-490-to-2-000/index.htm|title=Pricing: Chevrolet Volt home charger to cost $490 to $2,000|work=Consumer Reports|last=Evarts |first=Eric|date=2010-10-06|accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref> Early buyers can benefit from the [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Charging Equipment|federal tax credit]] available for charging equipment.<ref name=Edm1010>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2010/10/gm-prices-volt-home-charger-installation-names-national-installer.html|title=GM Prices Volt Home Charger, Installation; Names National Installer|work=Edmunds.com|date=2010-10-07|accessdate=2010-10-11|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010023313/http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2010/10/gm-prices-volt-home-charger-installation-names-national-installer.html|archivedate=2010-10-10|df=}}</ref>

The 2011 Volt was not submitted for application to the [[California Air Resources Board]]'s (CARB) [[Clean Vehicle Rebate Project]] rebate and therefore was not required to meet the 10-year {{convert|150,000|mi|km|adj=on}} battery warranty requirement for [[partial zero-emissions vehicle|enhanced advanced technology partial zero-emissions vehicle]]s (enhAT-PZEV). The Volt team explained that for the launch General Motors decided to go with a common national package that includes an 8-year {{convert|100,000|mi|km|adj=on}} battery warranty.<ref name=GCCPrice/><ref name=CVRPFAQ>{{cite web|url=https://energycenter.org/index.php/incentive-programs/clean-vehicle-rebate-project/frequently-asked-questions-cvrp#general|title=Clean Vehicle Rebate Project General CVRP Questions: Why does the Chevrolet Volt NOT qualify this year?|publisher=Center for Sustainable Energy California|accessdate=2011-05-22|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015173641/http://energycenter.org/index.php/incentive-programs/clean-vehicle-rebate-project/frequently-asked-questions-cvrp#general|archivedate=2011-10-15|df=}}</ref> For this reason owners of the 2011 Volt did not qualify for [[Clean Vehicle Rebate Project|California's rebate]]s and free access to use [[carpool lane]]s even when traveling solo.<ref>{{cite news |last=Motavalli |first=Jim |date=2011-09-20 |title=Banished from the H.O.V. Lane, Prius Drivers May Be First to Embrace New Plug-In Model |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/09/20/banished-from-the-h-o-v-lane-prius-drivers-may-be-first-to-embrace-new-plug-in-model/ |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |at=Wheels |accessdate=2011-09-25}}</ref> A third package, scheduled for 2013, is under development with an [[E85]] [[flexible fuel vehicle|flex-fuel engine]].<ref name=NYTVolt/><ref name=GCCPrice/> General Motors engineering team commented that "introducing two or three packages of an entirely new technology set and platform at the same time wasn't an option."<ref name=GCCPrice/>

[[File:1st gen Volt at Naval Air Station Alameda CA.jpg|thumb|Chevrolet Volt with California's [[HOV lane]] access green sticker.]]

In February 2012 General Motors began deliveries of a low emission version destined for California that features a new low emissions package that allows the 2012 Chevrolet Volt to qualify as an enhanced, advanced technology –partial zero emissions vehicle (enhAT-PZEV) and have access to California's [[high-occupancy vehicle lane]]s (HOV).<ref name=HOV>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2012/02/24/gm-starts-deliveries-of-2012-hov-lane-eligible-chevy-volts-in-ca/|title=GM starts deliveries of 2012 HOV-lane-eligible Chevy Volts in California |last=King |first=Danny |work=AutoblogGreen |date=2012-02-24|accessdate=2012-02-27}}</ref> The new standard California version of the Volt features a modified engine and exhaust components. The [[catalytic converter]] was modified to add a secondary air-injection pump that "''streams ambient air into the exhaust stream to increase its ability to remove pollutants''." Owners of a 2012 Volt with the low emissions package are eligible to apply for one of 40,000 available HOV lane stickers issued to vehicles that qualify as a California AT-PZEV. The permits are handed out on a first-apply, first-served basis. Additionally, the new low emissions package makes the 2012 Volt eligible for owners to receive up to {{USD|1,500}} in state rebates through the state's Clean Vehicle Rebate Project (CVRP). This incentive is in addition to the federal government's {{USD|7,500}} tax credit.<ref name=PZEV01>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/11/16/new-enhat-pzev-chevy-volt-ready-for-california-hov-access-extra/#continued|title=2012 Volt Moves Into California's HOV Fast Lane|work=AutoblogGreen |date=2011-11-16|accessdate=2011-11-17}} ''See details in GM Press Release''.</ref><ref name=PZEV02>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/11/volt-20111117.html|title=Chevy Volt gets a Low Emissions Package for California; HOV lanes access|work=Green Car Congress|date=2011-11-17|accessdate=2011-11-17}}</ref> Only the 2012 Volts manufactured after February 6, 2012, are fitted with the low emission package and sold as standard models in California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1071925_can-your-2012-chevy-volt-use-california-hov-lanes-it-depends|title=Can Your 2012 Chevy Volt Use California HOV Lanes? It Depends|author=Nikki Gordon-Bloomfield|work=Green Car Reports|date=2012-01-19|accessdate=2012-01-20}}</ref> Other states where the Volt has solo driving access to HOV lanes are Florida, Georgia, New York and Virginia.<ref name=HOV/><ref name=VAHOV>{{cite web|url=http://www.dmv.virginia.gov/vehicles/#cleanspecialfuel.asp|title=Clean Special Fuel Vehicles/Plates|work=Virginia Department of Motor Vehicles|accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref>

===== U.S. sales =====
Since sales began in December 2010, a total of 152,144 Volts have been sold in the country through December 2018.<ref name=USsales2018Volt>{{cite web|url=https://insideevs.com/top-three-phev-u-s-in-2018/ |title=Top 3 Plug-In Hybrid Cars In U.S. In 2018: Prius Prime, Clarity, Volt | first=Mark | last=Kane | publisher=InsideEVs.com| date=2019-01-25 | accessdate=2019-01-25}} ''The Chevrolet Volt is the best selling plug-in electric car in the U.S. with 152,144 units sold through the end of 2018.''</ref> The Volt ranked as the all-time top selling [[plug-in electric car]] in the United States until February 2015, when it was surpassed by the all-electric [[Nissan Leaf]] in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insideevs.com/nissan-leaf-sales-strengthen-in-march-takes-overall-us-plug-in-sales-lead/|title=Nissan LEAF Sales Strengthen In March, Takes All-Time US Plug-In Sales Lead |author=Jay Cole|publisher=InsideEVs.com|date=2015-04-01|accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> Cumulative Volt sales passed Leaf sales in March 2016, and became once again the best selling plug-in car in the U.S. ever.<ref name=TopUSVolt2016>{{cite news| url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/04/04/chevy-volt-reclaims-us-plug-in-sales-crown-from-nissan-leaf/ | title=Chevy Volt reclaims US plug-in sales crown from Nissan Leaf |first=Sebastian |last=Blanco | work=Autoblog.com | date=2016-04-04 | accessdate=2016-04-06}} "{{As of|2016|03}}, the Chevrolet Volt is the all-time selling plug-in car in the U.S. with 92,737 units, while the Nissan Leaf ranks second with 92,522 units sold, both, since December 2010."</ref> In July 2016, Volt sales in the American market passed the 100,000 unit milestone.<ref name=VoltUS100K/><ref name=Volt100Kmilestone/> In December 2018 the Volt still ranked as the all-time [[plug-in electric car]] in the U.S.<ref name=USsales2018Volt/> while in February 2019 it had been surpassed by the all-electric [[Tesla Model 3]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://insideevs.com/us-electric-car-sales-charted-february-2019/ |title= US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: February 2019 |first= Mark | last=Kane | work=InsideEVs.com| date=2019-03-12 | accessdate=2019-03-13}}</ref>

===== Resale value =====
[[File:Chevy Volt EDTA DC 04 2011 1787.jpg|thumb|left|Production Volts at a test drive event in [[Washington, D.C.]]]]

In May 2011 [[Kelley Blue Book]] (KBB) projected the 2011 Chevrolet Volt resale value at just over {{USD|17,000}} after 36 months, the length of a typical lease, which represents 42% of the car's {{USD|41,000}} [[suggested retail price]] (MSRP). KBB explains that even though the residual value seems low, the projection considered that the first 200,000 Volts sold qualified for a {{USD|7,500}} federal tax credit, which effectively reduces the MSRP to {{USD|33,500}}, making the {{USD|17,000}}represent 51% of its original value after the tax credit. In comparison, KBB notes, the 2011 Toyota Prius has a projected residual of 46% after 36 months. KBB's estimate assumed a gasoline price around {{USD|4}} per gallon in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/05/17/kbb-sets-chevy-volt-resale-value-at-17-000-after-36-months/ |title=KBB sets Chevy Volt resale value at $17,000 after 36 months |author=Automotive News|work=AutoblogGreen|date=2011-05-17|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref><ref name=CRresale/> For 2012, Kelley Blue Book expected the Volt to retain 42% of its original value after 3 years and 27% after 5 years. Based on these figures, in November 2011 KBB awarded the Volt with the 2012 Best Resale Value Awards in the [[plug-in electric car]] category.<ref name=KBB2012/> KBB explains that the residual value for the Volt is lower than the market 35.5% average due to the {{USD|7,500}} federal tax credit, which lowers the transaction price and pushes down the residual value.<ref name=NYT1116>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/16/toyota-and-lexus-are-back-on-top-in-kelley-blue-book-resale-value-survey/?ref=automobiles|title=Toyota and Lexus Are Back on Top in Kelley Blue Book Resale Value Survey|author=Cheryl Jensen|work=The New York Times|date=2011-11-16|accessdate=2011-11-17}}</ref>

[[Consumer Reports]]' analysis show that many Chevrolets lose about half of their purchase price after three years of ownership, and if the Volt depreciates the same, {{USD|17,000}} seems a reasonable estimate. However, Consumer Reports have noted that fuel-efficient hybrids and diesel models often depreciate far less than most vehicles, which might increase the Volt's resale value after three years above the {{USD|17,000}} estimate. Additionally, if gasoline prices continue to rise or if the tax credits expire, the demand for used Chevrolet Volts could quickly increase, raising their market value. On the other hand, if the next-generation Volt's battery has twice the capacity and cost less, as General Motors has claimed, the first generation Volts would be obsolete when the new ones come out in 2015. Considering these assumptions, Consumer Reports said, "At this point we believe it’s still unclear how the Volt will fare."<ref name=CRresale>{{cite web|url=http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2011/05/cheverolet-volts-resale-value-after-three-years-17000.html|title=Chevrolet Volt resale value after three years? $17,000|work=Consumer Reports|date=2011-05-18|accessdate=2011-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522055110/http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2011/05/cheverolet-volts-resale-value-after-three-years-17000.html|archive-date=2011-05-22|url-status = dead}}</ref>

===== Pecan Street demonstration project =====
General Motors is sponsoring the [[Pecan Street demonstration project]] at the Mueller neighborhood in [[Austin, Texas]]. The project objective is to learn the charging patterns of plug-in electric car owners, and to study how a residential fleet of electric vehicles might strain the electric grid if all owners try to charge them at the same, which is what the preliminary monitoring found when the plug-in cars return home in the evening. {{As of|2013|06}}, the community has nearly 60 Chevrolet Volt owners alone thanks to GM's commitment to match the federal government's {{USD|7,500}} rebate incentive, which halves the purchase price of the Volt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=remote-control-of-electric-cars|title=Will You or the Grid Control Your Electric Car?|author=David Biello|work=[[Scientific American]]|date=2013-06-18|accessdate=2013-06-23}}</ref>

==== Canada ====
[[File:Chevrolet Volt MIA 09 2017 5621.jpg|thumb|The second generation Volt is only sold in the U.S. and Canada.]]

Chevrolet began taking orders in May 2011<ref name=GCC050411>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/05/volt-20110504.html#tp|title=Chevrolet Canada begins taking orders for the Volt starting at C$41,545; Volts a showroom draw in US|work=Green Car Congress|date=2011-05-04|accessdate=2011-05-05}}</ref><ref name=GMCanada>{{cite web|url=http://media.gm.ca/content/media/ca/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/ca/en/2010/Dec/1202_Volt_Markets|title=Chevrolet Volt Canadian Launch Markets Revealed|work=General Motors Media|date=2010-12-02|accessdate=2010-12-07|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20101208040852/http://media.gm.ca/content/media/ca/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/ca/en/2010/Dec/1202_Volt_Markets|archivedate=2010-12-08|df=}}</ref> and deliveries began in September 2011 in major cities only.<ref name=Canada>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2011/09/01/chevy-volt-canada.html|title=Chevy brings electric Volt to Canada|author=The Canadian Press|work=[[CBC News]]|date=2011-09-01|accessdate=2011-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bclocalnews.com/greater_vancouver/burnabynewsleader/news/130147388.html|title=Eager customer takes delivery of Chevy Volt in Burnaby|author=Wanda Chow|work=Burnaby NewsLeader News|date=2011-09-19|accessdate=2011-09-22|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923192725/http://www.bclocalnews.com/greater_vancouver/burnabynewsleader/news/130147388.html|archivedate=2011-09-23|df=}}</ref> During 2012 the Volt was the best selling plug-in car in Canada, outselling all other PEVs combined.<ref name=GM082014>{{cite web |url=http://www.hybridcars.com/chevy-volt-price-reduction-confirmed-for-canada-also-5000/ |title=Chevy Volt Price Reduction Confirmed For Canada; Also $5,000 |last=Crowe |first=Phillipe |website=HybridCars.com |date=2013-08-14 |accessdate=2013-08-14}}</ref> Despite a 24% reduction from 2012 sales, the Volt continued as the top selling PEV in the Canadian market in 2013, and again in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1089601_plug-in-electric-car-sales-in-canada-in-2013-up-50-percent|title=Plug-In Electric Car Sales In Canada In 2013: Up 50 Percent|author=Matthew Klippenstein|publisher=Green Car Reports|date=2014-01-15|accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1096205_plug-in-electric-car-sales-for-canada-in-2014-steady-growth|title=Plug-In Electric Car Sales For Canada In 2014: Steady Growth|author=Matthew Klippenstein|publisher=Green Car Reports|date=2015-01-15|accessdate=2015-06-14}}</ref> {{As of|2018|09}}, the Volt continued to rank as the all-time top selling plug-in electric car in Canada.<ref name=VoltUS100K/> Since September 2011, a total of 16,653 new Volts have been delivered in Canada through the end of October 2018.<ref name=CanadaSales/> The monthly sales record was set in May 2018 with 731 deliveries.<ref name=CanadaSales>{{cite web| url=http://www.goodcarbadcar.net/2011/01/chevrolet-volt-sales-figures.html| title=Chevrolet Volt Sales Figures| first=Timothy |last=Cain| work=Good Car Bad Car| date=October 2018 |accessdate=2018-12-01}}</ref> Sales in 2016 set a calendar year record of 3,469 units delivered.<ref name=CanadaSales/>

The suggested retail price (MSRP) for the 2012 Chevrolet Volt started at {{CAD|41,545}} ({{USD|42,423}} in June 2011). This excludes any charges, fees, and optional equipment—and is before any available subsidies or incentives for qualifying buyers. The Canadian market offers the Volt in one standard trim level with two option packages: ''Premium Trim Package'' and ''Rear Camera and Park Assist Package''.<ref name=GCC050411/> Some provinces are offering [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Canada|Government incentives]] including Ontario,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/story_print.html?id=3843542&sponsor=|title=We'll go green if the price is right|author=Garry Marr|work=Ottawa Citizen|date=2010-11-17|accessdate=2011-06-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019071908/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/story_print.html?id=3843542&sponsor=|archive-date=2012-10-19|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref name=Ontario10>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.ontario.ca/mto/en/2010/06/ontario-paves-the-way-for-electric-vehicles.html|title=Ontario Paves The Way For Electric Vehicles|work=Newsroom Ontario|date=2010-06-18|accessdate=2010-06-21}}</ref> Quebec<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/04/11/quebec-offer-plug-in-vehicle-rebates-8000-dollars/|title=Quebec to offer plug-in vehicle rebates of up to C$8,000|author=Eric Loveday|work=AutoblogGreen|date=2011-04-11|accessdate=2011-06-08}}</ref> (both at {{CAD|8,500}} {{USD|8,680}}) and British Columbia has announced their new ''LiveSmart BC'' program in which the Chevrolet Volt qualifies for a {{CAD|5,000}} incentive/rebate as well as {{CAD|500}} towards charging equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livesmartbc.ca/incentives/transportation/|title=The Clean Energy Vehicle (CEV) Program|work=LiveSmart BC|date=2011-11-05|accessdate=2011-11-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114150054/http://www.livesmartbc.ca/incentives/transportation/|archive-date=2011-11-14|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref>

=== Europe ===
[[File:Opel Ampera ePionier Edition – Frontansicht, 9. Juli 2012, Heiligenhaus.jpg|thumb|Opel Ampera]]

The European version of the Volt, the [[Opel]] Ampera (known as the [[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] Ampera in the United Kingdom),<ref name=carmagazine1210>{{cite news|url=http://www.carmagazine.co.uk/News/Search-Results/Industry-News/Chevrolet-Volt-for-UK-sale-in-November-2011/|title=Chevrolet Volt for European sale in November 2011|author=Tim Pollard|work=[[Car Magazine]] Online|date=2010-12-13|accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> was unveiled at the [[Geneva Auto Show]] in March 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/blog/1032003_european-volt-makes-official-debut-as-the-new-opel-ampera|title=European Volt makes official debut as the new Opel Ampera|work=Motor Authority|date=2009-03-02|accessdate=2010-07-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014000508/http://www.motorauthority.com/blog/1032003_european-volt-makes-official-debut-as-the-new-opel-ampera|archive-date=2009-10-14|url-status = dead}}</ref> and also was exhibited at the 2009 [[Frankfurt Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calcars.org/calcars-news/1072.html |title=The Ultimate Posting on Plug-In Hybrid Developments: Clip & Save|work=Calcars.org|accessdate=2009-10-13}}</ref> Opel developed the battery control modules for the Ampera at the Opel Alternative Propulsion Center Europe in Mainz-Kastel, [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autostrassenverkehr.de/aktuell/zukunft/hxcms_article_503129_14972.hbs |title=AUTOStraßenverkehr |work=Autostrassenverkehr.de |date= |accessdate=2009-08-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402015700/http://www.autostrassenverkehr.de/aktuell/zukunft/hxcms_article_503129_14972.hbs |archivedate=2009-04-02 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> The production version of the Ampera was unveiled at the 2011 [[Geneva Motor Show]].<ref name=GCC021711/> The Ampera was assembled at the Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly plant, Michigan.<ref name=GCC051911/>
{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=left|image1=Opel Ampera.JPG|image2=Opel Ampera Heck.JPG|width=220|caption1=Opel Ampera frontal view|caption2=Opel Ampera rear view}}

The main differences between the Volt and the Ampera are in their styling. The Ampera has a distinctive front and rear [[Fascia (car)|fascia]], with a large cut-out in the rear [[Bumper (automobile)|bumper]]. The Opel Ampera features more stylized alloy wheels as standard, and the side skirts are body-colored rather than black. In the inside there are only minor differences and both versions share the same exact powertrain and battery pack.<ref name=Differences>{{cite web|url=http://www.allcarselectric.com/blog/1056301_chevrolet-volt-and-opel-ampera-what-are-the-differences |title=Chevrolet Volt and Opel Ampera: What Are The Differences? |author=Antony Ingram |work=AllCarsElectric.com |date=2011-03-04 |accessdate=2011-05-20}}</ref><ref name=GreenMuk>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenmotor.co.uk/2011/04/enno-fuchs-ampera-volt-uk-europe.html|title=Is the Ampera any more than a Volt with a nose job?|work=GreenMotor.co.uk|date=2011-04-17|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref> A key operational difference was that the Ampera has four drive modes, one more than the 2011/12 model year Volt. The additional option is ''City Mode'', which adapts battery management to the needs of [[commuting|commuter travel]]. City mode or "battery hold" engages the range-extender immediately, allowing to save the energy currently stored in the battery, and when switched off, the range-extender stops and the Ampera is then able to use the energy saved in the battery for pure electric driving, for example for traveling urban areas or restricted zones, such as the European [[low emission zone]]s or to allow the Ampera to qualify for an exemption of the [[London congestion charge]]<ref name=GCC021711/><ref name=Differences/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/05/20/bibendum-2011-opel-ampera-not-only-looks-better-than-the-chevy/|title=Bibendum 2011: Opel Ampera not only looks better than the Chevy Volt, it can do more, too|author=Sebastian Blanco|work=AutoblogGreen|date=2011-05-20|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref> The 2013 model year Volt included the "Hold Drive" button to allow drivers to conserve battery-pack energy for use at a particular time of their choice.<ref name=Volt2013_02/>

;Sales
General Motors production target for 2012 was to manufacture 10,000 Amperas for sale in Europe, 6,000 destined for Opel and 4,000 for Vauxhall in the UK, plus an additional 2,000 Volts were to be made available for the region. The carmaker targeted the Ampera for business fleet market and local government agencies, where Opel has a strong customer base, while the Volt is aimed at retail customers.<ref name=2012Prod/> According to Opel, by June 2011 around 5,000 customers across Europe had reserved an Ampera, with fleet or business customers representing 60% of reservations,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/07/08/report-is-the-2011-opel-ampera-sold-out/ |title=Report: Is the 2011 Opel Ampera sold out? |author=Opel |work=AutoblogGreen |date=2011-07-08|accessdate=2011-07-10}} ''See Opel press release''.</ref> and a total of 7,000 orders were received by March 2012, with [[Benelux]], Germany and the United Kingdom as the top markets in terms of orders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/03/ampera-20120305.html|title=Opel has received more than 7,000 orders for Volt cousin Ampera|work=Green Car Congress|date=2012-03-05|accessdate=2012-04-21}}</ref><ref name=DTN042012/>

The first deliveries of the Chevrolet Volt in Europe took place on November 30, 2011, to the U.S. Embassy in France.<ref name=EUVolt/><ref name=FRAVolt>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/01/u-s-embassy-in-france-buys-four-chevy-volts/|title=U.S. Embassy in France Buys Four Chevy Volts|author=William Diem|work=The New York Times|date=2011-12-01|accessdate=2011-12-12}}</ref> Distribution of the Opel Ampera to dealerships began in December 2011, but deliveries to customers were delayed until February 2012 because Opel decided to wait until the NHTSA completed its investigation of the Volt's battery fire risk after a crash.<ref name=EUVolt>{{cite news|url=http://europe.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20111212/ANE/111209860/1193 |title=Opel delays Ampera deliveries to customers on battery worries |author=David Jolley |work=[[Automotive News]]Europe |date=2011-12-12 |accessdate=2011-12-12 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=AmperaDeliver>{{cite web|url=http://media.opel.com/media/intl/en/opel/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/intl/en/2012/opel/02_21_opel_ampera_first_customer|title=Opel Ampera: First Customers Take Delivery|author=Opel Media|work=Opel Europe|date=2012-02-21|accessdate=2012-03-01}}</ref> Since May 2012 the Vauxhall Ampera is available through the [[Zipcar]] [[carsharing]] club in London, [[Bristol]], [[Cambridge]] and [[Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/05/vauxhall-ampera-offered-through-zipcar-car-sharing-scheme.html|title=Vauxhall Ampera offered through Zipcar car sharing scheme|work=Green Car Congress|date=2012-05-20|accessdate=2012-05-21}}</ref>

[[File:2014 Vauxhall Ampera Positiv CVT 1.4 Front.jpg|thumb|Amperas destined for the UK market carry the [[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] badge.]]

The Opel/Vauxhall Ampera was Europe's top selling plug-in electric car in 2012 with 5,268 units and captured a 21.5% market share of the region's plug-in electric passenger car segment.<ref name=EUsales2011_12/><ref name=TopEUAmpera/> {{As of|2013|10}}, the Ampera held a market share of almost 10% of European registration of plug-in electric cars since 2011. The market share in the Netherlands was 40% and 10% in Germany.<ref name=EU102013>{{cite web|url=http://www.ev-sales.blogspot.ca/2013/11/europe-october-2013.html|title=Europe October 2013|author=Jose Pontes|publisher=EV Sales|date=2013-11-23|accessdate=2013-11-23}}</ref> Ampera sales fell 40% in 2013 to 3,184 cars,<ref name=EUsales2013>{{cite news|url=http://europe.autonews.com/article/20140721/ANE/307259991/opel-will-discontinue-weak-selling-ampera-sources-say|title=Opel will discontinue weak-selling Ampera, sources say|author=Mike Colias|work=[[Automotive News|Automotive News Europe]]|date=2014-07-21|accessdate=2014-07-23}} ''Ampera sales in Europe totaled 3,184 units in 2013''.</ref> and within the plug-in hybrid segment, the Ampera was surpassed in 2013 by the [[Mitsubishi Outlander P-HEV]] (8,197), [[Volvo V60 Plug-in Hybrid|Volvo V60 plug-in]] (7,437), and the [[Toyota Prius Plug-in Hybrid|Prius plug-in]] (4,314). In 2013 the Ampera ranked eighth among Europe's top selling plug-in electric vehicles, and its market share fell to about 5%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.automotiveworld.com/news-releases/mitsubishi-outlander-phev-cy13-sales-european-inauguration/|title=Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV CY13 sales – European inauguration|author=Mitsubishi News Release|work=[[Automotive News]]|date=2014-01-20|accessdate=2014-07-24}} ''A total of 8,197 Mitsubishi Outlander P-HEVs were sold in Europe in 2013''.</ref><ref name=EU122013>{{cite web|url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com.br/2014/01/europe-december-2013.html|title=Europe December 2013|author=EV Sales|date=2014-01-26|accessdate=2014-07-24}} ''A total of 7,437 Volvo V60 PHEVs and 4,314 Prius PHEVs were sold in Europe in 2013''.</ref> During the first five months of 2014, only 332 units had been sold, down 67% from the same period in 2013.<ref name=EUsales2013/> In July 2014, Opel announced that due to the slowdown in sales, they would discontinue the Ampera after the second generation Volt launch—and that between 2014 and 2018, they plan to introduce a successor electric vehicle in Europe.<ref name=Opel_weak_sales>{{cite news|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20140723/OEM04/140729943/opel-plans-electric-successor-to-ampera-plug-in-hybrid|title=Opel plans 'electric' successor to Ampera plug-in hybrid|author=Staff|work=[[Automotive News]]|date=2014-07-23|accessdate=2014-07-23}}</ref> Ampera sales totaled 939 units in 2014, and only 215 units during the first nine months of 2015.

{{As of|2016|06}}, Opel/Vauxhall Ampera sales totaled just over 10,000 units since 2011,<ref name=Top10Global062016/><ref name=Ampera10K>{{cite news | url=http://www.autohaus.de/nachrichten/ampera-e-opel-bringt-2017-neues-elektroauto-1754252.html | title= Opel bringt 2017 neues Elektroauto |language=German|trans-title= Opel brings new electric car in 2017 |author=Staff | work=Autohaus.de | date=2016-02-11| accessdate=2016-03-31}} ''About 10,000 Opel Amperas were sold in Europe by the end of 2015.''</ref> with the Netherlands as the leading market with 5,031 Amperas registered,<ref name=RAISales2015/><ref name=RAISales2014/><ref name=NED2013/> followed by Germany with 1,542 units,<ref name=SalesGer2011/><ref name=SalesGer2012/><ref name=SalesGermany2013/><ref name=SalesGer2014/><ref name=SalesGer2015/> and the UK with 1,250 units registered by the end of June 2015.<ref name=Volt100K/> The Netherlands is also the top selling Volt market in Europe with 1,062 units registered through December 2014,<ref name=RAISales2015/><ref name=RAISales2014/><ref name=NED2013/> out of about 1,750 Volts sold through 2014.<ref name=Volt100K/>

;Pricing
In February 2011 Opel announced they would offer the Ampera throughout the [[Eurozone]] for a uniform {{€|42,900}} ({{USD|56,920}}, including [[VAT]]. Prices by country still varied due to different trim levels in each market.<ref name=GCC021711>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/02/opel-to-introduce-production-version-of-opel-ampera-in-geneva.html#tp|title=Opel to introduce production version of Opel Ampera in Geneva|work=Green Car Congress|date=2011-02-17|accessdate=2011-02-17}}</ref><ref name=Opel022011>{{cite web |url=http://media.opel.com/content/media/intl/en/news/news_detail.brand_opel.html/content/Pages/news/intl/en/2011/OPEL/02_17_production_version_of_opel_ampera_world_premiere |title=Production Version of Opel Ampera: World Premiere in Geneva |work=Opel Media (press release) |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2011-07-10 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110226041206/http://media.opel.com/content/media/intl/en/news/news_detail.brand_opel.html/content/Pages/news/intl/en/2011/OPEL/02_17_production_version_of_opel_ampera_world_premiere |archivedate=2011-02-26 |df= }}</ref> The Chevrolet Volt also has a uniform price that starts at {{€|41,950}} ({{USD|55,660}} in May 2012) including VAT.<ref name=EUPrice>{{cite web|url= http://www.autoblog.com/2011/03/07/chevrolet-volt-priced-from-41-950-in-europe/|title=Chevrolet Volt priced from €41,950 in Europe|author=Aaron Richardson|work=Autoblog.com |date=2011-03-07|accessdate=2011-12-31}}</ref> The Opel Ampera is eligible to several [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Europe|subsidies and tax breaks]] available for [[plug-in electric vehicle]]s in several European countries.<ref name=GCC0420>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/04/acea-tax-20100421.html#more|title=Growing Number of EU Countries Levying CO2 Taxes on Cars and Incentivizing Plug-ins|work=Green Car Congress|date=2010-04-21|accessdate=2010-04-23}}</ref><ref name=ACEA2>{{cite web|url=http://www.acea.be/index.php/news/news_detail/an_increasing_number_of_member_states_levy_co2_based_taxation_or_incentivis/|title=An Increasing Number of Member States Levy CO2-Based Taxation or Incentivise Electric Vehicles|work=[[European Automobile Manufacturers Association]]|date=2010-04-21|accessdate=2010-04-23}}</ref>

In the UK, the Vauxhall Ampera starts at {{GBP|37,250}} ({{USD|60,400}} in May 2012) before discounting the {{GBP|5,000}} [[Plug-in Car Grant]]<ref name=Vauxhall>{{cite web|url=http://www.t3.com/news/vauxhall-ampera-electric-car-uk-release-date-and-price|title=Vauxhall Ampera electric car UK release date and price|author=Luke Johnson|work=[[T3 (magazine)|T3]]|date=2012-05-02|accessdate=2012-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/may/01/vauxhall-ampera-electric-cars?newsfeed=true|title=Vauxhall predicts Ampera will boost electric car sales |author=Adam Vaughan|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2012-05-01|accessdate=2012-05-02}}</ref> The Chevrolet Volt was also be available in the UK at {{GBP|33,545}} ({{USD|54,400}} in May 2012) before the government grant. All Volts in the UK came standard with leather interior.<ref name=UKPrice>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2011/07/06/2012-chevrolet-volt-priced-from-28-545-45-860-usd-in-uk/|title=2012 Chevrolet Volt priced from £28,545 in UK|author=Eric Loveday|work=AutoblogGreen|date=2011-07-06|accessdate=2011-07-06}}</ref>

===China===
General Motors unveiled the Chevrolet Volt in [[Shanghai]] under its Chinese name of 沃蓝达 (Wo Lan Da) in September 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinacartimes.com/2010/09/01/chevrolet-volt-lands-in-china-sales-to-begin-next-year/|title=Chevrolet Volt lands in China, sales to begin next year|work=China Car Times|date=2010-09-01|accessdate=2012-08-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929010630/http://www.chinacartimes.com/2010/09/01/chevrolet-volt-lands-in-china-sales-to-begin-next-year/|archive-date=2012-09-29|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Aug/0831_china|title=General Motors Celebrates Arrival of Chevrolet Volt in China|date=2010-08-31|accessdate=2010-09-01|work=[[General Motors]] News Release}}</ref> The first Volts, out of the 10-vehicle demonstration fleet, arrived in China by late December 2011. The demonstration program is taking place in Beijing, [[Tianjin]] and Shanghai.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.chinaautoreview.com/pub/CARArticle.aspx?ID=7023|title=Chevy Volt enters China for demonstration|author=Ray Jing|work=China Automotive Review|date=2012-01-05|accessdate=2012-01-23}}</ref>

[[File:Chevrolet Volt 01 China 2012-05-26.JPG|thumb|left|Chevrolet Volt in [[Anting]], [[Shanghai]].]]

The Volt went on sale in China by late 2011 with pricing starting at {{CNY|498,000}} (around {{USD|78,300}} {{as of|2012|08|lc=y}}) and sales are limited to eight Chinese cities: [[Beijing]], [[Shanghai]], [[Hangzhou]], [[Suzhou]], [[Wuxi]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Shenzhen]] and [[Foshan]].<ref name=China>{{cite news|work=The Detroit News |url=http://www.detnews.com/article/20111121/AUTO01/111210408/1361/GM-sets-price-for-Chevy-Volt-in-China |last=Shepardson |first=David |title=GM sets price for Chevy Volt in China|date=2011-11-21|accessdate=2011-11-22}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> GM explained that 13 dealerships were selected in the eight cities, and they were chosen because these "''cities have more elites who are inclined to try new technologies and lead the fashion tide.''"<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.chinaautoreview.com/pub/CARArticle.aspx?ID=7073 |title=Volt will be a hot seller in China, but not now|author=Ray Jing|work=China Automotive Review |date=2012-01-11|accessdate=2012-01-23}}</ref>

[[File:Buick Velite 5.jpg|thumb|The Buick Velite 5 is a rebadged [[Chevrolet Volt (second generation)|second generation Chevrolet Volt]] tailored for the Chinese market.]]

However, according to General Motors, in a move illegal under [[WTO]] rules the Chinese government refused the allow Chevrolet Volt owners access to up to {{USD|19,300}} in [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#China|government subsidies]] available for plug-in vehicles unless GM had agreed to transfer intellectual property to a joint venture with a Chinese automaker for at least one of the Volt's three core technologies: electric motors, complex electronic controls, and power storage devices, whether batteries or a fuel cell. General Motors negotiated with the Chinese government to let the Volt qualify for the subsidies without the technology transfer, but {{as of|2011|11|lc=y}}, the subsidies were available only for electric cars made by Chinese automakers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/06/business/global/gm-aims-the-volt-at-china-but-chinese-want-its-secrets.html?_r=1&ref=automobiles|title=Hybrid in a Trade Squeeze|author=Keith Bradsher|work=The New York Times|date=2011-09-05|accessdate=2011-09-08}}</ref> As a result of the high import duties, General Motors reported in August 2012 that sales are minimal, those of a very low-volume car.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://europe.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20120810/OEM05/120819980/1131/gm-plans-alternative-energy-push-in-china-despite-slow-volt-launch |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130117100215/http://europe.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20120810/OEM05/120819980/1131/gm-plans-alternative-energy-push-in-china-despite-slow-volt-launch |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-17 |title=GM plans alternative-energy push in China despite slow Volt launch |author=Ben Klayman |work=[[Automotive News]] |date=2012-08-10 |accessdate=2012-08-14 }}</ref> According to LMC Automotive, a total of 18 Volts have been sold in China through June 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20120816/BLOG06/120819888#ixzz23qAGKfko|title= Volt sales target is red meat for the bashers|author=Mike Colias|work=[[Automotive News]]|date=2012-08-16|accessdate=2012-08-18}}</ref>

In March 2012, General Motors announced that an agreement was signed with the China Automotive Technology and Research Center (CATARC) to manage the Volt demonstration fleet in Beijing and to gather feedback from the fleet usage for one year. The demonstration Volts were scheduled to be delivered in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/03/catarc-20120326.html|title=GM China signs MOU with CATARC for Chevrolet Volt demo fleet|work=Green Car Congress|date=2012-03-26|accessdate=2012-03-26}}</ref>

The Buick Velite 5 was introduced at the 2017 [[Shanghai Auto Show]], a rebadged [[Chevrolet Volt (second generation)|second generation Chevrolet Volt]] tailored for the Chinese market. The Velite 5 will be manufactured in China.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.motortrend.com/news/buick-velite-5-chinas-take-chevrolet-volt/ |title=Extended range plug-in hybrid to be manufactured in China |first=Stefan |last=Ogbac |work=Motortrend |location=US |date=2017-04-18 |access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Other markets ===
;Australia
[[File:2012 Holden Volt (EV MY13) hatchback (26273290082).jpg|thumb|right|Holden Volt]]

Deliveries of the Holden Volt in the Australian market began in December 2012, and the first Volt was delivered to the U.S. Ambassador in [[Canberra]].<ref name=Australia>{{cite news|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/act-news/ambassador-gets-a-charge-out-of-new-volt-20121212-2bafe.html|title=Ambassador gets a charge out of new Volt|author=David Ellery|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=2012-12-13|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://insideevs.com/first-holden-volt-now-delivered-in-australia-an-owners-story/|title=First Holden Volt Now Delivered In Australia; An Owner’s Story |author=Martin Tesar|work=Inside EVs|date=2012-12-08|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref> Pricing starts at {{A$|59,990}} (around US$62,598).<ref name=Holden1>{{cite news|author=Mike Stevens|title=Holden Volt Pricing And Specifications Announced For Australia|url=http://www.themotorreport.com.au/54487/holden-volt-on-sale-in-australia-later-2012-pricing-and-specifications-announced|accessdate=2012-07-03|work=The Motor Report|date=2012-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/au/en/holden/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/au/en/2011/Dec/1209_HoldenVoltReinventsAutomotiveTransportation |title=Holden Volt Reinvents Automotive Transportation |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work=Holden Media Australia|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2011-12-15}}</ref> In November 2011 the first Holden Volt arrived in Australia for a series of evaluation tests. Holden stated that the Volt underwent numerous modifications to better suit it to Australian roads, though the test vehicles were still [[left-hand drive]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Holden Volt Hits Australia For Tests, Launch Set For Late 2012|url=http://www.themotorreport.com.au/52868/holden-volt-hits-australia-for-tests-launch-set-for-late-2012|accessdate=2011-11-15|newspaper=The Motor Report|date=2011-11-15}}</ref>

The Holden Volt was available through 49 select Holden dealerships throughout metropolitan and rural Australia, with 18 in Victoria, 11 in New South Wales, 9 in Queensland, 7 in Western Australia and 4 in South Australia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Only 49 dealers to sell Holden's Volt|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/only-49-dealers-to-sell-holdens-volt/story-fn3dxity-1226391004065|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=2012-06-11|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref> A total of 80 Holden Volts were sold during 2012,<ref name=SalesAust2012>{{cite web|url=http://bestsellingcarsblog.com/2013/01/05/australia-full-year-2012-mazda3-leads-again-in-record-market-no-local-model-on-podium-for-the-first-time-since-1930s/|title=Australia Full Year 2012: Mazda3 leads again in record market, no local model on podium for the first time since 1930s!|author=Mat Gasnier|work=Best Selling Car Blog|date=2013-01-05|accessdate=2013-01-18}}</ref> and 101 units in 2013.<ref name=AustSales2013>{{cite web|url=http://bestsellingcarsblog.com/2014/01/16/australia-q4-2013-jeep-grand-cherokee-shines/|title=Australia Q4 2013: Jeep Grand Cherokee shines|author=Mat Gasnier|publisher=Best Selling Cars Blog|date=2014-01-16|accessdate=2014-01-25}}</ref> A total of 246 had been sold in the country by mid April 2015, with the stock of the first generation almost empty. General Motors announced that it would not build the second generation Volt in right-hand-drive configuration, so the Volt was discontinued in Australia when the remaining stock sold out.<ref name=Volt2Aust>{{cite news|url=http://www.caradvice.com.au/350518/the-holden-volt-is-dead/|title=The Holden Volt is dead|author= Mike Costello|work=Car Advice|date=2015-04-25|accessdate=2015-04-26}}</ref>

;Brazil
[[General Motors do Brasil]] announced that it would import from five to ten Volts to Brazil during the first semester of 2011 as part of a demonstration and also to lobby the federal government to enact financial incentives for [[green vehicle|green cars]]. If successful, General Motors would adapt the Volt to operate on [[ethanol fuel]], as most new [[Flexible-fuel vehicles in Brazil|Brazilian cars are flex-fuel]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.estadao.com.br/estadaodehoje/20110110/not_imp664114,0.php |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731063437/http://www.estadao.com.br/estadaodehoje/20110110/not_imp664114,0.php |url-status = dead|archive-date=2012-07-31 |title=GM vai trazer Volt para o Brasil para fazer testes |work=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]] |date=2011-01-10 |accessdate=2011-01-17 |language=Portuguese }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unica.com.br/noticias/show.asp?nwsCode=A9BA7BF7-5B3D-48B6-A250-435BAE8CF632 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120719134939/http://unica.com.br/noticias/show.asp?nwsCode=A9BA7BF7-5B3D-48B6-A250-435BAE8CF632 |url-status = dead|archive-date=2012-07-19 |title=Carro híbrido Volt da GM deveria incluir tecnologia flex |work=[[UNICA, Brazil]] |date=2011-01-14 |accessdate=2011-01-17 |language=Portuguese }}</ref>

;Japan
In December 2010, General Motors announced plans to introduce the Volt in limited numbers into Japan in 2011 for technology and market test purposes. Exports for retail sales will depend on the results of this trial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gm-volt.com/2010/12/05/gm-announces-chevy-volt-canadian-rollout-plans-and-asian-exports/|title=GM Announces Chevy Volt Canadian Rollout Plans and Asian Exports|work=GM-Volt.com|date=2010-12-05|accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref>

;Mexico
The second generation Volt was released for retail customers in December 2015. Pricing starts at 638,000 pesos (~{{USD|36,880}}), and it is available in [[Mexico City]], [[Monterrey]], [[Guadalajara]], [[Querétaro City|Querétaro]], and [[Puebla City|Puebla]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insideevs.com/2016-chevrolet-volt-now-sale-mexico/|title=2016 Chevrolet Volt Now On Sale In Mexico |author=Mark Kane|publisher=InsideEVs.com|date=2015-12-26|accessdate=2015-12-26}}</ref> Sales totaled 36 units and in 2017 and 34 in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2019/02/chevy-volt-sales-increase-1-percent-to-5063-units-in-q4-2018/ |title=Chevy Volt Sales Increase 1 Percent To 5,063 Units In Q4 2018 |first=Alex |last=Luft |publisher=GM Authority |date=2019-02-10 |accessdate=2019-02-17}}</ref>

;New Zealand
The Holden Volt was released in New Zealand through three dealerships, with one in Auckland, Christchurch and Wellington.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holden's Volt dealers all fired up|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/motoring/news/article.cfm?c_id=9&objectid=10813100|accessdate=2012-06-23|newspaper=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=2012-06-16}}</ref> Deliveries began in late 2012 and pricing starts at {{NZ$|85,000}} (around {{USD|71,930}}).<ref name=NZL12>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/motoring/news/article.cfm?c_id=9&objectid=10848166|title=Holden: Charged up performer|author=Jacqui Madelin |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=2012-11-18|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref> By mid-2015, only 16 units were registered despite a price dropped to {{NZ$|75,000}}. Due to low sales of the first generation model, the second generation Volt was not available in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.driven.co.nz/news/news/holden-volt-unplugged/ |title=Holden Volt unplugged |first=Liz |last=Dobson |work=Driven |date=2015-07-05 |accessdate=2019-02-17}}</ref>

===Global sales===
Combined global Volt/Ampera sales passed the 100,000 unit milestone in October 2015.<ref name=Volt100K>{{cite news|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/gm-sells-its-100000th-volt-in-october/|title=GM Sells Its 100,000th Volt in October|author=Jeff Cobb|work=HybridCars.com|date=2015-11-04|accessdate=2015-11-04}}''About 102,000 units of the Volt/Ampera family have been sold worldwide by the end of October 2015''.</ref>  The Volt/Ampera family was the world's best selling plug-in electric car in 2012 with 31,400 units sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bestsellingcarsblog.com/2013/03/20/world-full-year-2012-discover-the-top-500-best-selling-models/|title=World Full Year 2012: Discover the Top 1000 best-selling models! |author1=Mat Gasnier |author2=Austin Rutherford |work=Best Selling Cars Blog|date=2013-03-20|accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> The Opel/Vauxhall Ampera was Europe's top selling plug-in electric car in 2012 with 5,268 units, representing a market share of 21.5% of the region's plug-in electric passenger car segment.<ref name=EUsales2011_12>{{cite web|url=http://bestsellingcarsblog.com/2013/02/10/europe-full-year-2012-top-350-all-models-ranking-now-available/|title=Europe Full Year 2012: Now with Top 350 models & Top 60 brands |author=Mat Gasnier|publisher=Best Selling Cars Blog |date=2013-02-10|accessdate=2013-02-13}} ''Ampera sales in Europe totaled 5,268 units in 2012 and 304 in 2011''.</ref><ref name=TopEUAmpera>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoviva.com/news/europe_s_best_selling_electric_car_is_the_opel_vau/7484|title=Europe's Best Selling Electric Car Is the Opel/Vauxhall Ampera|author=Christopher Bruce|publisher=Autovia|date=2012-12-12|accessdate=2013-02-13}}</ref> However, during 2013 Ampera sales fell 40%, and the declining trend continued during 2014 and 2015.<ref name=EUsales2013/>

{{As of|2018|10}}, global Volt/Ampera family sales totaled about 177,000 units since its inception in December 2010,<ref name=Top5Global102018>{{cite web |url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2018/11/global-all-time-top-5-until-oct-18.html |title=Global All-Time Top 5 (Until Oct. '18) |last=Pontes | first=Jose | publisher=EVSales.com| date=2018-11-30 | accessdate=2018-12-01}}</ref> including over 10,000 Opel/Vauxhall Amperas sold in Europe up to December 2015.<ref name=Top10Global062016>{{cite news|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/global-10-best-selling-plug-in-cars-are-accelerating-forward/ | title=Global 10 Best-Selling Plug-In Cars Are Accelerating Forward | first=Jeff | last=Cobb| work=HybridCars.com| date=2016-08-10| accessdate=2016-08-13}} ''{{As of|2016|06}}, cumulative global sales of the top selling plug-in electric cars were led by the Nissan Leaf (over 228,000), followed by the Tesla Model S (129,393), Votl/Ampera family (about 117,300), Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV (about 107,400), Toyota Prius PHV (over 75,400), BYD Qin (56,191), Renault Zoe (51,193), BMW i3 (around 49,500), Mitsubishi i-MiEV family (about 37,600) and BYD Tang (37,509).''</ref><ref name=LeafBest250K>{{ cite news | url=http://www.hybridcars.com/nissans-quarter-millionth-leaf-means-its-the-best-selling-plug-in-car-in-history/ |title= Nissan’s Quarter-Millionth Leaf Means It’s The Best-Selling Plug-in Car In History | first= Jeff | last=Cobb | work= HybridCars.com | date=2017-01-09 |accessdate=2017-01-10}} ''{{As of|2016|12}}, the Nissan Leaf is the world's best-selling plug-in car in history with more than 250,000 units delivered, followed by the Tesla Model S with over 158,000 sales, the Volt/Ampera family of vehicles  with 134,500 vehicles sold, and the Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV with about 116,500 units sold through November 2016. These are the only plug-in electric cars so far with over 100,000 global sales.''</ref> {{As of|2018|10}}, the Volt family of vehicles ranks as the world's all-time top-selling plug-in hybrid, and it is also the third best selling [[plug-in electric car]] in history after the [[Nissan Leaf]] (375,000) and the [[Tesla Model S]] (253,000).<ref name=Top5Global102018/>

{{As of|2018|12}}, Chevrolet Volt sales are led by the United States with 152,144 units delivered,<ref name=USsales2018Volt/> followed by Canada with 16,653 units through September 2018,<ref name=CanadaSales/> and the Netherlands with 1,062 Volts registered through December 2015.<ref name=RAISales2015/><ref name=RAISales2014/><ref name=NED2013/> Out of the 9,989 Opel/Vauxhall Amperas sold in Europe through December 2015,<ref name=EUsales2011_12/><ref name=EUsales2013/><ref name=PHEVSales2014/> 5,031 were registered in the Netherlands,<ref name=RAISales2015/><ref name=RAISales2014/><ref name=NED2013/> 1,542 in Germany,<ref name=SalesGer2011/><ref name=SalesGer2012/><ref name=SalesGermany2013/><ref name=SalesGer2014/><ref name=SalesGer2015/> and 1,279 in the UK by the end of September 2015,<ref name=UK3Q2015/> together representing 78% of Ampera sales.

The following tables present retail sales of the Volt and Ampera variants through December 2015 for the top selling national markets by year since deliveries began in December 2010. Demonstration vehicles allocated to dealerships are not included in retail sales reports while they are used for test drives.

