===End of production===
In 2018, General Motors decided to end production in March 2019. The primary reason given was that the Volt is a sedan, and sales of four-door vehicles were in decline. Car salesmen were proving resistant to selling the car because it was more complicated (and thus took more of their time) to explain how the vehicle operated.<ref>{{cite news
 | title=The Chevy Volt is dead; long live the Chevy Volt
 | first1=Jordan | last1=Golson
 | work=The Verge | publisher=Vox Media |location=US
 | url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/12/1/18119828/chevy-volt-cease-production-gm-ev-electric
 | date=2018-12-01 |access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> Marketing trends showed that sales of hybrids were dropping as more customers were turning to all-electric vehicles like the [[Chevrolet Bolt]]. The range-anxiety associated with all-electric vehicles had been in decline due to better battery technology, and most hybrid drivers were turning on their gas-powered engines less frequently. The battery technology developed for the Volt had already been incorporated into the Bolt.<ref>{{cite web
 | title=Why General Motors Is Ditching the Chevy Volt
 | first1=Julia | last1=Pyper
 | work=Greentech Media |location=US
 | url=https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/why-general-motors-is-ditching-the-chevy-volt
 | date=2018-12-10 |access-date=2019-07-04 }}</ref>

== Related concept cars ==
<!--Please keep these and future sub-sections short. The Converj already has its own article, and the MPV5 eventually might have its own-->
[[File:CadillacConverjConcept.jpg|thumb|right|The Cadillac Converj, unveiled at the 2009 [[North American International Auto Show]], shares the Volt's [[GM Voltec powertrain|Voltec powertrain]].]]

;Cadillac Converj
{{Main|Cadillac Converj}}
The Cadillac Converj is a [[plug-in hybrid]] [[concept car]] first unveiled at the 2009 [[North American International Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wot.motortrend.com/report-gm-will-produce-voltbased-cadillac-converj-plugin-concept-6718.html |title=GM Will Produce Volt-Based Cadillac Converj Plug-in Concept|author=Rory Jurnecka|work=[[Motor Trend]]|date=2010-01-11|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref> It incorporated the propulsion system from the Chevrolet Volt, including the [[Voltec]] powertrain. In August 2011, General Motors announced it would produce the Converj as the [[Cadillac ELR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/08/elr-20110817.html|title=Cadillac Converj extended range EV concept officially headed for production|work=Green Car Congress|date=2011-08-17|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref> The first 2014 ELRs rolled off the production line in late May 2013. These were pre-production units destined for testing purposes and production for retail customers started at the end of 2013.<ref name=ELR01>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/05/30/first-cadillac-elr-rolls-off-the-line/|title=First Cadillac ELR rolls off the line|author=Jeffrey N. Ross|work=Autoblog.com |date=2013-09-11|accessdate=2013-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=GM Prices Cadillac ELR Plug-In Coupe at $75,995|first=Melissa|last=Burden|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20131011/AUTO0103/310110094/1361/GM-prices-Cadillac-ELR-plug-in-coupe-at-$75-995|work=[[The Detroit News]]|date=2013-10-11|accessdate=2013-10-13|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131011203241/http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20131011/AUTO0103/310110094/1361/GM-prices-Cadillac-ELR-plug-in-coupe-at-$75-995|archivedate=2013-10-11|df=}}</ref> The ELR was released to retail customers in the U.S. in December 2013.<ref name=ELR1st>{{cite web|url=http://insideevs.com/cadillac-elr-december-2013-sales/|title=Cadillac ELR Arrives Early, Manages To Sell 6 Copies In December|author=Jay Cole|publisher=InsideEvs.com|date=2014-01-03|accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>

;Volt MPV5
At the 2010 [[Auto China]] show General Motors unveiled the Chevrolet Volt MPV5 Concept. The Volt MPV5 is a [[plug-in hybrid|plug-in]] [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover]] hybrid and has a top speed of {{Convert|100|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} and an [[all-electric range|electric range]] of {{Convert|32|mi}}. The MPV5 integrates design elements from the Volt, with a body style very similar to the [[Chevrolet Orlando]] and four inches larger than its predecessor, [[Chevrolet HHR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/04/22/beijing-2010-chevrolet-volt-mpv5-crossover-revealed/|title=Beijing 2010: Chevrolet Volt MPV5 crossover revealed|author=Sam Abuelsamid |work=AutoblogGreen|date=2010-04-22|accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/cn/en/news/news_detail.brand_chevrolet.html/content/Pages/news/cn/en/2010/Beijing/03|archive-url=https://archive.today/20100425053036/http://media.gm.com/content/media/cn/en/news/news_detail.brand_chevrolet.html/content/Pages/news/cn/en/2010/Beijing/03|url-status = dead|archive-date=2010-04-25|title=GM Unveils Chevrolet Volt MPV5 Electric Concept at Auto China 2010|work=General Motors Media|date=2010-04-22}}</ref>

;Opel Monza Concept
The [[Opel Monza Concept]] is a four-seat coupe plug-in hybrid concept car with [[gullwing door]] unveiled at the 2013 [[Frankfurt Motor Show]]. The concept shares the same basic plug-in hybrid setup as the Chevrolet Volt and Opel Ampera, but using a turbocharged 1 L 3-cylinder [[natural gas]]-powered engine as its [[range extender]] instead of General Motors’ current 1.4 L gasoline engine. According to Opel, this concept is the role-model for the next generation of Opel cars, and because of its modular chassis design, future cars based on it would be able to accommodate gasoline, diesel or electric power.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/10/frankfurt-motor-show-the-opel-monza-returns/?ref=automobiles&_r=0|title=Frankfurt Motor Show: The Opel Monza Returns|author=Stephen Williams|work=The New York Times|date=2013-09-10|accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/09/10/opel-monza-concept-frankfurt-2013/|title=Opel Monza Concept soars into Frankfurt [w/video]|author=Jeffrey N. Ross|work=Autoblog.com |date=2013-09-10|accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>

== Controversies and criticism ==
=== EPA fuel economy testing ===
{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=Erev PHEVseries 98mpg 500px.jpg|image2=Phev-blended paralell 65mpge 500px.jpg|width=220|caption2=Typical EPA's new [[Fuel economy and environment label|fuel economy label]] for an [[series hybrid|extended-range electric]] vehicle like the Chevrolet Volt (top), and for a blended or [[Series-parallel hybrid|series-parallel]] plug-in hybrid (bottom)}}

In 2008, [[General Motors]] was concerned about how the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) would test the Volt to determine its official [[fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] rating. The controversy centered on whether, by including a gasoline engine, the Volt should be classified as a [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]] rather than an [[electric car]] as claimed by General Motors. If tested with the same EPA tests used by other hybrids, the Volt's EPA fuel economy rating would be around {{Convert|48|mpgus|abbr=on}} due to the current EPA test for hybrids disallowing vehicles from boosting their mpg rating using stored battery power. General Motors stated that the Volt is an entirely new type of vehicle that the EPA's current fuel economy tests are not suited to rate, and that a new test should be devised for this emerging class of hybrid-electrics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/cars-trucks/daily-news/080908-Chevy-Volt-100-mpg-or-48-mpg-/|title=Chevy Volt – 100 mpg, or 48 mpg?|date=2008-09-08|work=U.S. News, Rankings and Reviews}}</ref> General Motors also advocated for a more simplified mpg calculation method to take into account the range of a plug-in hybrid while running solely on electricity. Because the Volt can travel {{convert|40|mi|km}} on batteries alone, GM argued that most drivers with a daily commute of less than that distance would drive only in electric mode, so long as they recharged their vehicle at work or at home overnight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.motortrend.com/6293345/government/could-the-epa-cripple-the-chevy-volt/index.html|title=Could the EPA cripple the Chevy Volt?|date=2008-09-05|work=[[Motor Trend]]}}</ref>

The EPA official rating issued in November 2010 included separate fuel economy ratings for [[all-electric mode]] and gasoline-only mode, with an overall combined city/highway gasoline-electricity fuel economy rating of {{Convert|60|mpgus|abbr=on}} [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent|equivalent]] (MPG-e).<ref name=GCCEPAVolt/><ref name="EPAmpge">{{cite web |url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/phevsbs.shtml |title=2011 Chevrolet Volt |website=Fueleconomy.gov |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2011-05-04 |accessdate=2011-05-08}}</ref><ref name=Bailey2010>{{cite news |last=Bailey |first=David |last2=Krolicki |first2=Kevin |date=2010-11-24 |title=Chevy Volt Tops Prius in Fuel Economy Rating |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE6AN65K20101124 |work=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=2010-11-24}}</ref> To address the variability of the fuel economy outcome depending on miles driven between charges, EPA also included in the Volt's [[fuel economy label]] a table showing fuel economy and electricity consumed for five different scenarios driven between a full charge, and a never-charge scenario.<ref name=GCCEPAVolt/> According to this table the Volt's fuel economy goes up to {{Convert|168|mpgus|abbr=on}} equivalent (MPG-e) if driven {{Convert|45|mi}} between full charges.<ref name=EPAmpge/> Also, in recognition of the multiple operating modes that a plug-in hybrid can be built with (all-electric, blended, and gasoline-only), for the new [[fuel economy and environment label]] that will be mandatory in the U.S. beginning in [[model year]] 2013, EPA and the [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA) issued two separate fuel economy labels for plug-in hybrids. One label is for extended-range electric vehicles, like the Chevy Volt, with two modes: all-electric and gasoline-only; and a second label for blended mode that includes a combination of all-electric, gasoline and electric operation, and gasoline only, like a [[hybrid electric vehicle|conventional hybrid vehicle]].<ref name=GCC2013>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/05/felabel-20110525.html|title=EPA, DOT unveil the next generation of fuel economy labels|work=Green Car Congress|date=2011-05-25|accessdate=2011-05-31}}</ref><ref name=EPA2013>{{cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/otaq/carlabel/420f11017.htm|title=Fact Sheet: New Fuel Economy and Environment Labels for a New Generation of Vehicles|author=EPA|publisher=[[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]]|date=May 2011|accessdate=2011-05-31}}''EPA-420-F-11-017''</ref>

=== EPA fuel economy rating ===
In August 2009, General Motors released its estimated city [[fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] rating for the Volt of {{convert|230|mpgUS|abbr=on}} of gasoline plus {{kWh|25}}/100&nbsp;mi (560 kJ/km) of electricity using the EPA's proposed method for evaluating plug-in hybrids.<ref name=NYT230>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/12/business/12auto.html|title=G.M. Puts Electric Car’s City Mileage in Triple Digits |work=The New York Times |date=August 11, 2009|accessdate=2009-08-11 |first1=Bill|last1=Vlasic | first2=Nick | last2=Bunkley}}</ref><ref name="CNNMoney">{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/08/11/autos/volt_mpg/index.htm?postversion=2009081108|title=Chevy Volt to get 230 mpg rating|work=CNN Money |date=2009-08-11|first=Peter|last=Valdes-Dapena|accessdate=2009-08-11}}</ref> The [[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) issued a statement clarifying that the "EPA has not tested a Chevy Volt and therefore cannot confirm the fuel economy values claimed by GM."<ref name=NYT230/> In July 2010, GM explained that their estimate was based on a formula that had not been officially approved and that they had been awaiting the EPA's decision on how the equivalent fuel economy of [[plug-in hybrid]]s would be estimated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2010/07/chevy-volt-fuel-economy-forecast-of-230-mpg-now-dead-actual-number-tbd/1?POE=click-refer|title=Chevy Volt 230-mpg forecast dead; feds work on new formula|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Sharon Silke Carty|date=2010-07-14|accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref>

The official EPA rating was issued in November 2010 and became the agency's first [[fuel economy label]] for a [[plug-in hybrid]]s. The EPA rated the 2011 Volt combined fuel economy at 93 [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent]] (MPG-e) in [[all-electric mode]], and {{Convert|37|mpgus|abbr=on}} in gasoline-only mode, for an overall combined fuel economy rating of {{Convert|60|mpgus|abbr=on}} equivalent (MPG-e). The label also shows the combined city-highway fuel economy in all-electric mode expressed in traditional energy consumption units, rating the Volt at 36 {{kWh|link=yes}} per {{Convert|100|mi}}.<ref name=GCCEPAVolt/><ref name=Bailey2010/>

=== Production cost and sales price ===
In 2009, the [[Presidential Task Force on the Auto Industry]] said that "GM is at least one generation behind [[Toyota]] on advanced, “green” powertrain development. In an attempt to leapfrog Toyota, GM has devoted significant resources to the Chevy Volt" and that "while the Chevy Volt holds promise, it is currently projected to be much more expensive than its gasoline-fueled peers and will likely need substantial reductions in [[manufacturing cost]] in order to become commercially viable."<ref>{{cite web |title=Determination of Viability Summary: General Motors Corporation |date=2009-03-30 |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/assets/documents/GM_Viability_Assessment.pdf |accessdate=2009-04-06 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090407084946/http://www.whitehouse.gov/assets/documents/GM_Viability_Assessment.pdf |archivedate=2009-04-07 |df= }}</ref>
A 2009 [[Carnegie Mellon University]] study found that a [[Plug-in hybrid|PHEV]]-40 will be less cost effective than a [[Hybrid electric vehicle|HEV]] or a PHEV-7 in all of the scenarios considered, due to the cost and weight of the battery.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.cmu.edu/me/ddl/publications/2009-EP-Shiau-Samaras-Hauffe-Michalek-PHEV-Weight-Charging.pdf|title=Impact of battery weight and charging patterns on the economic and environmental benefits of plug-in hybrid vehicles|last1=Shiau|first1=Ching-Shin Norman|last2=Samaras|first2=Constantine|last3=Hauffe|first3=Richard|last4=Michalek|first4=Jeremy J.|journal=Energy Policy|pages=2653–2663|year=2009|volume=37|accessdate=2011-05-22|doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2009.02.040 |issue=7}} ''See Figure 6, pp. 2661–2662''</ref> Jon Lauckner, a Vice President at General Motors, responded that the study did not consider the inconvenience of a {{Convert|7|mi}} [[all-electric range|electric range]] and that the study's cost estimate of {{USD|1,000}} per {{kWh|link=yes}} for the Volt's battery pack was "many hundreds of dollars per [[kilowatt hour]] higher" than what it costs to make today."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.treehugger.com/files/2009/03/gm-fights-back-chevy-volt-plug-in-hybrid-battery-cost.php|title=GM Fights Back: Volt Battery Pack "Hundreds Less" than $1,000/({{kWh}}) |work=Treehugger |author=Michael Graham Richard |date=2009-03-04|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref>

[[File:Barack Obama drives Chevy Volt.jpg|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] behind the wheel of a new Chevy Volt during his tour of the [[Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly|General Motors Auto Plant in Hamtramck]], [[Michigan]]]]

In early 2010, it was reported that General Motors would lose money on the Volt for at least the first couple of generations, but it hoped the car would create a green image that could rival the Prius.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/gm-exechybrids-unlikely-to-take-more-than-10-of-us-market-2010-02-13|title=GM exec:Hybrids unlikely to take more than 10% of U.S. market|author=Sharon Terlep|work=MarketWatch}}</ref>

After the Volt's sales price was announced in July 2010, there was concern expressed of the launch price of the Volt and its affordability and resulting popularity, especially when the federal subsidies of {{USD|2.4 billion}} were taken into account in the development of the car.<ref name=niedermeyer2010>{{cite news |last=Niedermeyer |first=Edward |title=G.M.’s Electric Lemon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/30/opinion/30neidermeyer.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=electric%20car%20lemon&st=cse |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |at=Opinion |date=2010-08-01 |accessdate=2010-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2010-08-01 |title=Low Voltage |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/31/AR2010073102589.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |at=Editorials |accessdate=2010-08-01}}</ref>

General Motors CEO [[Edward Whitacre Jr.]] rejected as "ridiculous" criticism that the Volt's price is too expensive. He said that "I think it's a very fair price. It's the only car that will go coast to coast on electricity without plugging it in, and nobody else can come close."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cheersandgears.com/topic/64689-whitacre-talks-to-the-news-about-volt-bailout-critics-more/ |title=Whitacre Talks to The News about Volt, Bailout Critics, More |work=The Detroit News |date=2010-08-06 |accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref> Despite the federal government being the major GM shareholder due to the 2009 government-led [[bankruptcy]] of the automaker, during a press briefing at the [[White House]] a [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury]] official clarified that the federal government did not have any input on the pricing of the 2011 Chevrolet Volt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideline.com/chevrolet/volt/2011/white-house-chevy-volt-pricing-decision-didnt-come-from-us.html|title=White House: Chevy Volt Pricing Decision Didn't Come From Us|work=Edmunds.com Inside Line|date=2010-07-30|accessdate=2010-08-05}}</ref>

There have also been complaints regarding price markups due to the initial limited availability in 2010 of between {{USD|5,000}} to {{USD|12,000}} above the recommended price,<ref name=NYT080510>{{cite web|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/let-the-chevrolet-volt-buyer-beware-as-some-dealers-mark-up-price/?ref=automobiles|title=Let the Chevrolet Volt Buyer Beware, as Some Dealers Mark Up Price |newspaper=The New York Times |author=Jonathan Schultz|date=2010-08-05|accessdate=2010-08-06}}</ref> and at least in one case a {{USD|20,000}} mark up in California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoobserver.com/2010/07/chevrolet-dealer-want-a-volt-thatll-be-an-extra-20k.html|title=Chevrolet Dealer: Want a Volt? That'll be an Extra $20K|work=Edmunds.com Auto Observer|author=Bill Visnic|date=2010-07-31|accessdate=2010-08-06}}</ref> Even though the carmaker cannot dictate vehicle pricing to its dealers, GM said that it had requested its dealers to keep prices in line with the company's suggested retail price.<ref name=NYT080510/>

In May 2011 the [[National Legal and Policy Center]] announced that some Chevrolet dealers were selling Volts to other dealers and claiming the {{USD|7,500}} federal tax credit for themselves. Then the dealers who bought the Volts sell them as used cars with low mileage to private buyers, who no longer qualify for the credit. General Motors acknowledged that 10 dealer-to-dealer Volt sales had taken place among Chevrolet dealers, but the carmaker said they do not encourage such practice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/02/over-g-m-s-objections-dealers-sell-used-chevy-volts-without-7500-tax-credit/?ref=automobiles|title=Over G.M.’s Objections, Dealers Sell "Used" Chevy Volts Without $7,500 Tax Credit |author=Mary M. Chapman|work=The New York Times|date=2011-06-02|accessdate=2011-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/autos/la-fi-autos-volt-20110603,0,6666334.story|title=Chevy Volt dealers inflate prices, take tax credits|author=Tiffany Hsu|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=2011-06-03|accessdate=2011-06-03}}</ref>

In September 2012, [[Reuters]] published an opinion/editorial article where it claimed that General Motors, nearly two years after the introduction of the car, was losing {{USD|49,000}} on each Volt it built.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maynard |first1=Micheline |title=Stunner: GM May Be Losing $50,000 On Each Chevrolet Volt |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michelinemaynard/2012/09/10/stunner-gm-may-be-losing-50000-on-each-chevrolet-volt/#1b9a84462cc9 |website=Fobes |publisher=Forbes Media, LLC |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref> The article concluded that the Volt is "over-engineered and over-priced" and that its technological complexity has put off many prospective buyers, due to fears the car may be unreliable.<ref>{{cite news|title=GM's Volt: The ugly math of low sales, high costs|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/10/us-generalmotors-autos-volt-idUSBRE88904J20120910|work=[[Reuters]] |author1=Bernie Woodall |author2=Paul Lienert |author3=Ben Klayman |date=2012-09-10|accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> GM executives replied that Reuters' estimates were significantly flawed as they also allocated the vehicle's [[research and development]] program costs only against the number of Volts sold in the United States ({{as of|2012|08|lc=y}}), instead of spreading the total costs over the entire lifetime of the model, as well as including those units sold in Europe and other countries. GM explained that the investments will pay off once the innovative technologies of the Volt are applied across multiple current and future products.<ref>{{cite web|title=GM Response to Reuters Story on Chevrolet Volt Development Costs|url=http://media.gm.com/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2012/Sep/0910_volt.html||author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|work=GM News United States|date=2012-09-10|accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref>

=== Battery pack fire risk ===
{{See also|Plug-in electric vehicle fire incidents}}
[[File:Volt NHTSA fire 01 before & after.jpg|thumb|Chevrolet Volt that caught fire after the pole test in June 2011. Top: before the NHTSA's pole test. Below: After the fire.]]

In June 2011 a Volt that had been subjected by the [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA) to a {{convert|20|mph|abbr=on}} side pole impact crash test followed by a post-impact rollover, caught fire three weeks later in the test center parking lot, burning nearby vehicles. The battery was found to be the source of the fire. After the fire, both Chevrolet and the NHTSA independently replicated the crash test and a subsequent vehicle rotation procedure to test for any fluid leakage, but in their first attempt they could not reproduce the conditions under which the battery pack ignited. The NHTSA said it had "concluded that the crash test damaged the Volt’s lithium-ion battery and that the damage led to a vehicle fire that took several weeks to develop."<ref name=Fire5>{{cite web |title=Defect Investigations Results - NHTSA Action Number : PE11037 |url=http://www-odi.nhtsa.dot.gov/defects/results.cfm?action_number=PE11037&SearchType=QuickSearch&summary=true |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work=Safercar.gov |date=2011-11-25 |accessdate=2011-11-27}}</ref><ref name=Fire1>{{cite news |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/11/chevy-volt-fire-prompts-federal-investigation-into-lithium-ion-batteries/?ref=automobiles |title=Chevy Volt Fire Prompts Federal Investigation Into Lithium-Ion Batteries |last=Jensen |first=Christopher |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=2011-11-11 |accessdate=2011-11-11}}</ref><ref name=Fire2>{{cite news |last=Green |first=Jeff |last2=Welch |first2=David |last3=Greiling Keane |first3=Angela |date=2011-11-11 |title=GM Volt Fire Prompts Probe of Lithium Batteries |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-11-11/gm-volt-battery-fire-is-said-to-prompt-u-s-probe-into-electric-car-safety.html |work=Bloomberg |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |accessdate=2011-11-11}}</ref> In further testing of the Volt's batteries carried out by NHTSA in November 2011, two of the three tests resulted in thermal events. One battery pack was rotated 180 degrees within hours after it was impacted and began to smoke and emit sparks after rotation. In the other case, the battery pack that was crashed-tested one week earlier and that had been monitored since the test caught fire. The NHTSA then took an uncommon step on November 25, 2011 and opened a formal safety defect investigation "without any data from real-world incidents" to examine the potential risks involved from intrusion damage to the battery pack in the Chevrolet Volt.<ref name=Fire5/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/26/business/regulators-investigate-chevrolet-volt-battery.html?_r=2&ref=automobiles |title=Formal Defect Inquiry of Volt Battery Begins |last=Bunkley |first=Nick |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |date=2011-11-25|accessdate=2011-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/26/us-gm-volt-idUSTRE7AO1SH20111126?type=GCA-GreenBusiness&feedType=RSS&feedName=GCA-GreenBusiness&rpc=43|title=U.S. opening formal probe into GM Volt fire risk |author=Tim Dobbyn|work=[[Reuters]]|date=2011-11-25|accessdate=2011-11-27}}</ref> After the initial Volt fire, the NHTSA examined the [[Nissan Leaf]] and other plug-in electric vehicles and said its testing "has not raised safety concerns about vehicles other than the Chevy Volt."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/22/business/tsunami-reveals-durability-of-nissans-leaf.html?_r=1&ref=automobiles|title=Tsunami Reveals Durability of Nissan’s Leaf |last=Bunkley |first=Nick|work=The New York Times|date=2011-12-21|accessdate=2012-01-02}}</ref>

[[File:Volt NHTSA fire 03 post test.jpg|thumb|left|Chevrolet Volt after being subjected to the [[NHTSA NCAP|NCAP]] pole test on May 12, 2011 at MGA Research's test facility.]]

As a result of this investigation, GM announced that it would offer any new GM car in exchange to any Volt owner who has concerns while the federal investigation was taking place.<ref name=NYT120111/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2011/11/gm-offering-loaner-cars-to-worried-chevrolet-volt-owners/1|title=GM offering loaner cars to worried Chevrolet Volt owners|author1=Chris Woodyard |work=[[USA Today]]|date=2011-11-28|accessdate=2011-11-28}}</ref> In December 2011, the company said that if necessary they were prepared to recall all the vehicles and repair them upon determination of the cause of the fires, and also announced they would buy back the car if the owner was too afraid of the potential for a fire.<ref name=NYT120111/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2011/12/gm-general-motors-buy-back-chevrolet-volts-crash-fires/1?csp=hf|title=GM offers to buy back Chevrolet Volts from fearful owners|author=Tom Krisher|agency=Associated Press|work=[[USA Today]]|date=2011-12-01|accessdate=2011-12-01}}</ref> GM's CEO also said that it may be necessary to redesign or make changes to the battery pack depending on the recommendations from federal officials.<ref name=NYT120111/><ref>{{cite video|url=http://insider.thomsonreuters.com/link.html?cn=share&cid=311268&shareToken=MzowZThkMGQ1OC00ZjhkLTQ5NWUtYWU1OC03YTk1YTNjNDNiMDc%3D|people=Paul Ingrassia (Reuters) and [[Daniel Akerson]] (General Motors CEO) | medium = Television news|title=GM may redesign the Volt battery - CEO Akerson | publisher =Reuters: Reuters Insider|date=2011-12-01|accessdate=2011-12-01}} ''Click on transcript to see the complete text''.</ref> As of December 1, 33 Volt owners in the U.S. and 3 in Canada had requested a loaner car.<ref name=NYT120111>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/02/business/gm-offers-to-buy-back-volts-over-fire-risk.html?_r=2&adxnnl=1&ref=automobiles&adxnnlx=1322831943-dKu5UwyE526IzewMp3iFCA|title=G.M. Offers to Buy Back Hybrid Volts From Owners|author=Bill Vlasic|work=The New York Times|date=2011-12-01|accessdate=2011-12-04}}</ref><ref name=CanadaNov11>{{cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/cars/clarifies+Volt+buyback/5813959/story.html?cid=megadrop_story|title=GM clarifies Volt 'buyback'|author=Grace Macaluso|work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=2011-12-05|accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref> As of December 5, General Motors reported that a couple dozen Volt owners had requested the carmaker to buy back their cars, and the company had already agreed to repurchase about a dozen. Before the carmaker agrees to buy back each vehicle, other options are explored as GM primarily wants to provide loaner cars, but "if the only way we can make them happy is to repurchase it, then we will," a GM spokesman said. General Motors explained that the buy back price includes the Volt purchase price, plus taxes and fees, less a usage fee based on how many miles the car has been run.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.detnews.com/article/20111205/AUTO01/112050420/1148/GM+says+%E2%80%98couple+dozen%E2%80%99+Volt+owners+seek+repurchase+after+fire+tests |title=GM says 'couple dozen' Volt owners seek repurchase after fire tests |last=Shepardson |first=David |work=The Detroit News |date=2011-12-05|accessdate=2011-12-06}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2011/12/few-dozen-owners-ask-gm-to-buy-back-their-chevrolet-volts/1|title='Few dozen' owners ask GM to buy back their Chevrolet Volts|author=Chrissie Thompson|work=[[USA Today]]|date=2011-12-06|accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://wot.motortrend.com/chevrolet-volt-wont-lose-top-safety-ratings-during-battery-fire-investigations-143217.html|title=Chevrolet Volt Won’t Lose Top Safety Ratings During Battery Fire Investigations|author=Jake Holmes|work=[[Motor Trend]]|date=2011-12-06|accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref> As of January 5, 2012, GM reported that around 250 Volt owners had requested either a loaner vehicle or a potential buyback.<ref name=ABG010512>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2012/01/05/chevy-volt-will-receive-safety-enhancements-but-dont-call-it-a/|title=Chevy Volt will receive safety enhancements, but don't call it a recall|author=Sebastian Blanco| work=AutoblogGreen| date=2012-01-05| accessdate=2012-01-05}} ''See GM Press Release''.</ref>

The NHTSA also said it was working with all automakers to develop postcrash procedures to keep occupants of electric vehicles and emergency personnel who respond to crash scenes safe. Additionally, NHTSA advised to be aware that fires may occur a considerable amount of time after a crash. General Motors said the first fire would have been avoided if GM's protocols for deactivating the battery after the crash had been followed.<ref name=Fire4/> These protocols had been used by GM since July 2011 but were not shared with the NHTSA until November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/buick/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Nov/1128_volt|title= GM Builds on Battery Safety to Ensure Confidence in Chevrolet Volt|work=GM Media News |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=2011-11-28|accessdate=2011-12-01}} ''See the details in the attached file:[http://media.gm.com/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Nov/1128_volt/_jcr_content/rightpar/sectioncontainer_1/par/download/file.res/112811%20Reuss%20Barra%20Volt%20Transcripts.doc112811 Reuss Barra Volt Transcripts.doc Mark Reuss and Mary Barra Volt Conference Call Transcripts]''</ref> In another statement the carmaker stated that they "are working with other vehicle manufacturers, first responders, tow truck operators, and salvage associations with the goal of implementing industrywide protocols."<ref name=Fire4>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/12/business/energy-environment/regulators-examine-electric-car-batteries-after-fire.html?_r=1&ref=electricvehicles|title=Batteries in Electric Cars Examined After Chevy Volt Fire|last=Bunkley |first=Nick|work=The New York Times|date=2011-11-11|accessdate=2011-11-11}}</ref>
{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=Volt NHTSA fire 05.jpg|image2= Volt NHTSA fire 04.jpg|width=220|caption1=NHTSA testing of the Volt's battery pack|caption2=Arcing event during manual rollover of post crashed Volt's battery, November 24, 2011.}}

Customer deliveries of the Opel Ampera in Europe were delayed until the NHTSA completed its investigation of the Volt's battery fire risk to make sure the vehicle is safe.<ref name=EUVolt/> However, deliveries of the first Chevrolet Volts in Europe began in France in November 2011.<ref name=EUVolt/><ref name=FRAVolt/> Deliveries of the Vauxhall Ampera in the UK continued as scheduled for May 2012.<ref name=EUVolt/> Opel Ampera deliveries began in February 2012.<ref name=AmperaDeliver/>

;Battery enhancements
On January 5, 2012, General Motors announced that it would offer a customer-satisfaction program to provide modifications to the Chevrolet Volt to reduce the chance that the battery pack could catch fire days or weeks after a severe accident. The carmaker described the modifications as voluntary enhancements and stated that neither the car nor the battery was being recalled. General Motors determined the June fire was the result of a minor intrusion from a portion of the vehicle into a side section of the battery pack. This intrusion resulted in a small coolant leak inside the battery of approximately {{cvt|50|mL}}. When the vehicle was put through a slow roll, where it was rotated at 90-degree increments, holding in each position for about five minutes, an additional {{convert|1|liter}} of coolant leaked. With the vehicle in the 180 degrees position (upside down), the coolant came in contact with the printed circuit board electronics at the top of the battery pack and later crystallized. Three weeks later this condition, in combination with a charged battery, led to a short circuit that resulted in the post-crash fire.<ref name=NYT010512>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/06/business/gm-to-reinforce-battery-in-hybrid-car.html?ref=automobiles |title= G.M. to Reinforce Battery in Hybrid Car |last=Bunkley |first=Nick |work= The New York Times |date= 2012-01-05 |accessdate= 2012-01-05}}</ref><ref name=GCC010512>{{cite web |url= http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/01/volt-20120105.html |title= GM makes modifications to Chevrolet Volt vehicle structure and battery coolant system to further protect from delayed electrical fire after severe crash |work= Green Car Congress |date= 2012-01-05 |accessdate= 2012-01-05}}</ref>

General Motors explained the modifications will enhance the vehicle structure that surround the battery and the battery coolant system to improve battery protection after a severe crash. The safety enhancements consist of strengthening an existing portion of the Volt's vehicle safety structure to further protect the battery pack in a severe side collision; add a sensor in the reservoir of the battery coolant system to monitor coolant levels; and add a tamper-resistant bracket to the top of the battery coolant reservoir to help prevent potential coolant overfill.<ref name=NYT010512/><ref name=GCC010512/> The additional side safety structural pieces have a total weight of {{cvt|2|to|3|lb|kg}}, and their function is to spread the load of a severe side impact away from the battery pack, reducing the possibility of intrusion into the pack.<ref name=GCR010512/>

During December 2011, GM conducted four crash tests of Volts with the reinforced steel and upgraded cooling system, resulting in no intrusion to the battery and no coolant leakage. On December 22, 2011, the NHTSA also subjected a modified Volt to the same test that led to the original fire, with no signs of the damage that is believed to have been the cause. The NHTSA said "the preliminary results of the crash test indicate the remedy proposed by General Motors today should address the issue of battery intrusion" though its investigation remained open. General Motors declined to say how much the modifications would cost.<ref name=NYT010512/><ref name=GCC010512/>

All 12,400 Chevrolet Volts produced until December 2011, including all Amperas in stock at European dealerships, were scheduled to receive the safety enhancements. Since production was halted during the holidays, the enhancements were in place when production resumed in early 2012. Sales continued, and dealers modified the Volts they had in stock. General Motors sent a letter to Volt owners indicating that they could schedule the service appointment to protect their batteries beginning in the last week of March 2012.<ref name=ABG010512/><ref name=GCR010512>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1071348_chevrolet-to-offer-volt-modifications-against-battery-fire-risk |title= Chevrolet To Offer Volt Modifications Against Battery Fire Risk |last=Voelcker |first=John |work=Green Car Reports |date=2012-01-05 |accessdate= 2012-01-05}}</ref><ref name=DTN0322>{{cite news |url=http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20120322/AUTO0103/203220490/1148/rss25 |title=GM to replace Volt power cords |last=Shepardson |first=David |work=The Detroit News |date=2012-03-22 |accessdate=2012-03-26 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> General Motors also decided to replace the 120-volt charging cords in most of the nearly 10,000 Volts sold since late 2010. The new cords were enhanced to add durability, and some of the chargers built after February 5 have the new cords.<ref name=DTN0322/>

;NHTSA findings
On January 20, 2012, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration closed the Volt's safety defect investigation related to post-crash fire risk. The agency concluded that "no discernible defect trend exists" and also found that the modifications recently developed by General Motors are sufficient to reduce the potential for battery intrusion resulting from side impacts. The NHTSA also said that "based on the available data, NHTSA does not believe that Chevy Volts or other electric vehicles pose a greater risk of fire than gasoline-powered vehicles." The agency also announced it has developed interim guidance to increase awareness and identify appropriate safety measures regarding electric vehicles for the emergency response community, law enforcement officers, tow truck operators, storage facilities and consumers.<ref name=NTHSAfind01>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/21/business/us-finds-no-defect-in-volt.html?_r=1&ref=automobiles |title=In Fire Investigation, Regulators Say They Found No Defect in Volt |last=Bunkley |first=Nick |last2=Vlasic |first2=Bill |work=The New York Times|date=2012-01-20 |accessdate=2012-01-21}}</ref><ref name=NTHSAfind02>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/01/nhtsa-concludes-safety-defect-investigation-into-post-crash-fire-risk-of-the-volt.html |title=NHTSA concludes safety defect investigation into post-crash fire risk of the Volt |work=Green Car Congress |date=2012-01-20 |accessdate=2012-01-21}}</ref>

;House of Representatives hearing

The chairman of the Subcommittee on Regulatory Affairs, Stimulus Oversight and Government Spending, [[U.S. Representative]] [[Jim Jordan (Ohio politician)|Jim Jordan]] held hearings on January 25, 2012, to investigate why the NHTSA opened a formal investigation only five months after the first postcrash battery fire occurred in June. The subcommittee of the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform wanted to determine if government officials, including from NHTSA, purposely held back information on the Volt fire for political reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20111206/OEM05/111209921|title=House will hold hearings on NHTSA's silence after Volt fire|last=Rogers |first=Christina|work=[[Automotive News]]|date=2011-12-06|accessdate=2011-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Vlasic |first=Bill |last2=Bunkley |first2=Nick |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/08/business/general-motors-to-re-examine-volts-welded-parts.html?scp=1&sq=Chevrolet%20Volt&st=cse |title=G.M. Re-examines Volt as Safety Concerns Rise |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company|date=2011-12-07|accessdate=2011-12-08}}</ref> Both [[Daniel Akerson]], General Motors CEO, and David L. Strickland, NHTSA administrator, denied any wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/26/business/republicans-charge-delay-in-volt-fire-announcement.html?emc=eta1|title=Accusations of Delay in Disclosing Volt Fire|last=Wald |first=Matthew L. |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company|date=2012-06-25|accessdate=2012-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/01/25/highway-safety-chief-says-government-ties-to-gm-played-no-role-in-delay-chevy/|title= Auto safety chief denies sitting on Chevy Volt warnings in heated hearing|work=[[Fox News]]|date=2012-06-25|accessdate=2012-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203718504577182853550398244|title=GM Boosts Volt Defense as Sales Falter |last=Terlep |first=Sharon |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=2012-06-26|accessdate=2012-01-26}}</ref>

== Reception ==
=== Awards and recognition ===
The Volt has received awards from multiple organizations:

