=== Spark EV === {{Infobox electric vehicle | name = Chevrolet Spark EV | image = File:2013-03-05 Geneva Motor Show 7862.JPG | manufacturer = [[General Motors]] | production = 2013–2016 | body_style = 5-door [[hatchback]] | motor = {{convert|130|bhp|kW|0|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=CSEVspecs>{{cite web |url=http://www.chevrolet.com/spark-ev-electric-vehicle/specs/dimensions.html |title=2014 Spark EV Models & Specs |publisher=[[Chevrolet]] |accessdate=June 20, 2013}}</ref> | battery = {{unbulleted list | (MY 2015+) 19 [[kWh]] [[lithium-ion battery]] by LG Chem<ref name="GM Shifts 2015 Chevy Spark EV Battery Manufacturing To In-House Facility">{{cite news |url=http://insideevs.com/gm-shifts-2015-chevy-spark-ev-battery-manufacturing-house-facility/ |title=GM Shifts 2015 Chevy Spark EV Battery Manufacturing To In-House Facility |first=Eric |last=Loveday |website=Inside EV's |date=May 14, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2015}}</ref> | MY 2014: 21.3 [[kWh]] [[Lithium iron phosphate]] by A123, claimed as nano-phosphate Li-ion battery<ref name=CR062013/>
}} | wheelbase = {{Convert|93.5|in|mm|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=CSEVspecs/> | length = {{Convert|146.5|in|mm|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=CSEVspecs/> | width = {{Convert|64.0|in|mm|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=CSEVspecs/> | weight = {{Convert|2989|lb|kg|abbr=on|0|order=flip}}<ref name=CSEVspecs/> | electric_range = {{convert|82|mi|abbr=in|0|order=flip}} ([[EPA]])<ref name=EPA_EV>{{cite web |url=http://insideevs.com/2014-chevy-spark-ev-gets-epa-range-rating-of-82-miles-119-mpge-combined/ |title=2014 Chevy Spark EV Gets EPA Range Rating of 82 Miles; 119 MPGe Combined |author=Eric Loveday |publisher=Inside EVs |date=April 24, 2013 |accessdate=April 25, 2013}}</ref> | sp = us | predecessor = [[General Motors EV1]] | successor = [[Chevrolet Bolt]] }}
The '''Spark EV''' was a limited production 5-door hatchback [[battery electric vehicle]] produced by Chevrolet in 2013–2016.
In October 2011, General Motors announced the planned production of the '''Chevrolet Spark EV''', an [[electric car|all-electric]] version of the third-generation Chevrolet Spark, with availability limited to select markets. The production version was unveiled at the November 2012 [[Los Angeles Auto Show#2012|Los Angeles Auto Show]].<ref name=NYT112812>{{cite news |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/28/2014-chevrolet-spark-ev-worth-the-extra-charge/?ref=automobiles |title=2014 Chevrolet Spark EV: Worth the Extra Charge? |author=Jerry Garrett |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 28, 2012 |accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref>
Within the framework of GM's vehicle electrification strategy,<ref name=VDI>{{cite web |title=Vehicle Electrification – Quo Vadis |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233987248_Vehicle_Electrification_-_Quo_Vadis__Fahrzeugelektrifizierung_-_Quo_Vadis |last1=Brinkman |first1=Norman |first2=Ulrich |last2=Eberle |first3=Volker |last3=Formanski |first4=Uwe-Dieter |last4=Grebe |first5=Roland |last5=Matthe |publisher=[[Verein Deutscher Ingenieure|VDI]] |date=April 15, 2012 |accessdate=April 27, 2013}}</ref> the Spark EV was the first all-electric passenger car marketed by General Motors in the U.S. since the [[GM EV1|EV1]], which was discontinued in 1999.<ref name=NYT101211/> The Spark EV was released in the U.S. in selected markets in California and Oregon in June 2013.<ref name=EVreleased>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1084889_first-2014-chevrolet-spark-evs-now-at-ca-oregon-dealers |title=First 2014 Chevrolet Spark EVs Now at CA, Oregon Dealers |author=John Voelcker |publisher=Green Car Reports |date=June 20, 2013 |accessdate=June 20, 2013}}</ref> The electric car went on sale in [[Maryland]] in the second quarter of 2015, the first [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] state where the Spark EV was available.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1096434_2015-chevrolet-spark-ev-to-go-on-sale-in-maryland-this-spring |title=2015 Chevrolet Spark EV To Go on Sale in Maryland This Spring |author=John Voelcker |work=Green Car Reports |date=January 22, 2015 |accessdate=January 22, 2015}}</ref> {{As of|2014|12}}, U.S. sales totaled 1,684 units.<ref name=Sales2014US>{{cite news |url=http://www.hybridcars.com/december-2014-dashboard/ |title=December 2014 Dashboard |author=Jeff Cobb |work=HybridCars.com and Baum & Associates |date=January 6, 2015 |accessdate=January 22, 2015}} ''See section "December 2014 Battery Electric Car Sales Numbers" ''</ref> The Spark EV was discontinued in December 2016, when Chevrolet began selling the [[Chevrolet Bolt|Bolt]], which had a much longer range.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2017/01/31/chevy-axes-spark-ev-favor-bolt-ev/97283876/|title=Chevy axes Spark EV in favor of Bolt EV|publisher=}}</ref>{{update after|2020|2|28}}<!-- do we have any sources which tell the total number of Spark EVs that GM made in their limited production effort with the Spark? -->
In October 2012, GM Korea announced it would start making and selling the Spark EV in Korea in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last=Szostech |first=Michael |url=http://www.myelectriccarforums.com/chevy-spark-ev-will-sell-in-south-korea-in-2013-us-later/ |title=Chevy Spark EV will sell in South Korea in 2013, US later |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref> Retail sales began in South Korea in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insideevs.com/sales-of-chevy-spark-ev-now-officially-underway-in-south-korea/ |title=Sales of Chevy Spark EV Now Officially Underway in South Korea |author=Mark Kane |publisher=InsideEVs.com |date=October 30, 2013 |accessdate=October 30, 2013}}</ref> GM also announced plans to sell the Spark EV in limited quantities in Canada and select European markets.<ref name=GCC112712>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/11/sparkev-20121127.html |title=Chevrolet Spark EV priced below $25,000 with tax incentives; Oregon and Canada added to markets |publisher=Green Car Congress |date=November 27, 2012 |accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chevy Spark EV will be sold in Europe Too |url=http://www.myelectriccarforums.com/chevy-spark-ev-will-be-sold-in-europe-too/ |publisher=My Electric Car Forums |accessdate=February 14, 2013 |author=Mike Szostech}}</ref> It was available in Canada for limited fleet sales.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mohit |first1=Surdas |title=Chevy Spark EV Priced at $29,995 in Canada; GM Confirms Public Sales Will Start in 2014 UPDATE: Will Continue To Be Fleet Only |url=http://insideevs.com/chevy-spark-ev-priced-at-29995-in-canada-gm-confirms-public-sales-will-start-in-2014-no-longer-to-be-fleet-only/ |publisher=insideevs.com |accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref>
The electric car was initially powered by a 21.3 [[kWh]] [[Lithium iron phosphate]] battery pack supplied by [[A123 Systems]].<ref name=NYT101211>{{cite news |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/12/chevrolet-to-sell-purely-electric-spark-hatchback-in-u-s/?ref=automobiles |title=Chevrolet to Sell Purely Electric Spark Hatchback in U.S. |author=Jonathan Schultz |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 12, 2011 |accessdate=October 12, 2011}}</ref><ref name=GCC101211>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2011/10/spark-20111012.html |title=Chevrolet to produce Spark battery electric vehicle for US and global markets starting in 2013 with A123 Systems pack; EN-V gets a Chevrolet badge |publisher=[[Green Car Congress]] |date=October 12, 2011 |accessdate=October 12, 2011}}</ref> In a white-paper,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.neces.com/assets/A123-Systems_Nanophosphate-overview-whitepaper_FINAL1.pdf |title=Nanophosphate®Basics: An Overview of the Structure, Properties and Benefits of A123 Systems’ Proprietary Lithium Ion Battery Technology |publisher=A123 Systems |location=US |access-date=August 10, 2017}}</ref> The 2014 production version featured a {{convert|130|hp|kW|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} motor, providing {{convert|400|lbft|Nm|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} of torque.<ref name=CR062013>{{cite news |url=http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2013/06/first-drive-electrifying-the-chevrolet-spark.html |title=First drive: The Chevrolet Spark EV shocks us |author=Gabe Shenhar |work=[[Consumer Reports]] |date=June 20, 2013 |accessdate=June 20, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624130055/http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2013/06/first-drive-electrifying-the-chevrolet-spark.html |archive-date=June 24, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1080487_2014-chevy-spark-ev-prototype-electric-car-first-drive |title=2014 Chevy Spark EV Prototype Electric Car: First Drive |author=General Motors |publisher=Green Car Reports |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=November 15, 2012}}</ref> The Spark EV can be fast-charged to 80% of capacity in 20 minutes using an optional [[Combined Charging System|CCS/SAE Combo Type 1]] connector, and charging time increases to about seven hours using a dedicated 240-volt charging station or about 17 hours using a standard household 120-volt outlet.{{cn|date=February 2020}}
In 2014, for the 2015 model year, the battery pack supplier was changed to LG Chem<ref name="GM Shifts 2015 Chevy Spark EV Battery Manufacturing To In-House Facility" /> which resulted in a smaller capacity pack (19&nbsp;kWh) while maintaining the same EV range. The drive ratio was also changed from 3.17 to 3.87 as well, with a new motor with torque reduced to {{convert|327|ftlb|Nm|abbr=on|0|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://insideevs.com/2015-chevy-spark-ev-highlighting-changes/ |title=2015 Chevy Spark EV – Highlighting The Changes |first=Eric |last=Loveday |website=Inside EV |date=May 15, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2015}}</ref>
