=== Marketing ===
;Africa
The Chevrolet Cruze was launched in the Egyptian market during mid-2009.<ref>{{cite web |date=June 5, 2009 |url=http://www.thedailynewsegypt.com/article.aspx?ArticleID=22212 |title=The Launch of the New Chevrolet Cruze in the Egyptian Market |work=[[Daily News Egypt]] |publisher=Egyptian Media Services |accessdate=September 19, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> South African sales of the Cruze commenced in September 2009.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 23, 2009 |url=http://www.motoring.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=5174913&fSectionId=751&fSetId=381 |title=There's Tom and Penny – now meet Chevy Cruze |publisher=Motoring & Independent Online |accessdate=October 4, 2009}}</ref>

;Asia
[[File:Daewoo Lacetti Premiere CDX sedan 01.jpg|thumbnail|right|Daewoo Lacetti Premiere CDX sedan (Vietnam)]]
South Korean-market versions of the Cruze entered production there in 2008 as the "Daewoo Lacetti Premiere".<ref name = "2011 Chevrolet Cruze First Drive"/> The Lacetti debuted on October 30, 2008, featuring the 1.6-liter [[naturally aspirated engine]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Hyun-cheol |first=Kim |date=October 29, 2008 |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/10/123_33479.html |title=Small Is Beautiful in Lean Times |work=[[The Korea Times]] |accessdate=May 23, 2009}}</ref> On January 30, 2009, GM Daewoo introduced the turbodiesel engine variant.<ref>{{cite web |date=January 30, 2009 |url=http://media.gmdaewoo.co.kr/content/media/kr/en/news/news_detail.brand_gmdaewoo.html/content/Pages/news/kr/en/2009/20090130 |title=GM Daewoo Launches Lacetti Premiere Diesel Sedan |publisher=[[General Motors]] |accessdate=February 28, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Inline with the February 2011 renaming of "GM Daewoo" to "GM Korea", the Lacetti Premiere adopted the international "Chevrolet Cruze" name from March 2, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Courtenay |first=Vince |date=January 20, 2011 |url=http://wardsauto.com/ar/daewoo_brand_company_110120/ |title=Daewoo Bowing Out as Brand, Company Name in Korea |work=[[Ward's|WardsAuto]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926235621/http://wardsauto.com/ar/daewoo_brand_company_110120/ |archivedate=September 26, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Seo |first1=Sookyung |last2=Trudell |first2=Craig |date=January 20, 2011 |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-01-20/gm-drops-daewoo-brand-for-chevrolet-in-south-korea.html |title=GM Drops Daewoo Brand for Chevrolet in South Korea |work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123112805/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-01-20/gm-drops-daewoo-brand-for-chevrolet-in-south-korea.html |archivedate=January 23, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> For the owners of the previous model, Lacetti, GM Korea decided to replace the old emblem to that of Chevrolet for free.<ref>{{cite web |date=January 24, 2011 |url=http://star.mk.co.kr/new/view.php?mc=ST&no=52441&year=2011 |title=Chevrolet offers free replacement of the emblem for Lacetti owerners |publisher=[[Maeil Kyungje]] |accessdate=April 11, 2012}}</ref>

The Chevrolet Cruze was launched in the Chinese market on April 18, 2009 as a sedan<ref>{{cite web |last=Gao |first=George |url=http://autonews.gasgoo.com/auto-news/1009802/Chevrolet-Cruze-to-hit-China-market-on-Apr-18.html |title=Chevrolet Cruze to hit China market on Apr. 18 – China automotive news |publisher=Gasgoo |date=March 30, 2009 |accessdate=June 6, 2009}}</ref> manufactured at GM India's [[Halol]] factory.<ref name="Gurgaon"/> Transmission choices were a five-speed manual or a six-speed automatic along with 1.6- or 1.8-liter engines. The sedan range consisted of the 1.6 SL, 1.6 SE, 1.8 SE (automatic only) and 1.8 SX (automatic only). Hatchback models were introduced in 2013 available with the 1.6-liter or 1.6-liter turbo engines.

The Chevrolet Cruze was released in India on October 12, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 24, 2009 |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/gm-india-expects-50-growth-in-2010/74285/on |title=GM India expects 50% growth in 2010 |work=Business Standard |accessdate=October 7, 2009}}</ref> It was offered in only two versions: LT and LTZ in diesel form only (''VCDi'').<ref>{{cite web |date=October 12, 2009 |url=http://www.motorbeam.com/cars/chevrolet-cruze-cars/gm-india-launches-chevrolet-cruze/ |title=GM India Launches Chevrolet Cruze |publisher=MotorBeam |accessdate=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213172300/http://www.motorbeam.com/cars/chevrolet-cruze-cars/gm-india-launches-chevrolet-cruze/ |archive-date=December 13, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

During 2009, there were reports that the Cruze was to become available in [[Malaysia]] with the 1.6 and a 1.8-liter engines.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chong |first=Elizabeth |date=May 11, 2009 |url=http://biz.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2009/5/11/business/3818839&sec=business |title=Cruze-ing along Targeted sales of 600 units of Chevrolet's new model |work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |publisher=Star Publications |accessdate=May 20, 2009}}</ref> The [[Naza]] automotive group in Malaysia has announced that it's expecting to launch the Cruze in the Malaysian market for the first time in the second quarter of 2010 and they are expecting to sell 1,200 to 1,500 units in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kouider |first=Hossine |date=April 6, 2010 |url=http://biz.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2010/3/5/business/5796678&sec=business |title=Naza to sell Chevrolets |work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |publisher=Star Publications |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref>

In Thailand, the car launch in December 2010, built at GM's Rayong facility. Specification levels comprised: Base (1.6-liter), LS (1.6- and 1.8-liter), LT and LTZ (1.8-liter), 6-speed automatic are standard in all models except 1.6 Base used 5-speed manual, with an optional 2.0-liter ''VCDi'' available on LTZ variant with 6-speed automatic.

;{{not a typo|Australia}}
{{Multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width =
