The '''Chevrolet Trailblazer''' is a [[Subcompact car|subcompact]] [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover]] slotted between the [[Chevrolet Trax|Trax]] and the larger [[Chevrolet Equinox|Equinox]] sold in China. It will make its debut in North America in 2020 as a 2021 model.

== Overview ==
The Trailblazer was launched on 16 April 2019 at the 18th [[Auto Shanghai|Shanghai International Automobile Industry Exhibition]] alongside the [[Chevrolet Tracker (China)|Tracker]], that both replace the outgoing Trax. It is a compact crossover that will be aimed for developed markets while the subcompact Tracker will be aimed for emerging markets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carscoops.com/2019/04/new-chevy-tracker-and-trailblazer-revealed-in-sporty-redline-trim-in-china/|title=New Chevy Tracker And Trailblazer Revealed In Sporty Redline Trim In China|date=April 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1122401_2020-chevrolet-trailblazer-debuts-at-2019-shanghai-auto-show|title=2020 Chevrolet Trailblazer debuts at 2019 Shanghai auto show|website=Motor Authority}}</ref> Developed by [[GM Korea]], the Trailblazer will be assembled in [[Incheon]], [[South Korea]].

The Trailblazer made its North American debut at the [[Los Angeles Auto Show]] in November 2019, and will be sold in the United States starting in early 2020 as a 2021 [[model year]] vehicle. Chevrolet announced that the MSRP will be priced below $20,000(USD). There will be five trim levels: L, LS, LT, ACTIV and RS. The latter two will come standard with dual exhaust and top of the line features.<ref>[http://gmauthority.com/blog/2019/11/2021-chevrolet-trailblazer-makes-u-s-debut-will-start-at-under-20000/ "2021 Chevrolet Trailblazer Priced at Under $20k"] from GM Authority (November 21, 2019)</ref> The ACTIV and RS will also feature a two-tone roof.<ref name="carlitus">{{cite web|url=https://www.carlitus.net/2020-chevy-trailblazer/|website=carlitus.net|title=2020 Chevy Trailblazer Ready for Its Comeback in the U.S.|accessdate=2019-09-07}}</ref>

Unlike the mid-size Trailblazer that was manufactured between 2002 and 2009, as well as the international market Trailblazer that is based on the Colorado pickup, this version of the Trailblazer will be slotted above the Trax, and below the Equinox. It features similar styling to the 2019 [[Chevrolet Blazer (crossover)|Blazer]], but in a smaller package.<ref name="autoblog">{{cite web|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2019/05/29/2021-chevy-trailblazer-revealed-blazer-little-brother/|website=autoblog.com|title=2021 Chevy Trailblazer is revealed as the Blazer's little sibling|accessdate=2019-09-07}}</ref>

On January 16, 2020, the Trailblazer was launched in [[South Korea]]. The Korean-market model is larger in dimension than Trailblazers sold in other markets, with a length of 4,425mm and width of 1,810mm.<ref name="www.chevrolet.co.kr">{{cite web|url=https://www.chevrolet.co.kr/rv/trailblazer-specification.gm|title=쉐보레 트레일블레이저 제원 안내/쉐보레 Chevrolet |accessdate=2020-01-16}}</ref>
